

// Database reverted to the original, uncompromised core list + B68 Additions
export const database = [  // --- CORE RULES & PLAYBOOKS ---
  { id:"action-attune-core", title:"Attune", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Resolve", tags:"ghost field, arcane, spectrology, spirits", preview:"Open your mind to the ghost field or other arcane power.", content:"Attune is how you interact with the supernatural world of Doskvol — ghosts, demons, arcane energies, and the ever-present ghost field that saturates the city. You use it to communicate with spirits, perceive beyond normal senses, or channel electroplasmic power. On a 6, you connect cleanly; on a 4/5, you get what you need but with a cost — perhaps the entity pushes back or you attract unwanted attention; on a 1-3, something goes wrong, and the ghost field pushes back hard. Example: Your Whisper reaches out to question a ghost lingering near the murder scene — Attune lets them make contact, but a 4/5 means the spirit is hostile and demands something in return." },
  { id:"action-command-core", title:"Command", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Resolve", tags:"intimidate, threaten, lead, obedience", preview:"Compel swift obedience through authority or menace.", content:"Command is raw authority — you make someone do what you want through force of will, threat, or sheer presence. It's what you roll when you bark orders at your own gang, intimidate a mark into backing down, or coerce a prisoner into talking. On a 6, they comply; on a 4/5, they obey but with hesitation, resentment, or a complication; on a 1-3, they defy you or the situation escalates. Example: Your Cutter stares down a rival gang blocking the alley — a 6 and they step aside, but a 1-3 means they call your bluff and things get violent." },
  { id:"action-consort-core", title:"Consort", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Resolve", tags:"socialize, friends, contacts, manipulate", preview:"Socialize with friends and contacts to open doors.", content:"Consort is about working your social network — schmoozing, making connections, calling in favors, and winning people over through charm, shared interests, or mutual benefit. It's the action for building relationships, getting introductions, or finding out what the underworld is buzzing about this week. On a 6, the contact comes through cleanly; on a 4/5, they help but want something in return or attach strings; on a 1-3, they can't help, or helping them creates a new problem. Example: Your Slide needs an invitation to the Lord's gala — Consort with a well-placed acquaintance gets you in, but a 4/5 means they want an embarrassing favor before they'll make the call." },
  { id:"action-finesse-core", title:"Finesse", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Prowess", tags:"graceful, subtle, dextrous, manipulate", preview:"Employ dextrous manipulation or subtle misdirection.", content:"Finesse covers delicate physical skill — pickpocketing, sleight of hand, precise knife work, controlling a vehicle through a tight space, or dueling with an elegant fighting style. It's the action for when accuracy and grace matter more than brute strength. On a 6, you execute cleanly; on a 4/5, you succeed but lose something (the wallet but not the watch, or the duelist scores a graze) or create a complication; on a 1-3, your technique fails you at the worst moment. Example: Your Lurk tries to lift the guard captain's key ring while distracting him — a 6 means it's gone before he notices, a 1-3 means you fumble and he grabs your wrist." },
  { id:"action-hunt-core", title:"Hunt", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Insight", tags:"track, ambush, shoot, precision", preview:"Track, stalk, and eliminate a target with precision.", content:"Hunt is the action of the patient predator — tracking someone through the city, setting up a long-range shot, arranging an ambush, or maintaining surveillance on a mark. It's methodical and precise rather than reactive. On a 6, you find your target or land your shot cleanly; on a 4/5, you succeed but tip them off, create noise, or get a worse angle than you wanted; on a 1-3, your quarry slips away or you're spotted first. Example: Your Hound is perched above the docks waiting for the informant — a 6 drops him clean, but a 4/5 might mean the shot connects but a witness saw the muzzle flash." },
  { id:"action-prowl-core", title:"Prowl", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Prowess", tags:"stealth, sneak, traverse, ambush", preview:"Move through danger unseen and unheard.", content:"Prowl is your ability to move through the world without being noticed — sneaking past guards, scaling a building in the dark, slipping through a crowded room without being remembered, or attacking from concealment. It's about controlling space and presence. On a 6, you move like a ghost; on a 4/5, you get through but leave a trace or hear someone getting close; on a 1-3, you're spotted, you make noise, or your route is blocked. Example: Your Lurk is belly-crawling under the window of the watch house — a 4/5 gets them past, but the guard pauses and squints into the dark." },
  { id:"action-skirmish-core", title:"Skirmish", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Prowess", tags:"combat, brawl, wrestle, melee", preview:"Engage enemies in the chaos of close-quarters combat.", content:"Skirmish is fighting in the thick of it — brawling, knife-fighting, wrestling, charging into a melee, or holding a position against multiple attackers. This is the action for chaotic, up-close violence where survival depends on aggression and toughness as much as skill. On a 6, you prevail and deal harm without taking much yourself; on a 4/5, you achieve your goal but take harm or end up in a worse position; on a 1-3, you're getting badly hurt or the fight is turning against you. Example: Your Cutter charges the two guards blocking the door — a 4/5 means you put them down but catch a blade across the ribs in the process." },
  { id:"action-study-core", title:"Study", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Insight", tags:"research, analyze, investigate, scrutinize", preview:"Scrutinize details and interpret evidence to uncover truth.", content:"Study is careful, focused analysis — reading documents, researching a topic, examining a crime scene for clues, or watching someone closely enough to detect deception or hidden emotion. It's slower and more deliberate than Survey. On a 6, you learn exactly what you need; on a 4/5, you get useful information but it's incomplete or comes with a confusing detail; on a 1-3, you misread the evidence or the research takes too long. Example: Your Spider reviews the ledger stolen from the docks — a 6 reveals the embezzlement scheme clearly, while a 4/5 shows something is wrong but the key entries are in a cipher you'll need time to crack." },
  { id:"action-survey-core", title:"Survey", source:"BitD Core", page:"58", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Insight", tags:"observe, anticipate, spot, uncover", preview:"Read a situation quickly and anticipate what's coming.", content:"Survey is fast, situational awareness — scanning a room for threats, reading the mood of a crowd, spotting the hidden guard before he spots you, or getting a quick read on how a negotiation is likely to go. Where Study is deep analysis, Survey is rapid pattern recognition. On a 6, you get a clear accurate read; on a 4/5, you notice something important but miss something else; on a 1-3, you misread the situation or don't notice a critical detail until it's too late. Example: Your Hound scans the meet before the crew enters — a 6 spots the two extra muscle hiding in the back, a 1-3 means you don't see them until they step out." },
  { id:"action-sway-core", title:"Sway", source:"BitD Core", page:"59", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Resolve", tags:"influence, charm, argue, persuade", preview:"Influence someone through guile, charm, or compelling argument.", content:"Sway is manipulation and persuasion — lying convincingly, seducing someone, constructing an argument they can't easily dismiss, or playing on someone's fears and desires to get what you want. Unlike Command, which relies on authority or intimidation, Sway works through cunning and appeal. On a 6, they're convinced or compliant; on a 4/5, they're partially persuaded but want more, or they comply with conditions attached; on a 1-3, they see through you or the attempt backfires. Example: Your Slide tries to talk the Bluecoat inspector into ignoring the lockpicks — a 6 and he waves you through, a 4/5 and he lets you go but pockets the lockpicks as 'evidence.'" },
  { id:"action-tinker-core", title:"Tinker", source:"BitD Core", page:"59", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Insight", tags:"fiddle, devices, mechanisms, gadget", preview:"Apply technical know-how to devices, locks, and mechanisms.", content:"Tinker covers all things mechanical and technical — picking locks, cracking safes, building or modifying gadgets, disabling alarms and traps, treating wounds, or leveraging the city's clockwork and electroplasmic infrastructure. It's the action of the clever hands-on problem-solver. On a 6, the mechanism yields to your expertise; on a 4/5, you get it done but with a complication (takes longer, makes noise, or you use up a resource); on a 1-3, something breaks, triggers, or backfires. Example: Your Leech tries to disarm the electroplasmic alarm on the vault door — a 4/5 cuts the circuit but the system logs the interruption, so security will notice it in their next check." },
  { id:"action-wreck-core", title:"Wreck", source:"BitD Core", page:"59", category:"Player", subcategory:"Actions", "sub-subcategory":"Prowess", tags:"smash, savage, force, sabotage", preview:"Destroy, break through, or create chaos with savage force.", content:"Wreck is about applying overwhelming physical force or explosive power — smashing through a door, bringing down a wall with a charge, sabotaging machinery, or using sheer destructive energy to overcome an obstacle. It's loud, it's messy, and it gets results when subtlety has failed. On a 6, you get through or destroy your target cleanly; on a 4/5, you succeed but create collateral damage, noise, or heat; on a 1-3, the thing you're trying to break fights back, or the destruction gets out of control. Example: Your Leech plants an explosive charge on the bridge support — a 6 drops it cleanly on schedule, a 4/5 means the blast is bigger than planned and sets fire to the nearby warehouse." },
  { id:"playbook-cutter-core", title:"Cutter", source:"BitD Core", page:"61", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"cutter, fighter, dangerous, intimidating, skirmish, violence, muscle, enforcer, core", preview:"A dangerous fighter and enforcer who solves problems with violence.", content:"The Cutter is the crew's physical threat — the enforcer, the leg-breaker, the duelist who ends arguments with a blade. They excel at Skirmish and Command, making them lethal in a fight and terrifying in a standoff. Their special abilities let them weather punishment that would drop anyone else, command gangs with iron authority, or project an aura of violence that makes enemies reconsider their choices before a single punch is thrown. Play a Cutter when you want to be the one the crew calls when things need to get brutal, fast." },
  { id:"playbook-hound-core", title:"Hound", source:"BitD Core", page:"65", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"hound, sharpshooter, tracker, deadly, hunt, long-range, precision, core", preview:"A deadly sharpshooter and patient tracker.", content:"The Hound is the crew's precision hunter — patient, methodical, and lethal at range. They specialize in Hunt and Survey, making them exceptional at tracking marks, setting up ambushes, and gathering intelligence before a score. Their abilities let them shoot with uncanny accuracy, read people and situations with unsettling clarity, or bond with a trained animal companion. Play a Hound when you want to work from the shadows, gather information, and ensure the crew never walks into a fight blind — or when you want to end it before it starts." },
  { id:"playbook-leech-core", title:"Leech", source:"BitD Core", page:"69", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"saboteur, technician, alchemy, tinkerer", preview:"A technical genius who builds, breaks, and poisons with equal skill.", content:"The Leech is the crew's mad inventor and chemical expert — they brew the drugs, forge the bombs, build the gadgets, patch the wounds, and understand exactly how to break whatever the city is made of. They specialize in Tinker and Wreck, and their abilities let them craft specialized alchemical concoctions, jury-rig solutions on the fly, or push their expertise to solve problems no one else even knows are problems yet. Play a Leech when you want to be the reason the crew always has exactly the right tool for exactly the wrong situation." },
  { id:"playbook-lurk-core", title:"Lurk", source:"BitD Core", page:"73", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"stealth, infiltrator, burglar, assassin", preview:"A ghost in the dark — infiltrator, burglar, and shadow assassin.", content:"The Lurk is the crew's master of stealth and infiltration. Where others knock on the front door, the Lurk is already inside. They specialize in Prowl and Finesse, and their abilities let them move through supernatural darkness, slip past wards and sensors, or strike from hiding with devastating effect. The Lurk earns xp when they address challenges with stealth or evasion, rewarding the player who thinks in three dimensions and treats every wall as a potential door. Play a Lurk when you want to go places you're not supposed to be — and leave no trace you were ever there." },
  { id:"playbook-slide-core", title:"Slide", source:"BitD Core", page:"77", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"manipulator, spy, deception, influence", preview:"A silver-tongued manipulator who moves through high and low society.", content:"The Slide is the crew's face, fixer, and social predator — the one who walks into any room and leaves with exactly what they wanted, and somehow everyone thinks it was their idea. They specialize in Consort and Sway, and their abilities let them maintain multiple cover identities, resist the social consequences of their schemes, or read a mark well enough to exploit their every weakness. The Slide earns xp when they address challenges with deception or influence. Play a Slide when you want to win without a fight — or when you want to make sure any fight that does happen is on entirely your terms." },
  { id:"playbook-spider-core", title:"Spider", source:"BitD Core", page:"81", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"mastermind, conspiracy, calculation, network", preview:"A calculating mastermind who weaves webs of influence and information.", content:"The Spider is the crew's strategist and information broker — they see five moves ahead, maintain a network of contacts and leverage, and turn the chaos of the Doskvolian underworld into an advantage. They specialize in Study and Consort, and their abilities let them anticipate threats, manipulate faction politics, or extract resources from relationships through sheer calculated pressure. The Spider earns xp when they address challenges with calculation or conspiracy. Play a Spider when you want to be the brain of the operation — the one whose plans account for every contingency, except the ones that make the game interesting." },
  { id:"playbook-whisper-core", title:"Whisper", source:"BitD Core", page:"85", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"arcane, channeler, ghost, adept", preview:"An arcane adept who traffics with ghosts and forbidden powers.", content:"The Whisper is the crew's supernatural specialist — they Attune to the ghost field, bind spirits into service, perform arcane rituals, and understand the invisible architecture of horror that underlies Doskvol. Their abilities let them channel ghost energies through their own body, maintain a stable of bound spirit servants, or reach into the ghost field to gather intelligence no mundane investigation could uncover. The Whisper earns xp when they address challenges with knowledge or arcane power. Play a Whisper when you want the game to lean into its weird, dark-fantasy setting — and when you're willing to pay the price for staring too long into the void." },
  { id:"item-blade-core", title:"A Blade or Two", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"melee, knife, sword, rapier", preview:"A personal melee weapon suited to your fighting style.", content:"This item represents any close-quarters weapon that fits your character's approach — a fighting knife worn in the boot, a pair of curved swords for a more aggressive style, a rapier and stiletto for dueling, or a heavy cleaver for brutality. The fiction of how you carry and use it matters: a duelist with a rapier fights very differently from a street brawler with a butcher's blade, even if both are using their Skirmish rating. The specific weapon shapes how the GM frames consequences and what approaches feel natural." },
  { id:"item-throwing-knives-core", title:"Throwing Knives", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"ranged, light, thrown, finesse, hunt, melee-range, load-0, item", preview:"Six small blades for ranged attacks or quick close work.", content:"A set of six small, balanced throwing blades — light enough to carry in a wrist sheath or jacket lining, and useful both as ranged weapons and as close backup. They're less powerful than a pistol but completely silent and can be deployed without the tell-tale smoke and sound of a firearm. A useful tool for anyone who needs a ranged option without drawing attention, at the cost of a limited supply that runs out fast in a real fight." },
  { id:"item-pistol-core", title:"A Pistol", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"ranged, firearm, slow-reload, hunt, skirmish, load-1, item, handgun", preview:"A heavy single-shot firearm — devastating, but slow to reload.", content:"A heavy, single-shot, breech-loading pistol — the kind that stops a fight immediately when it goes off. At close range it's devastating, capable of putting down almost any human target with one shot. The critical limitation is reload time: once you've fired, you're carrying an expensive club until you can reload, which takes real time and attention. In a firefight, that one shot has to count. The sound and the smoke also mean that anyone nearby knows exactly what just happened." },
  { id:"item-large-weapon-core", title:"A Large Weapon", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"melee, heavy, rifle, blunderbuss", preview:"A two-handed weapon built for serious damage or longer range.", content:"This covers any weapon that requires two hands and serious commitment — a battle-axe or greatsword for devastating melee power, a pole-arm for reach and control, a hunting rifle for precision at distance, or a blunderbuss for terrifying close-range impact. These weapons hit hard and carry weight at the table: a character with a blunderbuss in hand reads the situation very differently than one with a knife. The tradeoff is encumbrance and visibility — you can't exactly conceal a warhammer." },
  { id:"item-unusual-weapon-core", title:"An Unusual Weapon", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"melee, curious, whip, flail", preview:"An improvised or exotic weapon that catches enemies off guard.", content:"Not all weapons fit neatly into the sword-or-pistol categories. This covers whips for range and disarming, flails for unpredictable striking angles, hatchets that can be thrown or swung, lengths of chain, razor-edged fans, or purpose-built tools repurposed for violence. These weapons often provide narrative advantages — a whip can grab objects or trip opponents, a steel-toed boot passes every weapons check — at the cost of being less conventionally lethal than a blade or gun." },
  { id:"item-armor-core", title:"Armor", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"defense, leather, load-2, item, protection, resist, harm-reduction", preview:"Leather armor that absorbs one instance of physical harm.", content:"A set of heavy leather armor — reinforced tunic, gloves, and boots — that provides meaningful protection without completely restricting movement. Mechanically, when you check off your armor box, you negate or reduce one instance of physical harm from a consequence. You only have the one box, so choosing when to use it matters. It won't stop everything, and once it's checked you're unprotected for the rest of the score unless you also have Heavy Armor." },
  { id:"item-heavy-armor-core", title:"+Heavy Armor", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"defense, chain-mail, plate, load-3, item, protection, restricted, military", preview:"Chain and plate added over your leather — a second armor box.", content:"Heavy Armor is an upgrade taken alongside standard Armor — it represents adding chain mail, metal plates, and a helm on top of the leather base. Mechanically it gives you a second armor box, meaning you can absorb two instances of harm before you're unprotected. The obvious tradeoff is load: heavy armor weighs a lot, which cuts into what else you can carry on a score. It also makes you more obvious and less mobile — not ideal for a job that calls for discretion." },
  { id:"item-burglary-gear-core", title:"Burglary Gear", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"burglary, lockpicks, pry-bar, tools, finesse, tinker, load-1, item", preview:"The complete toolkit for bypassing locks and physical security.", content:"A professional burglar's kit: lockpicks in graduated sizes, a small pry-bar for stubborn doors and window frames, vials of silencing oil for squeaky hinges, wire and hooks for fishing keys through letter slots, and fine sand for checking floor pressure plates. This gear doesn't replace a good Tinker roll, but it provides the tools that make those rolls possible — and in the fiction, having the right tool can shift position from desperate to risky or effect from limited to standard." },
  { id:"item-climbing-gear-core", title:"Climbing Gear", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"climbing, rope, grappling-hook, harness, prowl, load-1, item, traverse", preview:"Rope, hooks, and harness for vertical access to any building.", content:"A full climbing kit: a large coil of rope, a smaller coil for secondary lines, multiple grappling hooks, chalk dust for grip, a proper climbing harness with carabiners, and iron pitons with a mallet for securing anchors. In Doskvol's vertical cityscape of towers, bridges, and rooftops, climbing is often the fastest way in — or the only way out. Having this gear means the Prowl roll to scale the building is possible in the first place; without it, the GM might call it impossible or desperate." },
  { id:"item-arcane-implements-core", title:"Arcane Implements", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"arcane, quicksilver, black-salt, spirit-bottle, attune, ritual, load-1, item", preview:"Vials and tools for working with ghosts and arcane energies.", content:"The working materials of arcane practice: a vial of quicksilver (conductive to ghost energies), a pouch of black salt (used to ward or bind spirits), a spirit anchor stone (keeps a ghost tethered to a location), a spirit bottle (for capturing entities), and a vial of electroplasm designed to shatter on impact. These implements support Attune rolls and ritual work, providing the physical components that give arcane actions their grounding in the fiction — a Whisper without their implements is improvising, which usually means worse position and effect." },
  { id:"item-documents-core", title:"Documents", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"documents, books, maps, ink, study, consort, load-1, item, investigation", preview:"Reference books, blank papers, and writing supplies for research and forgery.", content:"A small library of useful reference material — a registry of the nobility and their households, a directory of City Watch commanders, a list of notable citizens and their affiliations — plus blank pages, a pen, and a vial of ink for on-the-spot forgery, and a collection of maps both current and historical. These documents support Study rolls and reduce the need for risky information-gathering: knowing who owns a building before you break into it is always better than finding out afterwards. The blank papers and ink are the seed of any forgery operation." },
  { id:"item-subterfuge-supplies-core", title:"Subterfuge Supplies", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"subterfuge, make-up, forgery, disguise, sway, finesse, load-1, item, deception", preview:"A disguise kit and forgery tools for becoming someone else.", content:"The toolkit of the professional deceiver: a theatrical make-up kit capable of significant appearance changes, blank official documents ready for a forger's touch, costume jewelry for dressing up or dressing down, a reversible cloak that changes your silhouette entirely, and a forged badge of office that will pass casual scrutiny. This gear supports Sway and Finesse rolls in social situations, shifting the position when you need to pass as someone you're not — the difference between being questioned at the gate and being waved through." },
  { id:"item-demolition-tools-core", title:"Demolition Tools", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"demolition, sledgehammer, drill, crowbar, wreck, load-2, item, destruction", preview:"Heavy tools for breaking through walls, doors, and obstacles.", content:"The blunt instruments of forced entry and structural sabotage: a sledgehammer for doors and masonry, iron spikes for jamming mechanisms or bracing structures, a heavy drill for boring through walls or safes, and a crowbar for prying open anything that doesn't yield to the hammer. These tools support Wreck rolls and ensure the character has something in hand when subtlety has been abandoned. The tradeoff is noise and load — these are heavy, conspicuous tools that signal violent intent to anyone who sees you carrying them." },
  { id:"item-tinkering-tools-core", title:"Tinkering Tools", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"tinkering, jeweler, mechanism, tools, tinker, load-1, item, craft", preview:"Precision instruments for detailed mechanical and alchemical work.", content:"A compact but complete set of precision tools for working at small scale: a jeweler's loupe, fine tweezers, a tack hammer, needle-nose pliers, multiple screwdriver heads, and specialized picks for clock mechanisms. These tools are what make Tinker rolls possible on intricate work — cracking a fine lock, repairing a delicate clockwork device, or performing surgery in the field. Without them, detailed mechanical work shifts to desperate position or simply can't be attempted; with them, the character has professional-grade capability at their fingertips." },
  { id:"item-lantern-core", title:"Lantern", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"lantern, light, oil, electroplasmic, load-1, item, vision, ghost-field", preview:"A light source for working in Doskvol's perpetual darkness.", content:"In a city of eternal night, light is a practical necessity and a tactical consideration. A simple oil lantern is cheap and reliable; a fancier electroplasmic lamp burns brighter and longer and doesn't need oil, but it glows with an eerie blue-white light that is very recognizable. The choice matters: a lantern means you can be seen using it, so anyone who sees the light knows someone is there. Not having light at all means Prowl rolls in darkness may shift to limited effect, and any detailed work (Tinkering, Study) becomes significantly harder." },
  { id:"heritage-akoros-core", title:"Akoros", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"akoros, core, city, empire, diverse, doskvol, imperial, mainland", preview:"The industrial heartland of the Imperium, home to Doskvol itself.", content:"Akoros is the largest, most industrialized territory in the Imperium — and the most powerful. It's a vast mosaic of cultures that have merged and collided over centuries, producing a people who are pragmatic, diverse, and deeply familiar with living under imperial authority. Characters from Akoros might have grown up anywhere from the aristocratic towers of Brightstone to the laborer warrens of Coalridge, and that range of backgrounds shapes how they move through the city. Akorosi characters are home on Doskvol's streets in a way outsiders rarely are." },
  { id:"heritage-dagger-isles-core", title:"Dagger Isles", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"wanderer, ships, corsairs, merchants", preview:"Rootless seafarers from island chains beyond imperial reach.", content:"People from the Dagger Isles grow up on ships and spend their lives moving — trading, raiding, or running from one shore to the next. They live outside the Imperium's lightning barriers, which means they deal with spirits and the deathlands differently: through ritual, negotiation, and a pragmatic relationship with the supernatural that Akorosi scholars find both fascinating and alarming. Dagger Isles characters tend to be resourceful, independent, and comfortable with the idea that the rules are someone else's problem." },
  { id:"heritage-iruvia-core", title:"Iruvia", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"foreign, desert, rich, powerful", preview:"A wealthy desert kingdom with its own ancient power and traditions.", content:"Iruvia is a rich, powerful desert nation far to the south — independent of the Imperium and proud of it. It's a land of diverse cultures spanning ancient traditions, sophisticated courts, and a long history that predates imperial expansion. Iruvians in Doskvol are unmistakably foreign — often wealthy, educated, and carrying with them customs and arcane traditions quite different from the ghost-field sorcery of the north. The Red Sashes gang is Iruvian in culture, giving characters of this heritage an immediate connection to a key faction in Crow's Foot." },
  { id:"heritage-severos-core", title:"Severos", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"wild, nomadic, horse-tribes, deathlands", preview:"A hard land of nomadic survivors who live close to the deathlands.", content:"Severos is a blasted, harsh territory where most people live in nomadic horse-tribes, surviving in the ruins of ancient arcane fortresses whose wards still hold back the undead. Imperial settlements are few and fragile. Severosi who end up in Doskvol carry the self-reliance of people accustomed to real danger — not the manufactured dangers of the underworld, but actual existential threat from the deathlands. They often have unusual relationships with spirits and may know survival techniques and old-world knowledge that city-born characters simply don't." },
  { id:"heritage-skovlan-core", title:"Skovlan", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"marginalized, island, unity-war, refugees", preview:"Refugees from the last territory brought under imperial rule by force.", content:"Skovlan was independent until thirty-six years of brutal war ended in imperial annexation. Tens of thousands of Skovlanders lost their homes, their livelihoods, and their country — and many ended up in Doskvol as refugees and displaced workers, occupying the bottom rungs of the city's social hierarchy. Skovlander characters carry that history: the resentment of the colonized, the solidarity of the marginalized, and often a burning motivation that goes beyond simple profit. In the current political climate, being Skovlander in Doskvol means navigating real, daily hostility from Akorosi citizens." },
  { id:"heritage-tycheros-core", title:"Tycheros", source:"BitD Core", page:"53", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"weird, mythical, part-demon, telltale", preview:"A semi-mythical people said to carry demon blood in their veins.", content:"Tycheros is a distant, half-legendary place beyond the northern void sea, and its people are regarded by most Imperials with a mixture of fear and fascination — rumor says the Tycherosi are part-demon, and the truth isn't entirely comfortable. If you choose Tycherosi heritage, you create a demonic telltale that marks your character visibly: shark-black eyes, feathers instead of hair, a shadow that moves wrong, skin that shifts color in lamplight. This mark is permanent and public. It makes you memorable — and in the wrong part of town, it makes you a target." },
  { id:"background-academic-core", title:"Academic", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"scholar, student, philosopher, journalist", preview:"You came from scholarship, research, or the press.", content:"Your character's past life involved the pursuit of knowledge — as a professor or student at Doskvol Academy, a philosopher, a journalist, or some other intellectual vocation. This background gives you a natural cover for gathering information, contacts in educated circles, and a tendency to approach problems analytically. Academics in Doskvol often find that the city's underworld intersects uncomfortably with their old world: the same institutions that fund the universities also run protection rackets." },
  { id:"background-labor-core", title:"Labor", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"servant, factory, docker, sailor", preview:"You came up as a worker — docks, factories, or service.", content:"You know what it is to work for someone else, to be expendable, to survive on what you can scrape together. Dockers, factory hands, servants, sailors, coachmen — the bones of the city are built on people like who you used to be. This background gives you connections to the working poor, a deep familiarity with the districts where real work happens, and a chip on your shoulder that is entirely justified." },
  { id:"background-law-core", title:"Law", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"advocate, bluecoat, inspector, warden", preview:"You came from inside the law — enforcement, courts, or prison.", content:"Your past put you on the other side of the table — as a Bluecoat officer, a court advocate, a Spirit Warden, a prison guard at Ironhook, or a Rail Jack. You understand how the system works from the inside: its procedures, its blind spots, and which palm needs crossing to make something disappear. Former law enforcement in the underworld make dangerous contacts and formidable investigators — they know all the tricks because they used to catch people using them." },
  { id:"background-trade-core", title:"Trade", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"trade, shopkeeper, merchant, shipping, commerce, consort, core", preview:"You came from commerce — shops, shipping, or skilled crafts.", content:"Your past involved making, moving, or selling things — as a shopkeeper, merchant, skilled crafts-person, or shipping agent. Trade background gives you a nose for value, connections in legitimate commerce, and a familiarity with the logistics of moving goods (legally or otherwise) through the city. The Ministry of Preservation, the leviathan trade, the canal companies — these are your old world, and knowing how they work is valuable intelligence in the underworld." },
  { id:"background-military-core", title:"Military", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"military, soldier, mercenary, spy, violence, command, core", preview:"You came from the military — soldier, mercenary, or intelligence operative.", content:"You served: in the Imperial Army, in a Skovlander unit during the Unity War, as a mercenary for hire, or as an intelligence operative in some shadowy branch of the state. Military background gives you discipline, tactical thinking, connections to veterans (who are everywhere in Doskvol), and a capacity for violence that was professionally trained rather than street-learned. It also means you understand chains of command — which makes you very good at either maintaining them or breaking them." },
  { id:"background-noble-core", title:"Noble", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"noble, dilettante, courtier, high-class, influence, consort, core", preview:"You came from privilege — nobility, courts, and high society.", content:"You were born into or moved through the upper echelons of Doskvolian society — a noble house, the imperial court, or the wealthy merchant class that aspires to join it. Noble background gives you access to high society events, an understanding of aristocratic politics, and the kind of easy confidence that comes from growing up expecting doors to open for you. The underworld is a long way from Brightstone, which is either a problem or an enormous advantage depending on what you're planning." },
  { id:"background-underworld-core", title:"Underworld", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"urchin, gang, thug, outcast", preview:"You came up on the streets — gangs, urchins, and the criminal world.", content:"You've been in the underworld your whole life — as a street kid, a gang member, a young thug who learned the hard way, or simply someone the city chewed up and spat out into the gutter. This is home turf. You know the slang, the codes, the power structures, and who to avoid in which district. Underworld background gives you contacts where it counts and a thorough education in the real rules of Doskvol, the ones that don't get written down." },
  { id:"trauma-cold-core", title:"Cold", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"cold, trauma, unmoved, emotionless, detachment, callous, numb, disconnected, stress", preview:"Emotional appeals and social bonds no longer move you.", content:"Something broke in you, and now you move through the world without being touched by it. Fear, grief, love, loyalty — these things register intellectually, but they don't reach you the way they used to. Cold is a double-edged trauma: it makes you excellent under pressure and immune to manipulation through emotional leverage, but it erodes your relationships and can make you genuinely frightening to the people around you. When you let it complicate your character's life, you earn xp — and Cold creates rich dramatic tension when someone tries to get through to you and can't." },
  { id:"trauma-haunted-core", title:"Haunted", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"haunted, trauma, reverie, horror, visions, ghosts, memories, seeing-things, supernatural", preview:"You're trapped in loops of past horror — reliving, seeing, drifting.", content:"The things you've seen and done don't stay in the past. They surface as waking visions, intrusive memories, and a tendency to drift away from the present into scenes from before. Haunted scoundrels startle at shadows, see faces in crowds, and sometimes lose track of where and when they are. In Doskvol, where ghosts are real and the past has literal teeth, this trauma has an extra dimension: sometimes what you're seeing might actually be there. Haunted is excellent for portraying PTSD and for giving the GM hooks to pull you back into old storylines." },
  { id:"trauma-obsessed-core", title:"Obsessed", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"obsessed, trauma, fixation, compulsion, tunnel-vision, enthralled, ideology, activity", preview:"One thing consumes you — a person, a goal, an idea.", content:"Everything else is secondary now. There is one thing — a person, a cause, a skill, an ideology, a mystery — that your character cannot stop thinking about, cannot stop pursuing, cannot let go of no matter the cost. Obsession gives you tremendous drive in one direction and makes you dangerously unreliable everywhere else. When your obsession pulls you off-task, creates friction with the crew, or costs you something real, you earn xp. It's one of the more dramatically productive traumas: a character with a clear obsession is always interesting to watch." },
  { id:"trauma-paranoid-core", title:"Paranoid", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"paranoid, trauma, suspicion, distrust, enemies, hypervigilant, threat-perception, danger", preview:"You see threats everywhere and trust no one.", content:"The underworld will do this to you eventually: after enough betrayals, ambushes, and close calls, your pattern-recognition goes haywire. You start seeing betrayal in small things, reading danger into every offer of help, assuming every friendly face is a set-up. Paranoid characters are exhausting to be around and excellent at detecting actual threats — because they're looking for them everywhere, they find the real ones faster than anyone else. The trauma becomes interesting when it strains crew relationships or when your paranoia turns out to be entirely justified." },
  { id:"trauma-reckless-core", title:"Reckless", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"reckless, trauma, impulsive, consequences, thrill-seeking, careless, risk, danger", preview:"You've stopped caring whether you come back.", content:"Something broke your self-preservation instinct. Maybe you lost something that made survival feel worth it, or maybe you've been through so many close calls that the fear just burned out. Reckless scoundrels take stupid risks, volunteer for suicide runs, and shrug off consequences that would terrify a sane person. This makes them terrifyingly effective in the short term and dangerous to plan around. When your recklessness creates problems for the crew or forces a roll you should never have needed to make, you earn xp." },
  { id:"trauma-soft-core", title:"Soft", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"soft, trauma, sentimental, hesitation, mercy, kindness, passive, gentle, compassion", preview:"Your edge is gone — gentleness has replaced it.", content:"The harshness has been ground out of you. You've become sentimental, passive, unable to bring yourself to do the ruthless things the underworld demands. Soft is a fascinating trauma because it looks like weakness but can generate powerful dramatic moments: the enforcer who can't pull the trigger on the crying mark, the assassin who keeps the target's locket. When your softness costs the crew or puts you in danger, you earn xp — and Soft characters often push the whole table toward asking what this life is actually costing everyone." },
  { id:"trauma-unstable-core", title:"Unstable", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"unstable, trauma, volatile, rage, despair, mood-swings, breakdown, erratic, unpredictable", preview:"Your emotional state can snap in any direction without warning.", content:"You're a powder keg. Rage, despair, impulsive action, sudden paralysis — your emotional state is no longer reliably under your control, and the underworld is full of triggers. Unstable characters are exciting and dangerous to play: they can erupt at critical moments, make decisions that confound everyone, or lock up when they need to act. When your volatility drives the scene or creates a consequence the crew has to deal with, you earn xp. Unstable is especially interesting in long-term play when the triggers become known to the other players but not the character." },
  { id:"trauma-vicious-core", title:"Vicious", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Trauma", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"vicious, trauma, brutal, violence, aggression, ruthless, cruelty, hurt, intimidating", preview:"You've learned to enjoy causing pain.", content:"Something opened a door that didn't close. You seek out chances to hurt people — not out of necessity, not as a tool, but because part of you has started to like it. Vicious is the darkest trauma and the one that creates the most friction: it makes enemies out of witnesses, generates heat, and pushes crews toward moral conversations they might not want to have. When your viciousness complicates the crew's situation or crosses a line that forces a reaction, you earn xp. It's most powerful when the character is genuinely trying to keep it in check and failing." },
  { id:"teamwork-assist-core", title:"Assist", source:"BitD Core", page:"134", category:"Player", subcategory:"Teamwork", "sub-subcategory":"Maneuvers", tags:"assist, help, bonus-die, stress, maneuvers, bitd-core, group-action", preview:"Take 1 stress to give a teammate +1d on their roll.", content:"When a teammate is about to roll, you can step in and help — describe what your character does to support them (holding a light while they pick the lock, covering the door while they talk to the mark, providing a distraction) and take 1 stress. They get +1d added to their pool. Only one character can assist a given roll, so if multiple people want to help, you'll need to use Lead a Group Action instead. Assist is powerful because it costs the helper stress rather than an action, making it one of the most efficient ways the crew can support each other." },
  { id:"teamwork-lead-group-core", title:"Lead a Group Action", source:"BitD Core", page:"134", category:"Player", subcategory:"Teamwork", "sub-subcategory":"Maneuvers", tags:"coordination, multiple-pcs, stress, best-result", preview:"Coordinate the whole team on one action, sharing risk and reward.", content:"When multiple characters need to perform the same action at once — all picking up crates, all sneaking past the guard line, all putting on a convincing act — one PC leads the action. Everyone involved rolls the relevant action rating. The team uses the single best result, meaning the group succeeds if anyone succeeds. The cost: the leader takes 1 stress for each participant who rolled a 1-3 as their best die. Example: four scoundrels all Prowl past the sentries — if two roll a 6, one rolls a 5, and one rolls a 2, the group succeeds (best result: 6), but the leader takes 1 stress for the poor roll." },
  { id:"teamwork-protect-core", title:"Protect", source:"BitD Core", page:"134", category:"Player", subcategory:"Teamwork", "sub-subcategory":"Maneuvers", tags:"defense, intercept, consequence, resistance", preview:"Throw yourself in the way to take a consequence meant for a teammate.", content:"When a teammate is about to suffer a consequence — a blade meant for them, an accusation about to land on them, a bullet with their name on it — you can step in and take it instead. You describe how you intercept the consequence and suffer it yourself. You can then roll to resist it as normal, meaning a good resistance roll reduces or avoids it. Protect is the mechanical expression of 'I've got your back' — it creates powerful dramatic moments and can save a character from consequences that would take them out of the action entirely." },
  { id:"teamwork-setup-core", title:"Set Up", source:"BitD Core", page:"134", category:"Player", subcategory:"Teamwork", "sub-subcategory":"Maneuvers", tags:"indirect, assist, increased-effect, better-position", preview:"Create an opening that gives a teammate better position or effect.", content:"You take an action that creates conditions for a teammate to follow through with greater impact. If your action has its intended result, the teammate who acts next gets either +1 effect level or improved position — your choice when you describe the setup. Example: your Slide engages the vault manager in an absorbing conversation (Set Up), and your Lurk slips into the back office behind him — they get +1 effect on their Prowl roll because the manager's attention is fully occupied. Set Up rewards creative sequencing and rewards teams that think about how their actions chain together." },
  { id:"rule-gather-info-core", title:"Gather Information", source:"BitD Core", page:"36", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Information", tags:"questions, investigation, details, fortune-roll", preview:"Ask the right question; make a roll to find out the answer.", content:"Gathering information is how your crew prepares for a score and fills in the blanks during free play. You ask a specific question — 'What's the patrol schedule at the Leviathan Hunters' compound?' or 'What does Strangford's household staff look like?' — then take action to find out. If it's something you can simply look up or ask around about, no roll needed. If there's risk or uncertainty, an action roll is called for. If the outcome is mostly about how much you learn rather than whether you succeed, a fortune roll is used instead. The GM answers honestly based on the quality of the result." },
  { id:"rule-progress-clocks-core", title:"Progress Clocks", source:"BitD Core", page:"15", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"tracking, obstacles, danger, countdown", preview:"A circle divided into segments that tracks ongoing effort or danger.", content:"A progress clock is a circle divided into equal segments, used to represent anything that develops over time — a complex obstacle, a mounting danger, a long-term project, or a race against time. Four segments for something manageable, six for complicated, eight for daunting tasks. When you make progress (through rolls and effects), ticks fill the segments; when danger advances (through complications), ticks fill a separate clock. When the clock fills, something happens — the alarm triggers, the safe cracks, the guards close in. The GM uses clocks to make the world feel dynamic and alive: things are always moving, whether the crew acts or not." },
  { id:"downtime-acquire-asset-core", title:"Acquire Asset", source:"BitD Core", page:"153", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"temporary, gear, service, cohort", preview:"Get temporary use of an item, vehicle, expert, or gang for the next score.", content:"During downtime you can obtain something you need for the upcoming score — a specific piece of equipment, a vehicle, the services of an expert, or a temporary gang to back you up. Roll the crew's Tier to determine the quality of what you acquire: 1-3 gets you Tier-1 quality, 4/5 gets crew Tier, 6 gets Tier+1, and a critical gives you Tier+2. The asset lasts until it's used up or the score ends. This is crucial for jobs where your standard loadout isn't enough — need a boat, a forged document, a safe-cracker? This is how you get them." },
  { id:"downtime-long-term-project-core", title:"Long-Term Project", source:"BitD Core", page:"154", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"project, clock, investigation, crafting", preview:"Work toward a complex goal one downtime at a time.", content:"Some things can't be accomplished in a single roll — building a new gadget, investigating a conspiracy, developing a new contact, or healing from a persistent condition. A long-term project is represented by a clock (typically 6 or 8 segments), and each downtime you roll a relevant action to tick it: 1-3 gets 1 tick, 4/5 gets 2 ticks, 6 gets 3 ticks, and a critical gets 5 ticks. When the clock fills, you finish the project and gain the result. Projects give the crew things to work toward between scores and make downtime feel purposeful rather than mechanical." },
  { id:"downtime-recover-core", title:"Recover", source:"BitD Core", page:"155", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"recover, healing, harm, clock, downtime, physicker, rest, injury", preview:"Get medical treatment to start healing your harm.", content:"Harm doesn't go away on its own — you need treatment. To recover, you (or a Leech, or a doctor contact) rolls Tinker to tick your healing clock. The roll results apply: 1-3 gets 1 tick, 4/5 gets 2, 6 gets 3, critical gets 5. Your healing clock has 4 segments. When it fills, every harm level you're currently suffering drops by one — a level 3 injury becomes level 2, level 2 becomes level 1, level 1 clears. You can use multiple downtime actions to speed recovery, or find a safe house with a crew upgrade that provides better care." },
  { id:"downtime-reduce-heat-core", title:"Reduce Heat", source:"BitD Core", page:"155", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"reduce-heat, heat, wanted, law, downtime, bribery, misdirection, bluecoats", preview:"Lay low, bribe, or spin the story to cool the Bluecoats' interest.", content:"After a score, the crew accumulates heat — the attention of the City Watch, Spirit Wardens, and other authorities. High heat means dangerous entanglements and a rising Wanted Level. During downtime, you can take active steps to reduce it: lay low and let the story die down, bribe officials to lose paperwork, use your contacts to spin the narrative, or do something that shifts suspicion elsewhere. Describe your approach and roll the relevant action. 1-3 removes 1 heat, 4/5 removes 2, 6 removes 3, critical removes 5. The method you choose shapes the fiction and your position." },
  { id:"downtime-train-core", title:"Train", source:"BitD Core", page:"155", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"xp, experience, attribute, playbook", preview:"Practice and study to earn 1 xp toward an action or attribute.", content:"Spend a downtime action training to earn 1 xp in a chosen attribute (Insight, Prowess, or Resolve) or your playbook track. When you've accumulated enough xp, you can advance: add a dot to an action rating within the attribute, or unlock a new special ability from your playbook. If the crew has the relevant Training upgrade, you earn 2 xp instead of 1 when training that track. Training is the steady, long-term path to making your character more capable — it rewards consistent investment in a direction rather than trying to be good at everything at once." },
  { id:"downtime-indulge-vice-core", title:"Indulge Vice", source:"BitD Core", page:"156", category:"Player", subcategory:"Downtime", "sub-subcategory":"Activities", tags:"stress, vice, overindulge, purveyor", preview:"Visit your vice purveyor to clear stress.", content:"Every PC has a vice — something they turn to when the pressure becomes too much. During downtime, you visit your vice purveyor (a specific NPC who provides it) and indulge. Roll your lowest attribute rating and clear stress equal to the highest die result. If you clear all your stress and could clear more, you overindulge: choose a consequence from the overindulge list (attract unwanted attention, injure yourself, lose coin, betray a friend). Stress is the primary resource in Blades, and indulging vice is how you recover it — which means choosing your vice and finding its purveyor is genuinely important, not just flavor." },
  { id:"roll-action-core", title:"Action Roll", source:"BitD Core", page:"18", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rolls", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"danger, challenge, outcome, mechanics", preview:"The core roll — made whenever a PC does something dangerous or troublesome.", content:"The action roll is the central mechanic of Blades in the Dark. When a PC does something challenging, you build a dice pool equal to their relevant action rating, add bonus dice from assistance or pushing yourself, and roll — reading the highest single die. A 6 is a full success. A 4 or 5 is success with a complication. A 1-3 is a bad outcome with consequences. Two 6s is a critical success with increased effect. The GM sets position (how dangerous the situation is) and effect (how much your action accomplishes) before the roll — these two values are just as important as the result, because they determine what a 4/5 costs you and how much a 6 actually gets you." },
  { id:"roll-downtime-core", title:"Downtime Roll", source:"BitD Core", page:"153", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rolls", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"downtime-roll, downtime, safety, activities, results, advancement, core", preview:"Made during downtime to determine how much you accomplish.", content:"Downtime rolls are simpler and safer than action rolls — you're not in immediate danger, so there's no position to set. You roll a relevant action rating and read the result as a quality level: 1-3 gets the minimum result, 4/5 gets a decent result, and 6 gets a strong result (with a critical getting the maximum). Each downtime activity (Recover, Reduce Heat, Acquire Asset, Long-Term Project, Train, Indulge Vice) specifies what each result level means. The key difference from action rolls is that consequences here are usually softer — you might accomplish less, but you're not getting stabbed." },
  { id:"roll-engagement-core", title:"Engagement Roll", source:"BitD Core", page:"128", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rolls", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"planning, fortune, score, starting-position", preview:"Determines what position the crew is in when the score begins.", content:"After the crew picks their target and plan, the GM cuts straight to the score in progress — and the engagement roll determines how the opening moment looks. It's a fortune roll starting with 1d for sheer luck, modified by the quality of the plan, the crew's Tier, the target's Tier, and any relevant features of the approach. Controlled (6) means things are going well when the scene opens. Risky (4/5) is the default — you're in the action but not in trouble yet. Desperate (1-3) means something went wrong before you even started. The engagement roll replaces long planning scenes with immediate drama." },
  { id:"roll-fortune-core", title:"Fortune Roll", source:"BitD Core", page:"34", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rolls", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"fortune-roll, chance, gm-tool, disclaim-decision, core, outcome, luck", preview:"A roll to leave outcomes up to chance rather than character action.", content:"The GM uses fortune rolls to determine the outcome of events the PCs aren't directly controlling — how well a hired gang performs without supervision, whether a contact comes through on time, how badly a fire spreads, whether an NPC survives. Build the dice pool from the relevant trait, rating, or a flat number of dice reflecting the likelihood of success: 1d (unlikely), 2d (possible), 3d (likely), 4d (very likely). Read the highest result normally. Fortune rolls keep the world moving without requiring the GM to make every decision alone, and they create surprising outcomes that no one planned for." },
  { id:"roll-resistance-core", title:"Resistance Roll", source:"BitD Core", page:"32", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rolls", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"stress, consequence, defense, mitigate", preview:"Roll to reduce or avoid a consequence, paying stress for the privilege.", content:"When a consequence lands that you don't want to accept in full, you can resist it. Declare what you're resisting and roll the relevant attribute: Insight to resist mental or intellectual consequences, Prowess to resist physical harm or exertion, Resolve to resist fear, temptation, or social pressure. You take stress equal to 6 minus the highest die result (so a 6 costs 1 stress, a 1 costs 5 stress). The consequence is either avoided entirely or reduced — the GM decides which based on what makes sense in the fiction. Example: you resist 'Broken Arm' and roll a 4, taking 2 stress — the harm becomes 'Sprained Wrist' instead." },
  { id:"position-controlled-core", title:"Controlled", source:"BitD Core", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Position", tags:"controlled, position, safe, advantage, setup, prepared, low-risk, opportunity", preview:"You have the upper hand — things go well even if the roll isn't great.", content:"Controlled position means you're operating from a position of strength — you have a golden opportunity, you're exploiting a clear advantage, or the situation is set up in your favor. Even a bad roll (1-3) in controlled position just means you falter and have to choose: withdraw, or press on by accepting a risky opportunity. A 4/5 only causes a minor complication. Controlled is rare but powerful; the GM grants it when you've earned an advantage through smart play, good preparation, or a favorable circumstance. Example: you're ambushing a guard from hiding while your partner holds his attention — that's controlled." },
  { id:"position-risky-core", title:"Risky", source:"BitD Core", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Position", tags:"risky, position, standard, default, duress, chance, normal-play, balance", preview:"The default — you're in the action with real stakes on every result.", content:"Risky is the baseline position for most action rolls in Blades in the Dark. You're acting under duress, taking a chance, or going head-to-head with an obstacle. A 6 is clean success. A 4/5 means you succeed but take harm, cause a complication, end up in a worse position, or have reduced effect. A 1-3 means things go badly — harm, complications, or you end up in desperate trouble. Risky captures the core fantasy of the game: daring scoundrels in over their heads, succeeding at real cost. Most of the game lives here." },
  { id:"position-desperate-core", title:"Desperate", source:"BitD Core", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Position", tags:"desperate, position, danger, high-stakes, long-shot, overreaching, trouble, last-resort", preview:"You're in serious trouble — every result hurts except a 6.", content:"Desperate position means the situation is as bad as it gets before a roll. You're overreaching, you're outmatched, or you're attempting something that has no business working. A 6 still gets you success, but a 4/5 means severe harm or serious complications even with success, and a 1-3 is the worst outcome — severe harm, serious complications, and you lose the opportunity. The silver lining: you earn 1 xp just for attempting a desperate action, because Blades rewards the reckless bravado that gets scoundrels killed. Sometimes desperate is the only option left." },
  { id:"effect-great-core", title:"Great Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"24", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Effect", tags:"great-effect, effect, exceptional, 3-ticks, overwhelming, decisive, powerful", preview:"Your action accomplishes more than expected.", content:"Great effect means your action has an outsized impact — you achieve what you set out to do and then some. In terms of progress clocks, great effect ticks 3 segments. The GM asks: 'How does the extra effort manifest? What additional benefit do you enjoy?' Great effect doesn't come for free; the GM grants it when the fiction supports it — when you have a significant advantage in potency, quality, or scale over the obstacle. A Tier III gang storming a Tier I operation has great effect. A master safecracker with the right tools has great effect." },
  { id:"effect-standard-core", title:"Standard Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"24", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Effect", tags:"standard-effect, effect, normal, expected, 2-ticks, baseline, default", preview:"Your action accomplishes what you'd normally expect.", content:"Standard effect is the baseline — you achieve what a competent person doing this action should achieve. Not exceptional, not weak, just the normal result. In terms of progress clocks, standard effect ticks 2 segments. Most action rolls run at standard effect, meaning the GM asks whether that's enough to solve the problem or whether more effort remains. Standard is the default that both limited and great are measured against — when nothing special tips the scales, standard is what you get." },
  { id:"effect-limited-core", title:"Limited Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"24", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Effect", tags:"limited-effect, effect, weak, partial, 1-tick, reduced, obstacles, resistance", preview:"Your action only partially accomplishes its goal.", content:"Limited effect means your action works but doesn't get you all the way there — a partial result, a weak impact, a glancing blow. In terms of progress clocks, limited effect ticks only 1 segment. The GM asks: 'How is your impact diminished? What effort remains to achieve your goal?' Limited effect is triggered when the obstacle has a real advantage over you — better quality, greater scale, or specific potency that your approach doesn't counter. Example: you Skirmish a heavily armored guard with a knife — limited effect because your weapon can't get through the plate." },
  { id:"effect-zero-core", title:"Zero Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"25", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Effect", tags:"zero-effect, effect, blocked, impossible, overwhelmed, factors, futile, no-progress", preview:"No matter what you roll, your action has no impact here.", content:"When the factors are stacked so heavily against you that even success wouldn't matter, the GM calls zero effect. No roll, no result — your action simply cannot move the needle in this situation. A knife against a ghost, your crew against a Tier V faction, a smooth-talker trying to persuade someone under magical compulsion: zero effect. The only ways forward are to change the factors — push yourself to change the fiction, use a setup action, find a tool that counters the obstacle — or accept that this approach doesn't work and try something else entirely." },
  { id:"effect-extreme-core", title:"Extreme Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"25", category:"Player", subcategory:"Pos & Effect", "sub-subcategory":"Effect", tags:"extreme-effect, effect, devastating, 5-ticks, maximum, catastrophic, scale, overwhelming", preview:"A critical success or massive advantage creates an extraordinary result.", content:"Extreme effect is what happens when you roll a critical success (two 6s) or when the factors are overwhelmingly in your favor. It represents impact far beyond the normal scope of the action — demolishing a problem rather than just solving it, a blow so precise it ends the fight in a single moment, a social maneuver that doesn't just convince but converts. In terms of progress clocks, extreme effect ticks 5 segments, which can complete most clocks in a single roll. It's rare, it's memorable, and it usually changes the situation dramatically." },
  { id:"vice-faith-core", title:"Faith", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"faith, god, cult, religion, types, bitd-core, stress", preview:"Devotion to a forgotten god, ancestor, or mysterious entity.", content:"Your character turns to something bigger than themselves when the stress gets too heavy — a forgotten deity, an ancestral spirit, a mysterious cosmic entity, or a secret cult with its own rituals and demands. Faith as a vice doesn't require the religion to be real or good; it just needs to be what your character reaches for. Your purveyor is whoever or whatever facilitates that devotion — a secret temple, a spirit medium, a cult chaplain. Playing this vice well means letting the religious dimension create complications: gods and cults rarely have simple demands." },
  { id:"vice-gambling-core", title:"Gambling", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"gambling, bet, risk, games, types, bitd-core", preview:"Games of chance and high-stakes risk scratch an itch nothing else can.", content:"The tables, the track, the card game in the back room — your character needs the specific high that comes from letting chance decide everything. Your purveyor is a gambling house or a specific game-runner who knows your face and welcomes your coin. This vice creates great dramatic friction because the same impulse that drives your gambling also shapes how your character makes decisions in scores: they're drawn to the risky bet, the long shot, the moment where it could all go wrong. Overindulgence might mean you lose the score's cut before you even get back to the lair." },
  { id:"vice-luxury-core", title:"Luxury", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"luxury, expensive, high-class, display, types, bitd-core, stress", preview:"Expensive things and displays of status are the balm your soul needs.", content:"Fine clothes, rare food, expensive rooms, art, jewelry — your character de-stresses by surrounding themselves with beautiful, costly things. Your purveyor might be a high-end tailor, a luxury restaurant, or an auction house that turns a blind eye to where the money comes from. Luxury as a vice is interesting because it connects directly to money: overindulgence means you spend more than you should, and the habit can make you conspicuous in the wrong neighborhoods. It also says something about where your character wants to end up — or where they're trying to prove they belong." },
  { id:"vice-obligation-core", title:"Obligation", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"obligation, family, charity, debt, types, bitd-core, stress", preview:"You're bound by a responsibility that weighs on you and won't let go.", content:"Some people don't have the luxury of a simple vice — their stress relief comes from fulfilling a responsibility they can't abandon. Family obligations, a debt of honor, a charity they support, a person they protect — whatever it is, meeting this obligation is the one thing that makes the rest of the life feel worth it. Your purveyor is whoever or whatever receives your attention and support. This vice generates excellent drama because the obligation pulls you away from crew interests and creates relationships the GM can leverage as complications." },
  { id:"vice-pleasure-core", title:"Pleasure", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"lovers, food, drink, sensation", preview:"Physical sensation — lovers, gourmet food, drugs, fine art.", content:"Your character unwinds through sensory indulgence — lovers, fine food, carefully chosen intoxicants, the pleasurable ache of a long hot bath, beautiful music. Your purveyor might be a specific person, an establishment, or a dealer. This is one of the more broadly interpretable vices — the key is that it's specific and has a person (the purveyor) attached to it who becomes a recurring character. Overindulgence in this vice has interesting consequences: you might attract the wrong kind of attention, overextend yourself emotionally, or surface at the start of a score in worse shape than you started." },
  { id:"vice-stupor-core", title:"Stupor", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"stupor, drugs, alcohol, escape, types, bitd-core, stress", preview:"You seek total oblivion — in substances, fighting pits, or brutal sensation.", content:"Some stress can only be burned off by going somewhere the mind can't follow — deep into an opiate haze, the bottom of a bottle, or the blank-brained simplicity of getting beaten bloody in a fighting pit. Your purveyor is whoever supplies the specific oblivion your character needs: a den-keeper, a bartender who knows your order, a pit-fight organizer. Stupor is the most self-destructive vice in the list, and playing it means leaning into that: overindulging means you surface damaged, broke, or missing time — which is exactly the kind of complication that makes a character feel real." },
  { id:"vice-weird-core", title:"Weird", source:"BitD Core", page:"55", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"weird, rituals, ghosts, arcane, types, bitd-core, stress", preview:"Strange experiments, spirit-consorting, or bizarre rituals ease your mind.", content:"Your character's release from stress involves things that would alarm ordinary citizens — experimenting with ghost essences, maintaining a personal relationship with a bound spirit, performing arcane rituals that blur the line between self and the supernatural, or observing taboos that make sense only to you. Your purveyor might be a spirit medium, an underground occultist, or the ghost itself. Weird as a vice pairs naturally with Whisper characters but is available to anyone — and it suggests a character whose relationship with Doskvol's supernatural landscape is deeply, personally entangled." },
  { id:"crew-tier-core", title:"Tier", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"tier, crew-stat, advancement, quality, scale, resources, power-level, faction", preview:"Your crew's rank in the underworld hierarchy — determines quality and scale.", content:"Tier represents your crew's standing in Doskvol's criminal ecosystem. It runs from 0 (scrappy newcomers) to 4 (dominant underworld power), and it determines the quality of your default items (Tier counts as a quality bonus), the scale of your gang cohorts, and how you stack up against other factions in conflicts. To advance Tier, you need to fill your advancement track with 12 Rep and spend coin — the amounts increase at each level. Most crews start at Tier 0 or I and spend campaigns clawing their way up. Tier is the single number that tells you where you stand in the food chain." },
  { id:"crew-hold-core", title:"Hold", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"hold, crew-stat, strong, weak, territory, stability, foundation, power", preview:"How securely your crew controls its current Tier — strong or weak.", content:"Hold is a binary: Strong or Weak. It represents how stable your position is at your current Tier — whether your territory is secure, your alliances are solid, and your reputation is well-founded. When your Hold drops below Weak (through consequences from entanglements, faction conflicts, or bad decisions), you lose a Tier. Strong Hold means you're secure; Weak Hold means you're vulnerable to challenges from below and pressure from above. After advancement, you start at Weak Hold for the new Tier, meaning the first job is always consolidating your new position." },
  { id:"crew-rep-core", title:"Rep", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"rep, reputation, crew-stat, influence, standing, notoriety, advancement, underworld", preview:"Your crew's street reputation — earned through scores, spent to advance.", content:"Rep is how the underworld measures your crew's clout and notoriety. You earn Rep after each score: the base amount depends on the Tier of the target and your crew Tier (scoring against a higher-tier faction earns more Rep). You need 12 Rep to fill the advancement track and increase your Tier. Each piece of Turf your crew controls reduces that requirement by 1. Rep doesn't stay earned — spending it on advancement means you're constantly working to rebuild your reputation, which is exactly the kind of perpetual hustle that gives the game its shape." },
  { id:"crew-turf-core", title:"Turf", source:"BitD Core", page:"45", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"turf, territory, crew-stat, claims, district, support, advancement, map", preview:"Territory your crew controls that reduces the Rep needed to advance.", content:"Turf is territory — neighborhoods, venues, or operations your crew controls. Each piece of Turf reduces the Rep cost to advance your Tier by 1, making it a mechanical incentive to expand your footprint rather than just running scores. Turf also carries narrative weight: it's something to defend, something rivals want, and something that generates ongoing income and conflict. Acquiring Turf typically happens through scores, deals, or faction negotiations — and losing it to a hostile faction is one of the nastiest consequences available to the GM." },
  { id:"crew-heat-core", title:"Heat", source:"BitD Core", page:"147", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"heat, police, attention, law, general, bitd-core", preview:"How much attention the law is currently paying to your crew.", content:"After every score, the crew picks up Heat based on how visible and violent the job was — quietly lifting a ledger generates 2 heat, a bloody assault on a noble manor generates much more. The 9-segment Heat track fills up and, when it overflows, converts to Wanted Level. High Heat means the GM rolls on the Entanglements table after each job, bringing Bluecoat patrols, inspectors, informant networks, and worse down on the crew. Managing Heat — by lying low, bribing officials, or staying under the radar — is one of the key resource challenges of the game." },
  { id:"crew-wanted-level-core", title:"Wanted Level", source:"BitD Core", page:"148", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Stats", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"wanted-level, crew-stat, arrest, prison, heat, entanglements, bluecoats, law", preview:"How badly the law wants your crew — escalates with each overflow of Heat.", content:"Wanted Level tracks how much of an institutional priority your crew has become for law enforcement. It runs from 0 to 4, rising each time your Heat track fills to capacity. At Wanted Level 0 you're unknown; at 4 you're subject to military-level suppression. Higher Wanted Levels make entanglement rolls more dangerous and give the GM license to deploy more serious opposition mid-score — Bluecoat task forces, Spirit Wardens, even the Inspectors of the Ministry. Unlike Heat, Wanted Level is very slow to reduce; one way is to incarcerate a crew member as a scapegoat, which brings the level down." },
  { id:"consequence-reduced-effect-core", title:"Reduced Effect", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Consequences", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"reduced-effect, consequence, impaired, effect, obstacles, weak, outcome", preview:"You succeed, but your action is less impactful than you hoped.", content:"Reduced Effect means your roll worked, but the result was weaker than expected — you got through the lock, but took longer than planned; you landed the blow, but it wasn't clean. Effect drops one level (from Standard to Limited, for example). This is one of the 'softer' consequences because you still make progress — it's the GM saying 'yes, but it costs you forward momentum.' It's particularly common on 4/5 results and a useful tool for maintaining pace without completely blocking the crew's plan." },
  { id:"consequence-complication-core", title:"Complication", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Consequences", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"trouble, danger, threat, clock", preview:"A new problem enters the picture — often a ticking clock.", content:"A complication doesn't stop you from succeeding at your immediate action, but it adds something new and bad to the situation. The GM either creates an immediate problem (a guard heard the noise, a witness spotted your face) or ticks a danger clock (1 tick for minor, 2 for standard, 3 for serious). Complications are some of the most interesting consequences because they layer problems on top of each other — the crew succeeds at step 3 of a plan while step 7 is already compromised. They keep pressure building even when nothing has gone catastrophically wrong yet." },
  { id:"consequence-lost-opportunity-core", title:"Lost Opportunity", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Consequences", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"lost-opportunity, consequence, shift, change-approach, missed, timing", preview:"The window you were trying to use has closed.", content:"Lost Opportunity means you don't just fail — the specific approach you were using is no longer available. The guard moved on, the conversation window closed, the distraction ran out. To try again, you need a genuinely new approach: different action, different framing, different circumstance. It's not 'you can't do this,' it's 'you can't do this this way.' Lost Opportunity is a consequence that pushes the fiction forward and demands creative problem-solving, because simply re-rolling the same action won't work." },
  { id:"consequence-worse-position-core", title:"Worse Position", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Consequences", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"worse-position, consequence, danger, escalation, position, risky-to-desperate", preview:"You succeed, but the situation slips further out of your control.", content:"Worse Position means your action worked but put you in more danger than you were in before — you picked the lock but now there's a guard right behind you; you talked your way past the first challenge but you've flagged yourself as suspicious. You can press on and try again, but your next roll is at a worse position than this one. This is one of the most dramatically useful consequences because it creates a sense of escalating danger without stopping the action — the crew keeps moving forward but the ground keeps shifting under them." },
  { id:"consequence-harm-core", title:"Harm", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Consequences", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"harm, consequence, injury, damage, penalty, level, health", preview:"Physical or mental injury that impairs future action.", content:"Harm is injury recorded on your character sheet — a specific description of what happened to you, placed in the appropriate level slot (1: minor but real, 2: a serious injury, 3: nearly incapacitating). Harm in a relevant level slot imposes a -1d penalty to rolls where it matters — a broken arm affects Prowess-based actions, a shaken mind affects Resolve-based rolls. Level 4 harm takes you out entirely. You can resist harm to reduce its severity, or check your armor box to absorb physical harm outright. The specific description is important: it drives the fiction forward and creates conditions the GM can pull on." },
  { id:"upgrade-carriage-house-core", title:"Carriage House", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"carriage-house, transport, vehicle, goats, lair, bitd-core", preview:"A carriage, two goats, and a stable — your own transport.", content:"The Carriage House upgrade gives your crew a serviceable horse-drawn carriage, a pair of goats to pull it, and a stable for housing them. This means the crew has their own transport for scores — useful for moving quickly through the city, carrying large loads, or providing a quick getaway. Further upgrades can add armor plating or increase the goats' speed. It's a practical upgrade that opens up vehicle-based approaches to scores and occasionally means someone has to stable the goats during a tense standoff." },
  { id:"upgrade-boat-house-core", title:"Boat House", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"boat-house, water, vehicle, canal, lair, bitd-core", preview:"A boat and a dock — access to Doskvol's canal network.", content:"Doskvol's canal system is a network of waterways that connects districts, bypasses checkpoints, and offers approaches to buildings that have no street-facing entry. The Boat House upgrade gives your crew a boat (starting simple, upgradeable) and a dock on a canal. This opens up a whole category of planning options: water approaches, smuggling routes, quick escapes by river. Further upgrades improve the boat's capacity and speed. It's one of the upgrades that most dramatically changes how you approach scores." },
  { id:"upgrade-hidden-lair-core", title:"Hidden Lair", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"hidden-lair, secret, disguise, safety, lair, bitd-core, downtime", preview:"Your lair's location is disguised from outsiders.", content:"The Hidden Lair upgrade means your base is concealed — behind a false business front, below an innocent-looking building, in a space that doesn't appear on any official map. Finding it requires inside knowledge or extraordinary effort. This makes it much harder for rival factions, Bluecoats, or targets of your scores to find and raid your base. The caveat: if it is discovered, you must spend downtime and coin to relocate — the secrecy isn't invulnerable, but it raises the cost of being found." },
  { id:"upgrade-mastery-core", title:"Mastery", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Training", tags:"mastery, action-rating, maximum, advance, training, bitd-core, xp-trigger", preview:"Removes the cap on action ratings, allowing advancement to 4.", content:"By default, PC action ratings are capped at 3 dots — you can't put a fourth dot in an action until your crew unlocks Mastery. Once unlocked, all PCs in the crew can advance any action rating up to 4 (the maximum), representing the kind of elite expertise that makes a scoundrel genuinely legendary at their specialty. This is a late-game upgrade for established crews and represents a significant investment in a particular character's direction. A Lurk with 4 dots in Prowl is on a different level than any street-level thief." },
  { id:"upgrade-quality-core", title:"Quality", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"quality, items, tier, bonus, gear, bitd-core", preview:"Improves quality of specific item categories beyond your Tier.", content:"Specific Quality upgrades (Documents, Gear, Tools, etc.) each add +1 quality to items in that category, on top of your crew's Tier. Since quality factors directly into effect level, this means your crew's specialized items punch above their Tier. A Tier I crew with quality Documents effectively operates at Tier II when forgeries and paperwork are involved — which can shift the effect level of a whole approach from limited to standard. These upgrades reward crews that specialize and invest in their specific playstyle." },
  { id:"upgrade-quarters-core", title:"Quarters", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"quarters, sleep, living, safety, lair, bitd-core, xp-trigger", preview:"Your lair has safe sleeping quarters for the whole crew.", content:"Without Quarters, your PC's resting place is exposed — you're sleeping somewhere the crew doesn't control, which means you're potentially vulnerable. The Quarters upgrade establishes proper living space inside your lair: beds, some privacy, the basic infrastructure for actually living at your base. Beyond the fictional benefit, it means the GM has less leverage to introduce threats to sleeping characters, and it reinforces the sense that the lair is truly a home base rather than just a meeting spot." },
  { id:"upgrade-secure-lair-core", title:"Secure Lair", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"locks, alarms, traps, spirits", preview:"Locks, alarms, and traps protect your lair from intruders.", content:"The Secure Lair upgrade adds physical hardening to your base: reinforced doors with serious locks, alarm systems, and traps to slow or deter uninvited guests. The first level covers mechanical security; a further upgrade adds arcane measures specifically against spirit entities, which matters in a city as haunted as Doskvol. A secure lair doesn't make you invulnerable — a determined, high-Tier faction can breach it — but it raises the cost significantly and means you're not always worried about someone walking in while you sleep." },
  { id:"upgrade-training-core", title:"Training", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Training", tags:"training, xp, experience, advancement, bitd-core, downtime, xp-trigger", preview:"Double the xp earned when training a specific track.", content:"Training upgrades (one exists for each attribute track plus the playbook track) mean that when you spend a downtime action training that specific track, you earn 2 xp instead of 1. This halves the time it takes to advance in your specialty. For a crew of Shadows who all want to improve their Prowess actions, the Prowess training upgrade is a huge long-term investment. Training upgrades reward crews that commit to a playstyle — the assassins who all want to be better fighters, or the social crew that all wants to level up their Resolve." },
  { id:"upgrade-vault-core", title:"Vault", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"vault, coin, storage, secure, lair, bitd-core", preview:"A secure vault that expands your coin storage capacity.", content:"By default, crews can only store 4 coin at the lair before it attracts attention or risk. The Vault upgrade increases that to 8 coin, and a second Vault upgrade raises it to 16. This matters because coin is how you pay for Tier advancement, upgrades, and bribes — and having more of it sitting safely in the lair means less pressure to spend it fast or spread it around insecurely. The Vault is a pure mechanical upgrade that enables long-term financial planning, which is exactly what high-Tier crews need." },
  { id:"upgrade-workshop-core", title:"Workshop", source:"BitD Core", page:"95", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Upgrades", "sub-subcategory":"Lair", tags:"tinkering, alchemy, projects, tools", preview:"A fully equipped workshop for crafting, tinkering, and research.", content:"The Workshop upgrade installs a proper working space in your lair — tools, a library, equipment for tinkering and alchemical work. Mechanically, it means crew members can undertake Long-Term Projects from the safety of the lair rather than needing to go out and find a facility. Fictionally, it's where the Leech brews their formulas, where the Whisper maintains their arcane equipment, where the Tinkerer builds the gadget that's going to make the next job work. It's an investment in the lair as a functional base of operations rather than just a place to sleep." },
  { id:"cohort-gang-core", title:"Gang", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"gang, cohort, group, scale, quality, crew-upgrade, strength-in-numbers, downtime", preview:"A group of NPCs who work for the crew with scale and quality based on Tier.", content:"A Gang is a cohort consisting of multiple NPC fighters or specialists — the number in the group is determined by the crew's Tier (a Tier I gang might be 6-10 people; a Tier IV gang could be 40+). The gang's quality rating starts at Tier and can be improved with upgrades. Gangs are typed: Adepts (arcane work), Rooks (social/deception), Rovers (transport), Skulks (stealth), or Thugs (violence). The type determines what the gang is effective at and shapes their edges and flaws. Leading a gang in action uses the Lead a Group Action rules, and they can suffer harm (on their own harm track) independently of the PCs." },
  { id:"cohort-expert-core", title:"Expert", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"expert, cohort, individual, quality, specialist, crew-upgrade, skilled, single-person", preview:"A single specialist NPC with quality equal to Tier+1.", content:"An Expert is a single highly skilled NPC ally — a specialist who works for the crew at a quality rating one step above the crew's Tier, making them consistently more capable than a gang in their specific domain. A Tier I crew's Expert operates at quality 2, which puts them on par with Tier II opponents. Experts have a single type (the same list as gangs) and the same edges and flaws system. They're especially useful when you need one very good person rather than a group — a master forger, a Whisper's spirit ally, a veteran soldier who acts as a personal bodyguard." },
  { id:"cohort-edge-fearsome-core", title:"Fearsome", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Edges", tags:"fearsome, edge, cohort, intimidation, reputation, morale, enemy-hesitation, fear", preview:"This cohort's reputation alone is enough to make enemies hesitate.", content:"A cohort with the Fearsome edge has a reputation — for brutality, for supernatural menace, for a body count that precedes them into every room. When you deploy them in a situation where their reputation could matter (intimidation, establishing dominance, discouraging attack), they gain potency and improved effect. The Fearsome edge is particularly valuable for Thug gangs used as enforcers, where half the work is making sure the other side doesn't want to fight in the first place. It also affects how NPCs react to them in free play — people know who they are and step aside." },
  { id:"cohort-edge-independent-core", title:"Independent", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Edges", tags:"independent, edge, cohort, initiative, autonomous, resourceful, smart, self-direction", preview:"This cohort can make good decisions without direct orders.", content:"Most cohorts require a PC to be actively directing them to function at full effectiveness — without leadership, they default to cautious inaction or poor decisions. An Independent cohort doesn't have this limitation: they can assess a situation, make reasonable calls, and act effectively even when the PCs aren't present or available to command them. This makes them vastly more useful for operations where you need to split the group, leave them on overwatch, or assign them tasks that run in parallel with the crew's main effort." },
  { id:"cohort-edge-loyal-core", title:"Loyal", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Edges", tags:"loyal, edge, cohort, trust, unbribable, reliable, devotion, steadfast", preview:"This cohort cannot be turned against the crew by rivals.", content:"A Loyal cohort has true allegiance to the crew — not just a paycheck, but genuine devotion built on shared history, ideological alignment, or deep personal bonds. Rivals and enemies can't buy them out, intimidate them into betrayal, or manipulate them through their ordinary pressure points. In a game where your enemies are constantly looking for leverage, having people who genuinely won't turn is a real strategic asset. The Loyal edge doesn't make them invulnerable to harm or capture, but it means the information flow only runs one direction." },
  { id:"cohort-edge-tenacious-core", title:"Tenacious", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Edges", tags:"tenacious, edge, cohort, stubborn, driven, resilient, persistent, endurance", preview:"This cohort keeps going when others would quit.", content:"A Tenacious cohort is exceptionally difficult to stop or discourage. They don't break under pressure, they don't abandon a task when it gets difficult, and they don't give up when they've suffered harm — they push through until the job is done or they're physically incapacitated. This is different from Loyal (which is about allegiance) and Independent (which is about initiative): Tenacious is about pure grit under adversity. It's invaluable in a prolonged fight or an extended operation, where lesser gangs would have pulled back hours ago." },
  { id:"cohort-flaw-principled-core", title:"Principled", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Flaws", tags:"principled, flaw, cohort, ethics, morals, refuses-orders, limits, code", preview:"This cohort has a code they won't break, even when ordered to.", content:"A Principled cohort has moral lines they won't cross, regardless of instructions from the crew. This isn't stubbornness — it's ethics: they won't harm civilians, they won't work against a specific faction they respect, they won't torture, they won't commit acts they consider dishonorable. This flaw creates interesting tension because the crew has reliable allies who are also unpredictable in specific scenarios. The trick is knowing your cohort's principles before you deploy them in a situation that tests them — because finding out mid-score is expensive." },
  { id:"cohort-flaw-savage-core", title:"Savage", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Flaws", tags:"savage, flaw, cohort, violent, cruel, collateral-damage, overkill, brutal", preview:"This cohort escalates beyond what's needed, generating heat and enemies.", content:"A Savage cohort is effective but excessive — they use more violence than the situation requires, leave witnesses hurt or humiliated when silence would serve better, and have a habit of turning jobs that should be clean into bloodbaths that generate maximum heat. They're useful for intimidation and direct action, but deploying them in any situation that requires restraint is a gamble. The crew will likely need to manage the fallout of their cohort's methods on a regular basis, and it makes certain kinds of work (subtlety, social operations) essentially off-limits for this group." },
  { id:"cohort-flaw-unreliable-core", title:"Unreliable", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Flaws", tags:"unreliable, flaw, cohort, absent, distracted, undependable, delays, missing", preview:"This cohort isn't always available when you need them.", content:"An Unreliable cohort has other things going on — their own vices, personal obligations, poor discipline, or a tendency to drift when the crew doesn't maintain close oversight. When you want to deploy them, the GM might rule they're not available, or arrive late, or show up at partial strength. This flaw is less dramatic in play than Savage but more practically frustrating: you can't plan around a resource you can't count on, and a cohort that arrives after the crisis point has passed is no help at all." },
  { id:"cohort-flaw-wild-core", title:"Wild", source:"BitD Core", page:"96", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Cohorts", "sub-subcategory":"Flaws", tags:"wild, flaw, cohort, drunk, loud, erratic, undisciplined, draws-attention", preview:"This cohort is drunk, loud, and a liability in any subtle operation.", content:"A Wild cohort has no discipline when they're off the leash — they drink, they brag, they start fights, they attract attention. In direct confrontation they can be effective, but deploy them anywhere that requires staying unnoticed and they'll blow the operation within minutes. The Wild flaw matters most during planning: any score that involves blending in, moving quietly, or maintaining a low profile effectively cannot use this cohort. And even in the lair, their behavior is a constant low-level source of heat and liability." },
  { id:"entangle-cooperation-core", title:"Cooperation", source:"BitD Core", page:"151", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Factions", tags:"cooperation, entanglement, favor, ally, request, faction, heat-1, core", preview:"A friendly faction needs something from you — help or lose standing.", content:"An allied faction (one with +3 status or better toward the crew) comes to you with a request: a job they need doing, a resource they want, a problem they'd like to hand off. If you agree and follow through, your standing with them holds or improves. If you refuse or fail them, you lose Rep and status. Cooperation entanglements are a reminder that relationships in the underworld are reciprocal — your allies helped you get where you are, and they fully expect that to flow in the other direction when they need it." },
  { id:"entangle-demonic-notice-core", title:"Demonic Notice", source:"BitD Core", page:"151", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Supernatural", tags:"demonic-notice, entanglement, demon, bargain, threat, arcane, core", preview:"Something from the other side has taken an interest in your crew.", content:"A demon or powerful supernatural entity has become aware of the crew's activities and makes contact with a proposal — something it wants in exchange for something you need, or perhaps just a threat wrapped in a courteous delivery. You can accept the bargain (and navigate its terms carefully), go to ground and wait for it to lose interest (costing 3 Rep), or find another way to deal with it entirely. Demonic Notice is a tone-setter: it reminds the crew that in Doskvol, the supernatural doesn't stay in the background forever." },
  { id:"entangle-flipped-core", title:"Flipped", source:"BitD Core", page:"151", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Factions", tags:"flipped, entanglement, rival, traitor, contact, betrayal, core", preview:"A rival faction has flipped one of your contacts.", content:"The heat your crew has been generating has given a rival faction enough leverage or incentive to turn one of your contacts or customers. That person now feeds them information, stops working with you, or actively works against your interests. This entanglement directly erodes your network — the GM chooses a contact that makes narrative sense given your recent activity. The crew needs to decide how to handle it: win the contact back, cut ties, or use it as a lead to find out which rival faction is making moves." },
  { id:"entangle-gang-trouble-core", title:"Gang Trouble", source:"BitD Core", page:"151", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Crew", tags:"gang-trouble, entanglement, cohort, flaw, reprisal, conflict, core", preview:"One of your cohorts let their flaw cause a problem.", content:"Your cohort's flaw surfaces in a way that creates real trouble — the Savage gang roughed up a merchant who turned out to be protected, the Wild thugs got drunk and bragged about the last job, the Unreliable gang missed an assignment that needed covering. Now the crew faces the fallout: either lose standing (forfeit Rep) and smooth it over, or face direct reprisals from whoever was wronged. Gang Trouble entanglements are a feature, not a bug — they keep cohort flaws from being purely abstract and ensure there are ongoing consequences to having volatile people in your employ." },
  { id:"entangle-show-force-core", title:"Show of Force", source:"BitD Core", page:"151", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Factions", tags:"show-force, entanglement, rival, threat, territory, violence, core", preview:"A rival faction moves against your territory or contacts.", content:"A rival faction uses your elevated Heat as cover for an aggressive move — they push into your territory, pressure one of your contacts into dropping your business, or make a claim on something you control. You can pay them off (coin or status), let them take it and absorb the loss, or fight back with all the conflict that implies. Show of Force entanglements are the underworld's version of rent: your rivals will test you whenever they sense weakness, and your response defines your reputation for the next cycle." },
  { id:"entangle-unquiet-dead-core", title:"Unquiet Dead", source:"BitD Core", page:"152", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Entanglements", "sub-subcategory":"Supernatural", tags:"unquiet-dead, entanglement, ghost, rogue, horror, supernatural, core", preview:"A rogue spirit is haunting your lair and making life miserable.", content:"A rogue ghost has taken up residence in or around the crew's lair — drawn by violence, trauma, or arcane residue from recent activities. It's disruptive, potentially dangerous, and definitely a problem that can't be ignored for long. Options: a Whisper or hired arcane specialist deals with it (possibly at significant cost), the crew relocates to temporary quarters (exposing themselves to other risks), or someone makes a deal with it. Unquiet Dead is a reminder that Doskvol's supernatural infrastructure never fully stays in the background when you're doing violent, arcane, or reckless work." },
  { id:"faction-billhooks-core", title:"The Billhooks", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-billhooks, tough, butchers, extortion, criminal, bitd-core, xp-trigger", preview:"Dock-district butchers turned brutal extortion gang.", content:"The Billhooks started as literal butchers working the slaughterhouses and meatpacking operations near Crow's Foot, and they never left the trade — they just expanded what they consider meat. They run extortion rackets through the docks district with a signature brutality: hooks, cleavers, and a willingness to leave very visible messages. They're not sophisticated, but they're numerous and genuinely vicious. Getting on their bad side means very direct, very physical consequences. Getting on their good side means having a wall of large, violent people between you and your problems." },
  { id:"faction-bluecoats-core", title:"The Bluecoats", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Law", tags:"the-bluecoats, police, corrupt, city-watch, law, bitd-core, command", preview:"The City Watch — publicly trusted, institutionally corrupt.", content:"The Bluecoats are Doskvol's official law enforcement: uniformed, nominally accountable, and deeply, structurally corrupt at every level. Beat officers take protection money from businesses; inspectors sell information to the gangs they're supposed to be investigating; commanders maintain quiet understandings with whichever factions keep the major streets from getting too messy. The Bluecoats aren't wholly evil — there are genuine reformers and honest officers — but the institution runs on bribery and selective enforcement. They're simultaneously an obstacle, a resource, and a constant background pressure on every crew's operations." },
  { id:"faction-crows-core", title:"The Crows", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-crows, old-gang, extortion, crow-foot, criminal, bitd-core, faction", preview:"An established Crow's Foot gang in political turmoil after their leader's murder.", content:"The Crows are one of the oldest gangs in Crow's Foot, built on extortion, gambling, and territorial control going back two generations. Their longtime leader Roric was recently murdered under contested circumstances, leaving the gang in an unstable succession crisis between multiple would-be successors. This makes them simultaneously dangerous and vulnerable: dangerous because their infrastructure and loyalty network are intact, vulnerable because internal division creates openings for rivals. The crew's relationship with the Crows during this transition will shape much of the early campaign's faction politics." },
  { id:"faction-dimmer-sisters-core", title:"The Dimmer Sisters", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Arcane", tags:"the-dimmer-sisters, witches, occult, ghosts, arcane, bitd-core, faction", preview:"Reclusive occultists who trade in ghosts and arcane secrets.", content:"The Dimmer Sisters are a small, isolated, and deeply strange faction of occultists who deal in ghost-harvesting, arcane research, and secrets better left alone. They maintain a low profile by design — their power comes from knowledge rather than numbers — but those who've crossed them tend to disappear in ways the Spirit Wardens find professionally interesting. They're a resource for crews willing to pay in unusual coin (favors, information, arcane components), and they're useful allies against supernatural threats. Getting involved with them, however, tends to make your life significantly weirder." },
  { id:"faction-fog-hounds-core", title:"The Fog Hounds", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-fog-hounds, smugglers, canal, transport, criminal, bitd-core, faction", preview:"Canal-running smugglers with routes through every waterway in the city.", content:"The Fog Hounds specialize in moving things — contraband, people, information — through Doskvol's extensive canal network, using boats and barge traffic to avoid the checkpoints that snag land-based operations. They know the waterways better than anyone and have arrangements with dock workers, lock keepers, and canal patrol officers that keep their routes clear. For a crew that needs to move something quietly, the Fog Hounds are a natural partner or subcontractor. For a crew working the river district, they're the dominant faction that controls access to the most useful routes." },
  { id:"faction-hive-core", title:"The Hive", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-hive, merchants, trade, legitimate-front, criminal, bitd-core, xp-trigger", preview:"A vast merchant guild that runs criminal operations behind legitimate trade.", content:"The Hive is one of the most powerful factions in Doskvol — not because of brute force but because of reach. They operate through a network of legitimate trade businesses: shops, warehouses, shipping companies, and import/export operations that give them access to money, goods, and the cooperation of city officials who benefit from their economic activity. Their criminal operations (smuggling, money laundering, protection) run inside that legitimate shell, making them nearly untouchable through conventional means. They're not flashy enemies; they're the kind of faction that buries you under legal complications and economic pressure." },
  { id:"faction-lampblacks-core", title:"The Lampblacks", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-lampblacks, war, coal, territory, criminal, bitd-core", preview:"Former coal merchants now deep in a bloody gang war over Crow's Foot.", content:"The Lampblacks began as legitimate coal merchants — the 'lampblack' (soot) from their trade gave them the name — and their transformation into a criminal gang happened gradually as the underworld economy made criminal operations more profitable than honest ones. Now they're locked in a bloody turf war with the Red Sashes over control of Crow's Foot, and that conflict is the background radiation of the district. The Lampblacks are scrappy and territorial, led by Bazso Baz, who has vision beyond simple street control — but vision and resources are not the same thing." },
  { id:"faction-red-sashes-core", title:"The Red Sashes", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-red-sashes, swordsmen, academy, war, criminal, bitd-core", preview:"Iruvian sword-masters running criminal operations from behind a fighting school.", content:"The Red Sashes operate behind the cover of a legitimate Iruvian sword-fighting academy — and unlike many criminal fronts, the school is genuinely excellent. Their students learn real technique from real masters, and the alumni network extends into legitimate society in ways that give the Red Sashes social connections beyond their criminal tier. Their ongoing war with the Lampblacks is about territory and pride in equal measure, and their Iruvian cultural identity shapes their methods: formal, honor-conscious, and capable of both sophisticated negotiation and extremely skilled violence." },
  { id:"faction-spirit-wardens-core", title:"The Spirit Wardens", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Law", tags:"the-spirit-wardens, arcane, ghosts, hunters, law, bitd-core, hunt", preview:"Elite masked hunters who contain and destroy rogue spirits.", content:"The Spirit Wardens are the city's official response to the ghost problem — an elite, masked, secretive corps of arcane specialists who hunt rogue spirits, contain possessions, and dispose of the supernatural threats that the City Watch is completely unequipped to handle. They're respected, feared, and deeply strange: the masks, the rituals, the willingness to work in the most haunted parts of the city at any hour. They're an obstacle for crews working near ghost activity and a potential (if uncomfortable) resource for Whispers who need specialist support. Their institutional secrecy makes them unpredictable partners." },
  { id:"faction-unseen-core", title:"The Unseen", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-unseen, conspiracy, spies, hidden, criminal, bitd-core, faction", preview:"A hidden conspiracy of spies and assassins with fingers in every institution.", content:"The Unseen are what they sound like: invisible. No one outside their organization knows who's in it, what they want, or how many of them there are. Their agents operate at every level of Doskvolian society, gathering information and applying pressure through intermediaries. They don't fight directly; they make problems disappear or appear at convenient times. Dealing with the Unseen is like fighting smoke — you can't hit what you can't find, and by the time you know they're targeting you, the trap is usually already closed. They're most useful as a long-term mystery faction whose nature the crew slowly uncovers." },
  { id:"faction-wraiths-core", title:"The Wraiths", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Criminal", tags:"the-wraiths, thieves, ghosts, stealth, criminal, bitd-core, assist", preview:"Elite thieves who use ghost-tech to pull off impossibly clean heists.", content:"The Wraiths are professional thieves operating at the highest end of the craft — the kind of crew that steals things from places that shouldn't be stealable. They specialize in ghost-assisted infiltration: using spirit-tech, ghost passage, and arcane tools to bypass security that would stop any conventional approach. They're not soldiers and they don't want direct conflict, but they're so good at what they do that they rarely need to fight. For a crew of Shadows or Lurks, the Wraiths represent both aspirational targets (what you're trying to become) and potential rivals (they don't like competition in their niche)." },
  { id:"faction-deathlands-scavs-core", title:"Deathlands Scavengers", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Outcasts", tags:"deathlands-scavengers, wilderness, survivors, toxic, outcasts, bitd-core", preview:"Tough survivors who venture outside the lightning barriers for salvage.", content:"The Deathlands Scavengers operate in the most dangerous real estate on earth: the areas outside Doskvol's lightning barriers, where the deathlands stretch in every direction and the dead walk freely. They're survivors first, merchants second — trading old-world salvage, rare materials, and sometimes information about what's happening in the ruins to anyone willing to pay. They're rough, paranoid, and distinctly strange after years spent in places that do things to a person's relationship with death. Hiring them for off-city work or buying what they've found is one of the few ways to access pre-Cataclysm knowledge and technology." },
  { id:"faction-ironhook-core", title:"Ironhook Prison", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Law", tags:"ironhook-prison, jail, warden, punishment, law, bitd-core, faction", preview:"The great prison — a faction unto itself with its own internal economy.", content:"Ironhook isn't just where people go when they get caught — it's a functioning society with its own power structures, economy, and factions operating entirely within the walls. The warden runs the official operation; powerful inmates run everything else. There are gangs, trade networks, information brokers, and enforcers operating inside, and many of them have lines out to the city's underworld. For a crew with members who've done time (or who are currently incarcerated), Ironhook is a living institution with relationships, obligations, and opportunities. Getting sent there isn't necessarily the end — it's often a different kind of beginning." },
  { id:"faction-leviathan-hunters-core", title:"Leviathan Hunters", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Trade", tags:"leviathan-hunters, ships, blood, industrial, trade, bitd-core, electroplasm", preview:"The massive ships that harvest leviathan blood to power the city.", content:"The Leviathan Hunters are the industrial backbone of Doskvol's survival: massive ships, crewed by the toughest and most desperate workers in the Imperium, that venture into the lightless void sea to hunt the enormous supernatural creatures whose blood (electroplasm) powers the lightning barriers and every electrical system in the city. Without them, the barriers fall and Doskvol dies within days. This makes them powerful beyond their Tier suggests — they're essential infrastructure, and the factions that control the leviathan blood trade control the city's fundamental dependency." },
  { id:"faction-sailors-core", title:"Sailors", source:"BitD Core", page:"285", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Trade", tags:"sailors, docks, working-class, ships, trade, bitd-core, faction", preview:"The dock workers and mariners who keep Doskvol's trade alive.", content:"The Sailors represent the collective of dockworkers, sailors, longshoremen, and maritime workers who keep goods flowing through Doskvol's port — the largest in the Imperium. They're not a criminal organization, but they're a faction with real power: a work stoppage at the docks can cripple the city in days, and their informal networks carry information, contraband, and favors at a speed that rivals the formal underworld. Crews with dock district operations need good relationships with the Sailors; alienating them means everything that moves through the port suddenly becomes much harder to move." },
  { id:"playbook-hound-68", title:"Hound", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"hound, fixer, instinct, tracker, general, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"A hard-bitten fixer who solves problems with instinct and resourcefulness.", content:"The Blades 68 Hound is the crew's fixer and improviser — someone who can find what others want to keep hidden, whether that's a person, a solution, or the one lead in a cold case. Unlike the Core Hound's focus on hunting and shooting, the B68 version leans into resourcefulness and networks: they know people, they follow their gut, and when they have no leads they manufacture them. They earn xp when they address challenges through instincts or personal connections, rewarding a player who wants to play a scrappy, street-savvy generalist with a nose for trouble." },
  { id:"playbook-hull-68", title:"Hull", source:"B68", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"hull, robot, soul, automaton, b68, mechanical, spirit, construct, paranormal", preview:"A condemned criminal's soul trapped inside a malfunctioning robotic body.", content:"The Hull is one of the strangest playbooks in Blades 68: your character is a robotic automaton — built to be a productive, compliant laborer — but something went wrong. The criminal soul inside refuses to stay rehabilitated. You have a robot's capabilities (built-in armor, mechanical strength, no stress — only Drain) and a human's ambitions, memories, and criminal instincts, all in a body that was designed to betray the former. You choose two frame features that shape your physical capabilities, and you start with no Keys because your emotional connections are almost entirely gone. Hull play is about a character who is neither quite human nor quite machine and is figuring out which one they want to be." },
  { id:"playbook-intellectual-68", title:"Intellectual", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"intellectual, engineer, scientist, philosopher, b68, knowledge, research, academic", preview:"A brilliant analytical mind who solves problems science and society haven't solved yet.", content:"The Intellectual is the crew's technical genius and analytical backbone — the engineer who understands how the city works, the scientist who knows which rules can be broken, the philosopher who sees angles no one else considers. They specialize in research, crafting inventions, and providing the crew with specialized expertise that shifts the terms of a problem entirely. Their abilities reward investment in long-term projects and technical solutions, and they have a Sparkmind assistant — a specialized AI-adjacent device — that expands their reach. Play an Intellectual when you want to be the person who makes impossible things merely very difficult." },
  { id:"playbook-operative-68", title:"Operative", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"operative, stealth, espionage, spy, b68, covert, infiltration, intelligence", preview:"A clinical espionage professional who moves unseen and leaves no trace.", content:"The Operative is a trained intelligence professional — covert, methodical, and thoroughly practiced at entering places they shouldn't be and leaving with things they shouldn't have. Unlike the Core Lurk (who is urban and improvisational), the Operative brings a tradecraft framework: deep cover identities, dead drops, sleeper agents, and the ability to vanish into the resonance field entirely. They earn xp when they address challenges with stealth or subterfuge. Play an Operative when you want a character whose skills come from institutional training rather than street necessity — smooth, precise, and quietly terrifying." },
  { id:"playbook-paranormalist-68", title:"Paranormalist", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"paranormalist, occult, ghost, bizarre, b68, supernatural, arcane, investigation", preview:"A maverick who studies what the Age of Consensus insists doesn't exist.", content:"The Paranormalist is a character who treats the supernatural as a scientific field — one that the current Age of Consensus refuses to officially acknowledge, which makes their expertise both extraordinary and dangerous to advertise. They commune with resonance entities, study anomalies that mainstream science explains away, and use their knowledge to do things that look like magic to everyone watching. Their abilities lean heavily into arcane interaction and psychic phenomena. Play a Paranormalist when you want a character whose expertise is in the impossible — and who has the evidence to prove it's real." },
  { id:"playbook-radical-68", title:"Radical", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"radical, agitator, incendiary, explosives, b68, revolutionary, political, disruption", preview:"A political agitator who fights the system — in every sense of the word.", content:"The Radical is a true believer who is done waiting for change. They use the underworld as a launching pad for political action: spreading revolutionary literature, rallying the oppressed, sabotaging the infrastructure of power, and occasionally blowing things up when the situation calls for a more direct form of argument. Their abilities reward public action, ideological commitment, and building a movement rather than just a crew's bank account. They earn xp when they address challenges by fighting for their ideology. Play a Radical when you want your character's ambitions to be bigger than the next score." },
  { id:"playbook-swinger-68", title:"Swinger", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"swinger, social, charm, driving, b68, charisma, mobility, connections", preview:"A charming improviser who thrives on speed, fun, and human connection.", content:"The Swinger is the crew's social whirlwind — someone who's good at talking, better at improvising, and best when the situation is moving fast enough that no one has time to check their credentials. They specialize in Sway and Consort and lean into quick thinking, personal charm, and the ability to turn any situation into a social opportunity. Their abilities reward working with people, letting themselves be talked into things, and having fun in a way that benefits the crew. Play a Swinger when you want a character who treats every interaction as an opportunity and every problem as a conversation waiting to happen." },
  { id:"playbook-veteran-68", title:"Veteran", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"veteran, military, scarred, violence, b68, soldier, experience, resilience", preview:"A soldier who survived the front lines and now applies that training to the underworld.", content:"The Veteran has done the worst kind of work — infantry, combat operations, the kind of sustained violence that leaves permanent marks. They carry military discipline, combat effectiveness, and the specific psychological weight of having been state-sanctioned in killing. Their abilities reward leading from the front, protecting their crew, and applying military principles (overwhelming force, unit cohesion, logistics) to criminal operations. They earn xp when they address challenges using their military training. Play a Veteran when you want a character who is very good at violence and is actively trying to figure out what else they are." },
  { id:"playbook-ghost-echo-68", title:"Ghost/Echo", source:"B68", page:"335", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"ghost, echo, spirit, paranormal, non-corporeal, resonance, haunting, anomaly, unnatural, b68", preview:"A spirit or anomalous resonance entity caught between worlds.", content:"The Ghost/Echo playbook represents a character who is not quite alive in the conventional sense — a spirit that has retained its personality and agency, a resonance anomaly that has achieved something resembling consciousness, or a person who crossed into the ghost field and didn't come back entirely unchanged. These characters navigate the world with capabilities that purely physical characters don't have and limitations that make ordinary life complicated. Specific rules vary by implementation, but the core experience is of a character who exists in the margins of reality and uses that to do extraordinary things." },
  { id:"playbook-vampire-68", title:"Vampire", source:"B68", page:"336", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"vampire, undead, blood, strictures, immortal, paranormal, dayfire, resonance-echo, unnatural, b68", preview:"An undead predator bound by ancient laws and sustained by blood.", content:"The Vampire playbook plays into Doskvol's dark fantasy roots: a character who is genuinely undead, requiring blood to sustain themselves, subject to specific supernatural vulnerabilities, but possessed of power and longevity that living scoundrels can't match. Playing a Vampire means navigating the social and practical complications of being something the city fears and hunts, while leveraging the advantages that come with it. The 'ancient strictures' — the rules vampires must follow — create built-in dramatic constraints that generate interesting play when they collide with the crew's needs." },
  { id:"playbook-time-traveler-68", title:"Time Traveler", source:"B68", page:"221", category:"Player", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"time-traveler, temporal, glitch, future, displacement, anachronism, paranormal, echo, unnatural, b68", preview:"A visitor from another era whose presence destabilizes the timeline.", content:"The Time Traveler is a character from a different point in history who has become unstuck in Doskvol 68's timeline — and whose very presence creates temporal anomalies, glitches in the fabric of events, and moments where past and future leak into the present. They carry knowledge from outside the current era that no one else has access to, at the cost of constantly destabilizing the timeline around them. This is the most conceptually experimental playbook in the B68 set, designed for groups who want to push the setting into science-fiction territory." },
  { id:"crew-dealers-68", title:"Dealers", source:"B68", page:"98", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"pushers, illegal, product, drugs", preview:"A crew that acquires and sells illegal product across a defined territory.", content:"The Dealers are a crew built around the acquisition, processing, and distribution of illegal substances across a defined sales territory. Their game revolves around supply chains (acquiring product in bulk), market management (maintaining customers and territory), and competitive pressure (rivals who want a piece of their action). They earn xp when they execute successful bulk acquisition, bulk sales, social intrigue, or show of force operations. Instead of hunting grounds, they have a sales territory — a district or venue they've claimed for their distribution network. Play Dealers when the crew wants their criminal operation to feel like running a business, complete with all the complications that implies." },
  { id:"crew-hit-squad-68", title:"Hit Squad", source:"B68", page:"108", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"hit-squad, crew, assassins, murder, contract, b68, targeted-violence, professional", preview:"Contract killers who specialize in discreet, deniable violence.", content:"The Hit Squad is a crew of professional killers — they take contracts from factions, individuals, and parties who need problems made permanently disappear. Their special moves and upgrades revolve around the execution of specific operation types: accidents (deaths that look natural), disappearances (targets who simply cease to be findable), murder (direct, professional elimination), and ransom (holding something or someone until paid). They earn xp for successfully pulling off these operation types. Play a Hit Squad when you want the crew's work to feel clinical, purposeful, and very high-stakes — where every job has specific parameters and failure has escalating consequences." },
  { id:"crew-racers-68", title:"Racers", source:"B68", page:"124", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"racers, crew, thrill-seekers, driving, hijack, b68, vehicles, speed, chase", preview:"Speed junkies and vehicle specialists who live for the chase.", content:"The Racers are built around vehicles and movement — they specialize in the transport, escape, and interception phases of operations, with special moves and upgrades that make them exceptional behind the wheel (or tiller, or throttle). They run illegal races, handle smuggling contracts that depend on speed and route knowledge, and execute jobs where the getaway is the most critical element. Play Racers when you want the crew's identity to be tied to velocity and the specific thrill of chases, narrow escapes, and the knowledge that your vehicle is faster than anything the opposition can put on the road." },
  { id:"crew-shadows-68", title:"Shadows", source:"B68", page:"132", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"covert, heists, espionage, theft", preview:"Covert specialists who steal objects, information, and secrets.", content:"The Shadows are a crew of professional infiltrators and thieves — they specialize in getting into high-security locations, taking what they came for, and getting out clean. Their hunting grounds are the high-value targets of Doskvol: corporate vaults, government facilities, noble estates, and the personal sanctuaries of the powerful. Their upgrades and special moves revolve around covert entry, bypassing security, and operating without leaving traces. Play Shadows when you want heists to be the center of the campaign — careful planning, clever execution, and the steady accumulation of sophisticated skills and equipment." },
  { id:"rule-armor-68", title:"Armor", source:"B68", page:"153", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"armor, defense, reduction, b68, protect, harm, consequence, load", preview:"Armor automatically reduces physical harm once per scene.", content:"In Blades 68, armor works somewhat differently from the Core rules. As long as you're wearing armor, all physical harm is automatically reduced by one level every time you take it — think of it as a free resistance roll that's always on. This means you're consistently protected without spending stress, as long as the harm is physical. The tradeoff: you can choose to total your armor, which completely negates one instance of physical harm instead of reducing it, but the armor is destroyed in the process and you lose its protection for the rest of the score. This makes the decision of when to total your armor a meaningful tactical moment." },
  { id:"rule-keys-68", title:"Keys", source:"B68", page:"154", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"keys, xp, personality, traits, b68, advancement, roleplaying, deadlocks", preview:"Character traits that generate xp when expressed in play.", content:"Keys replace the Core game's xp triggers in Blades 68. A Key is a central personality trait — something your character genuinely is, not just does — and if you act on it meaningfully during a session, you mark 1 xp. Keys might be things like 'loyal to those who've earned it,' 'cannot walk past injustice,' or 'always has an angle.' They're player-defined and character-specific, making them a powerful tool for communicating what kind of scenes you want to play. When a Key no longer fits who your character is (after growth or trauma), you can retire it and earn a benefit for doing so." },
  { id:"rule-stacks-bank-68", title:"Stacks and Bank", source:"B68", page:"158", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"stacks-and-bank, currency, wealth, retirement, b68, money, savings, advancement", preview:"B68's wealth system — stacks of cash and long-term savings in the bank.", content:"Blades 68 replaces Coin and Stash with Stacks and Bank. Stacks are the liquid cash equivalent — the money flowing through operations, used for bribes, acquisitions, and crew expenses. Bank is the long-term savings layer: money put away safely in financial institutions, investment vehicles, or well-hidden physical caches. Like Stash in the Core game, Bank represents your character's retirement fund and long-term security — the higher your Bank, the better your retirement outcome. The distinction matters because Stacks are vulnerable (they can be seized, spent, or stolen) while Bank is secure but less accessible." },
  { id:"rule-ticking-timebombs-68", title:"Ticking Timebombs", source:"B68", page:"273", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"ticking-timebombs, clocks, background, crisis, b68, pressure, threat, escalation", preview:"City-wide background crises that interrupt the crew's business at random.", content:"Ticking Timebombs are a GM-facing tool in Blades 68 for representing large-scale background crises that simmer in the city and periodically blow up in ways that directly affect the crew. Unlike faction clocks (which are driven by PC actions), Timebombs are independent: they tick forward based on in-world conditions, and when they fill, something significant happens whether or not the crew was paying attention. Examples might include political instability, supernatural emergence events, or escalating gang wars that restructure the city's power map. They make Doskvol 68 feel like a living city with its own momentum." },
  { id:"phase-personal-business-68", title:"Personal Business", source:"B68", page:"164", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Phases", tags:"personal-business, downtime, free-play, phases, between-scores, b68, activities", preview:"B68's combined downtime phase — free play woven together with downtime activities.", content:"Personal Business replaces the Core game's distinct downtime phase with something more fluid. Rather than a structured sequence of downtime activity slots, Personal Business is free play with downtime activity options woven through it: your character can go places, do things, make rolls, talk to NPCs, and handle downtime activities (from the official list) in whatever order and mix makes sense. The only rule is that the formally listed downtime activities (like Recover, Acquire Asset, or working on Long-Term Projects) are the ones that require the limited 'action slots.' Everything else is just play. This makes downtime in B68 feel continuous rather than procedural." },
  { id:"faction-unseen-68", title:"The Unseen", source:"B68", page:"297", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"the-unseen, secret, powerful, conspiracy, underworld, b68, faction", preview:"A secret society believed to pull the strings of most of Doskvol's power.", content:"The Unseen in Blades 68 are an even more substantial mystery than their Core counterpart — widely believed to be the hidden architects behind most of what happens in the city, with agents embedded in every major institution and faction. Their base of operations is rumored to be hidden inside the dormant volcano of Red Queen Island, but nothing is confirmed. Dealing with the Unseen means never knowing exactly who you're actually talking to, what their full agenda is, or how many layers separate you from whoever is actually in charge. They are, in every sense, the deep state of the Doskvol 68 underworld." },
  { id:"faction-bluecoats-68", title:"Bluecoats", source:"B68", page:"349", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutional", tags:"bluecoats, police, corrupt, watch, institutional, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"The City Watch of Doskvol 68 — rebranded as friendly, still corrupt.", content:"In Blades 68, the Bluecoats have been through a PR transformation: decades of public relations work have repositioned them as 'your friendly local constables,' community-focused, accountable, and approachable. The reality hasn't changed. They're just as corrupt, violent, and selectively enforcing as they've always been — they've just gotten better at managing their image. The rebranding actually makes them more dangerous to work against: it's harder to build public sympathy against an institution that people are culturally disposed to view positively, even when they personally experience its brutality." },
  { id:"faction-burn-corps-68", title:"The Burn Corps", source:"B68", page:"343", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"the-burn-corps, radical, militant, severosi, underworld, b68", preview:"The armed wing of Severosi activist politics.", content:"The Burn Corps is the militant arm of Burning Orange, a Severosi social activism collective that has decided peaceful protest is insufficient. They specialize in armed defense of Severosi communities against Bluecoat brutality, targeted direct action against institutions that oppress their community, and providing muscle for political operations that more respectable activists can't publicly endorse. They're not primarily criminal — their violence has political purpose — which makes them both valuable allies for Radical characters and complicated relationships for crews that don't want to get tangled in their ideology." },
  { id:"faction-mirror-house-68", title:"Mirror House", source:"B68", page:"363", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"mirror-house, science, rogue, anomaly, underworld, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Rogue scientists monopolizing the trade in metaphysical anomaly materials.", content:"Mirror House is a faction of scientists who went off-grid — researchers who became convinced that the officially forbidden study of paranormal phenomena was more important than institutional approval or personal safety. They've been systematically cornering the market on alluvium (a rare material associated with metaphysical anomalies) and other resonance-adjacent substances, building both expertise and supply advantage that makes them essential to anyone working with paranormal phenomena. Their methods are not always ethical, and their research occasionally produces results that alarm even them." },
  { id:"faction-d13-68", title:"D-13", source:"B68", page:"356", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"d-13, soldiers, military, desperate, underworld, b68", preview:"Veterans with no future who've turned their training toward survival.", content:"D-13 is what you get when you take soldiers the military has used up and discarded — veterans of the Unity Wars and subsequent conflicts who came home to find no support, no transition resources, and no legitimate path forward — and give them a purpose. They're organized along military lines, operate with discipline and tactical competence that gang-trained criminals rarely match, and they're motivated by a combination of loyalty to each other and a pragmatic absence of better options. They're dangerous, capable, and sympathetic in a way that makes them interesting moral terrain for crews to navigate." },
  { id:"ability-hound-instincts-b68", title:"Hound's Instincts", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hounds-instincts, push, tracking, leads, hound, b68, push-yourself", preview:"When you push yourself, you can generate leads from nothing or command attention.", content:"When you push yourself (taking 2 stress), you can do one of two things beyond the standard push benefits: figure out where to go next even with zero leads — your character's gut fills in where evidence runs out — or make someone stop and listen to you for a few moments regardless of how hostile or distracted they are. The first option is invaluable for investigations that have gone cold; the second is a social tool that doesn't require a roll. Together they define the Hound as someone who moves forward when others are stalled and commands attention when they need it." },
  { id:"ability-learn-hard-way-b68", title:"Learn the Hard Way", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"learn-the-hard-way, harm, gather-info, resilient, hound, b68, stress", preview:"Taking harm clears stress and automatically provides useful information.", content:"Whenever you take harm, two things happen automatically: you clear stress equal to the harm level (level 1 harm clears 1 stress, level 2 clears 2, etc.), and it counts as a successful Gather Information roll with detail quality equal to the harm level. The GM tells you what you learn from the experience. This ability reframes suffering as intelligence — getting hurt is uncomfortable, but for this Hound, pain is data. It makes them resilient to harm in a non-obvious way and rewards putting themselves in danger to gather information directly." },
  { id:"ability-just-a-scratch-b68", title:"Just a Scratch", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"just-a-scratch, harm, penalty, ignore, hound, b68, skirmish", preview:"Harm penalties don't slow you down during a score.", content:"Harm doesn't factor into your effect level during a score — a broken arm doesn't reduce your Skirmish rolls, a cracked rib doesn't limit your Prowl. Level 4 harm (taken out) is still fatal and still ends your participation, and you still roll for harm complications normally, but the mechanical penalty of lower-level harm simply doesn't apply while you're in the field. Additionally, if someone has caused you harm, you gain potency when you Consort with them — an interesting social edge derived from shared suffering. This ability lets you play through injuries that would bench most characters." },
  { id:"ability-fixer-b68", title:"Fixer", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"downtime, acquire, heat, prison", preview:"Better at acquiring assets, reducing heat, and surviving prison.", content:"During downtime, you get +1 result level on Acquire Asset and Reduce Heat rolls — turning partial successes into better outcomes and clean successes into excellent ones. When incarcerated, you take +1d to any real-time prison action rolls, or +2d to a prison time-skip roll, meaning you survive incarceration better than most and come out with something to show for it. The Fixer ability defines a Hound who is essentially a logistics specialist: someone who makes the crew's support infrastructure more reliable through sheer competence and a well-maintained network." },
  { id:"ability-in-too-deep-b68", title:"In Too Deep", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"in-too-deep, consort, bond, bonus, hound, b68, potency", preview:"Form an intimate bond with an NPC during a score for ongoing bonuses.", content:"Once per score, you can Consort with an NPC to form an intimate bond with them. This doesn't have to be romantic — it can be any deep personal connection established under pressure. If you already have such a bond with someone involved in the score, you get +1d and potency on any actions that involve dealing with them. The bond is lasting, not transient — it becomes a relationship in the fiction that the GM can pull on. This ability makes social connections mechanically powerful and creates compelling NPCs with real stakes attached to them." },
  { id:"ability-echo-pet-b68", title:"Echo Pet", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"echo-pet, pet, paranormal, companion, hound, b68, potency", preview:"Your animal companion is imbued with anomalous resonance abilities.", content:"Your pet (established in your character concept) has been touched by the resonance field and gained abilities beyond a normal animal. It gains potency when tracking or fighting paranormal entities, and you choose one paranormal ability for it: time-glitching (it occasionally phases briefly out of the present moment), mind-link (you share a telepathic connection), or mirror-field (it can create a brief illusory double of itself). Taking this ability again lets you choose an additional ability for your pet. Echo Pet creates a recurring character with supernatural utility, and its limitations (a pet is still vulnerable) keep it from being simply a bonus." },
  { id:"ability-dogged-persistence-b68", title:"Dogged Persistence", source:"B68", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"dogged-persistence, resist, exhaustion, push, hound, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use tenacity to resist mental fatigue or push through investigations.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your tenacity to either resist a consequence of exhaustion, mental harm, fear, confusion, or losing track of someone — or to push yourself when you're trying to influence someone or searching for clues. This is the Hound's version of a resilience ability, specifically flavored around the experience of tracking and investigation: the detective who keeps going when every lead seems dead, the hunter who doesn't break when the quarry is elusive. The twice-per-score limit keeps it meaningful rather than routine." },
  { id:"ability-automaton-b68", title:"Automaton", source:"B68", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"automaton, robot, drain, mechanics, hull, b68, stress", preview:"You are a soul powering a robotic body with built-in armor and no stress.", content:"This is the Hull's foundational ability, representing your nature as a robotic body rather than a flesh-and-blood person. You have built-in armor (this doesn't cost load), human-equivalent strength and senses by default, and your former human emotional life is almost entirely gone — you start with no Keys. You cannot take Stress; instead, you take Drain (a parallel resource representing power and mechanical wear). You can be repaired if damaged. You choose two frame features that define your body's specific capabilities. Automaton is what makes you fundamentally different from every other playbook — it's the gift and the cost of being a Hull." },
  { id:"ability-powerhouse-b68", title:"Powerhouse", source:"B68", page:"36", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"powerhouse, strength, push, extreme, hull, b68", preview:"Take 1 Drain to perform feats of extreme physical strength or speed.", content:"By spending 1 Drain, you can perform a feat of physical ability that would be impossible for a human: running faster than an autopod vehicle, tearing metal apart with your bare hands, lifting a weight that would require multiple people. This factors into effect — you're doing something genuinely beyond normal human capability, which means the GM gives you an appropriate effect level for it rather than ruling it impossible. Powerhouse is the Hull's license to occasionally do something spectacular and mechanical, at the cost of their power reserve." },
  { id:"ability-retractable-arsenal-b68", title:"Retractable Arsenal", source:"B68", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"retractable-arsenal, items, load, hidden, hull, b68", preview:"Carry +2 load of items hidden inside your frame.", content:"Your frame has internal storage — items built into your chassis that can retract beneath panels and be completely hidden from casual inspection. You gain +2 load capacity for items that can be stored internally, and those items are effectively invisible unless someone does a thorough physical search of your body. This is enormously useful for passing weapons checks, smuggling items into secure locations, or simply always having your tools on hand without advertising what they are. Combined with a Hull's already unusual appearance, Retractable Arsenal makes you a very effective carrier of hidden assets." },
  { id:"ability-energy-beam-b68", title:"Energy Beam", source:"B68", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"energy-beam, shock, barrier, weapon, hull, b68, electroplasm", preview:"Release stored energy as an electric shock or directed beam.", content:"You can discharge the electroplasmic energy in your frame as either a close-range shock (an arc around your body, useful against anyone in contact or nearby) or a directed beam at a specific target. You can also use this ability to create a lightning barrier — an arc of energy that repels or traps resonance entities, which is a capability most characters in B68 can't replicate easily. The cost is 1 Drain per magnitude level of the effect. Energy Beam gives the Hull a built-in combat option and an arcane utility that makes them surprisingly useful against paranormal threats." },
  { id:"ability-interface-b68", title:"Interface", source:"B68", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"interface, attune, control, network, hull, b68, ghost-field", preview:"Attune to the city's electroplasmic power grid to control connected systems.", content:"By attuning to the local electroplasmic power field (the grid that runs through all of Doskvol 68's infrastructure), you can interact with and influence anything connected to it — electrical systems, other hulls, networked devices. This is a broader version of what a Whisper does with the ghost field: the Hull's Interface is technological rather than arcane, but the scope is similar. You can turn systems on or off, receive data from connected devices, and in some cases control another Hull's actions if their defenses are down. Interface makes you a cyberpunk operative in a steampunk setting." },
  { id:"ability-frame-upgrade-b68", title:"Frame Upgrade", source:"B68", page:"36", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hull", tags:"frame-upgrade, upgrade, features, hull, b68, command, heat", preview:"Choose two additional frame features to expand your physical capabilities.", content:"Your frame gains two additional built-in features from the list: Advanced Visual Sensors (see in low light, detect heat signatures, enhanced detail), Lifelike Appearance (pass as a standard human on casual inspection), Hidden Compartment (additional internal storage), Smokescreen Emitter (release a concealing cloud on command), Surveillance Hardware (record and transmit audio/video), or Jet Propulsion (short bursts of powered flight or speed). Frame Upgrade lets you customize your Hull toward whatever role the crew needs — scout, spy, tank, transport — and makes each Hull mechanically distinct based on their configuration." },
  { id:"ability-unalloyed-genius-b68", title:"Unalloyed Genius", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"unalloyed-genius, crafting, invention, bonus, intellectual, b68", preview:"Get +1 result level when crafting inventions, which also start with a free tick.", content:"When you roll to craft an invention, you take +1 result level on the roll — a 4/5 becomes effectively a 6, a 6 becomes effectively a critical. Additionally, all invention clocks start with 1 segment already filled in, meaning you need one fewer successful roll to complete any project. This compounds over long crafting projects into significant time savings. Unalloyed Genius represents an Intellectual at the top of their field — someone for whom the basic technical problems others struggle with are simply already solved, leaving them free to attack the genuinely interesting parts of the problem." },
  { id:"ability-mentalist-b68", title:"Mentalist", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"mentalist, study, mind, bonus, intellectual, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Study someone to reveal their current intentions and a hidden desire.", content:"You can deduce trivial details about anyone through observation alone (dress, posture, micro-expressions). When you take time to Study a specific person, you learn two things: their current intentions in this moment, and a deep desire they're keeping secret or don't fully know they have yet. Once you have this information, you get +1d and potency when acting on it — making your social actions extremely precise. Mentalist turns the Intellectual into a formidable social operator despite not being a social specialist, because understanding someone completely is more useful than being charming." },
  { id:"ability-insomniac-b68", title:"High-Functioning Insomniac", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"high-functioning-insomniac, downtime, project, research, intellectual, b68, long-term-project", preview:"Get two free ticks to distribute among research-related project clocks in downtime.", content:"During the personal business phase, you get two free ticks to distribute among any long-term project clocks that involve research, investigation, or crafting. You don't need to spend a downtime action to get these ticks — they're free, on top of whatever actions you take. This represents the Intellectual who simply doesn't stop working: they're thinking about the problem in the background, filling pages with notes at 3 AM, running mental simulations on the walk to a meet. For an Intellectual with multiple active projects, these two free ticks add up to significant acceleration over the course of a campaign." },
  { id:"ability-dont-break-it-b68", title:"Try Not to Break It This Time", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"try-not-to-break-it-this-time, flashback, gadget, free, intellectual, b68, downtime", preview:"Flashback to providing a teammate with exactly the right gadget, for free.", content:"Any flashback that reveals you giving another crew member just the right gadget or tool before the score costs 0 Stress instead of the normal 1-2 Stress. You also gain one free downtime action to actually craft such a gadget — the flashback triggers its creation retroactively. This ability keeps the Intellectual in the center of operations even during scores where they're not physically present: other characters can flash back to 'oh, the Intellectual gave me a widget for this' at no cost to anyone. It rewards collaborative storytelling and makes the Intellectual feel like the crew's invisible preparation machine." },
  { id:"ability-researcher-b68", title:"Researcher", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"researcher, resist, fatigue, push, intellectual, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use research to resist fatigue or push yourself on technical challenges.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your research preparation to either resist a consequence of fatigue, weakness, or resonance effects — or to push yourself when you're working with technical skills or handling resonance objects. This is the Intellectual's resilience ability, flavored around preparation and methodical work rather than physical toughness: you're not pushing through pain, you're drawing on the fact that you already solved this problem in the lab. The twice-per-score limit keeps it significant, and the resonance object application makes you safer working with the paranormal materials your research often involves." },
  { id:"ability-anatomist-b68", title:"Anatomist", source:"B68", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"anatomist, healing, tinker, bonus, intellectual, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Treat wounds and study bodies with medical expertise.", content:"You can Tinker the human body as a medical practitioner — treating wounds in the field, stabilizing critically injured characters, or performing actual surgery given time and equipment. You can Study a sickness, a corpse, or a medical condition to understand it in detail. Beyond your own practice, everyone in your crew gets +1d to their healing treatment rolls, meaning your expertise makes the whole team more resilient to harm over the course of a campaign. Anatomist positions the Intellectual as the crew's medic and forensic specialist — someone who understands the body the same way they understand any other machine." },
  { id:"ability-encyclopedic-knowledge-b68", title:"Encyclopedic Knowledge", source:"B68", page:"45", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"encyclopedic-knowledge, push, exploit, distract, intellectual, b68, push-yourself", preview:"When you push yourself, instantly find a weakness or dazzle with intellect.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two additional things beyond the normal push benefits: instantly identify a weak point or exploitable pattern in any obstacle (a structural flaw, a logical inconsistency, a procedural gap in a security system), or dazzle an audience with a flood of information that leaves them genuinely confused and distracted for the moment. The first option supports tactical problem-solving with specific, actionable intelligence; the second is a social tool that creates openings without requiring a separate roll. Together, they define an Intellectual who can always find the angle if given a moment to think." },
  { id:"ability-advanced-sparkmind-b68", title:"Advanced Sparkmind", source:"B68", page:"45", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Intellectual", tags:"advanced-sparkmind, cohort, sparkmind, upgrade, intellectual, b68, assist", preview:"Upgrade your Sparkmind assistant with an additional type, edge, or fewer flaws.", content:"Your Sparkmind — the specialized AI-adjacent assistant device that is central to the Intellectual's playbook — gains an additional upgrade: either choose an additional type (adding a new area of capability), add an edge (an operational advantage), or remove a flaw (eliminating an existing limitation). Taking this ability multiple times continues improving the Sparkmind. This ability makes the Sparkmind a growing, customizable tool rather than a fixed asset, and rewards Intellectuals who invest in developing their assistant over the course of a campaign into a genuinely formidable specialized partner." },
  { id:"ability-clean-b68", title:"Clean", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"clean, resist, detection, push, operative, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use precision to resist detection or push athletic and stealth feats.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your professional precision to resist a consequence from detection or security measures — a camera that caught your face, an alarm you triggered, a guard who heard something — or to push yourself on a feat of athletics or stealth. This is the Operative's core resilience ability: where other characters might take harm or consequences, the Operative uses their training to stay clean. It's specifically about professional execution, not raw ability — you're not faster or stronger, you're just better at not making the mistakes that get people caught." },
  { id:"ability-double-agent-b68", title:"Double Agent", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"double-agent, faction, downtime, project, operative, b68, long-term-project", preview:"Maintain a second backing faction, with bonuses to influencing both.", content:"You gain a second backing faction immediately — a second institutional relationship that provides resources, cover, and protection (but also expectations and obligations). You get +2d when working on long-term projects to influence either of your backing factions. The Double Agent ability is a powerful expansion of your resource base, but it comes with the obvious complication that two factions both believe you're working for them, and the day those interests conflict is a very bad day. This ability rewards Operatives who want their character's double life to be mechanically represented and dramatically consequential." },
  { id:"ability-dead-drop-b68", title:"Dead Drop", source:"B68", page:"51", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"dead-drop, items, acquire, flashback, operative, b68, downtime", preview:"Have a bound spirit deliver items to you anywhere, for free.", content:"You have a bound resonance entity in your service that acts as a delivery system. It can leave up to 2 load worth of items at any location you specify, and the flashback to requesting this delivery is free (0 Stress). You can also flashback to an Acquire Asset roll for those items as a free downtime action. This means you can always have the right equipment in the right place — the key is hidden under the loose cobblestone, the weapons cache is behind the third locker in the bathhouse. Dead Drop makes the Operative feel genuinely prepared in a way that other characters' standard loadouts can't fully replicate." },
  { id:"ability-echo-walker-b68", title:"Echo Walker", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"echo-walker, teleport, ghost, stealth, operative, b68, stress", preview:"Step into the resonance field and reappear wherever you choose.", content:"By spending 2 Stress, you step into the resonance field and disappear entirely from the physical world. You reappear at a moment and location of your choice — wherever you could physically get to, whenever you want to surface. The only cost beyond the Stress is the cold: when you reappear, you take level 1 harm (you may resist this). Echo Walker is the Operative's most dramatic ability — it's essentially short-range teleportation with a timing element, and it's most powerful when used to bypass security that has no counter to simply not being present. The potential applications for infiltration, escape, and tactical positioning are significant." },
  { id:"ability-wetwork-b68", title:"Wetwork", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"wetwork, push, combat, speed, operative, b68, push-yourself", preview:"When you push yourself, make impossible shots or perform superhuman athletics.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two things beyond the normal push benefits: make an improbable shot at extreme distance or with extreme speed (a target moving at full sprint, a shot around a corner, a throw that defies reasonable physics), or perform an athletic feat that verges on superhuman (scaling a frictionless surface, covering ground faster than should be possible, a leap that clears something absurd). Wetwork is the Operative's combat and movement escalation — when precision alone isn't enough, you can dip briefly into something that looks more like a trained reflex than a human capability." },
  { id:"ability-cipher-b68", title:"Cipher", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"cipher, identity, disguise, bonus, operative, b68, long-term-project", preview:"Maintain a deep cover identity that provides bonuses and tactical surprise.", content:"You have a deep cover identity — a complete alternate persona with its own documentation, social connections, and history. When operating under this identity, you get +1d on rolls to deflect suspicion or confuse enemies about who you are. When you reveal your true identity at a key moment, the resulting shock gives you the initiative in the scene plus +1d and potency on your immediate actions. If the cover is blown, you can create a new one with a 4-segment long-term project. Cipher rewards patience: the longer you stay in cover, the more valuable the reveal becomes, and managing when to blow it is one of the ability's core tactical decisions." },
  { id:"ability-sleeper-agents-b68", title:"Sleeper Agents", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"sleeper-agents, npc, turn, surprise, operative, b68, stress", preview:"Once per score, reveal an NPC has been working for you all along.", content:"Once per score, you can spend 2 Stress and nominate any minor NPC present in the scene — they've been your agent this entire time, and they reveal it at the moment you choose. The guard who's been watching the door turns to face the other guards. The servant who's been bringing tea was listening to every conversation. This ability rewards retroactive planning: you can set it up by describing how you briefed this person before the score, or simply let the reveal be a surprise that the fiction then explains. Sleeper Agents is the Operative's most cinematic ability, and it changes the dynamics of any scene it appears in." },
  { id:"ability-control-b68", title:"Control", source:"B68", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Operative", tags:"control, group-action, leadership, crit, operative, b68, stress", preview:"Lead group actions with reduced stress cost and the possibility of multiple crits.", content:"Choose one of your action ratings. When you lead a Group Action using that action, you can suffer at most 1 Stress regardless of how many participants rolled poorly — the normal cost of 1 Stress per failed roll is capped. Additionally, when leading this action, multiple 6s from different participants count as a critical success. This ability makes the Operative an exceptional unit leader for their specialty action, reducing the stress cost of coordination and enabling the kind of synchronized, perfectly executed group operations that are the hallmark of professional intelligence work." },
  { id:"ability-third-eye-b68", title:"Third Eye Opened", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"third-eye-opened, ghost, sense, command, paranormalist, b68, attune", preview:"Always aware of nearby resonance entities — and can force them to obey.", content:"You have permanent passive awareness of any resonance entity in your vicinity — ghosts, echoes, bound spirits, and anomalous presences register to you without any roll or effort. Additionally, you can Attune to the resonance field to force a nearby entity to appear (if hidden) and obey a single command you give it. This is a stronger version of what most Whispers can attempt: you're not asking the entity, you're telling it. Third Eye Opened makes you the table's supernatural early warning system and gives you authority over entities that would simply ignore or terrify other characters." },
  { id:"ability-precognition-b68", title:"Precognition", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"precognition, assist, free, planning, paranormalist, b68, stress", preview:"Assist teammates twice per score for free by predicting what they'll need.", content:"Two times per score, you can assist a teammate without spending the usual 1 Stress. You tell the table how you anticipated this moment — how you prepared for it in advance, what you glimpsed in a vision or statistical model, why you had exactly what they needed ready. The mechanical effect is identical to standard Assist (+1d to their roll) but costs you nothing. Precognition rewards narrating your character as genuinely prescient rather than merely reactive, and it makes the Paranormalist a valuable support presence even when they're not taking primary actions." },
  { id:"ability-psychokinesis-b68", title:"Psychokinesis", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"psychokinesis, push, levitate, telekinesis, paranormalist, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Push yourself to levitate briefly or move objects with your mind.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two things beyond normal push benefits: levitate for a short time (not full flight, but enough to reach a second-floor window, cross a gap, or get above a crowd), or violently push or pull objects through the air using telekinetic force. The levitation application is primarily for movement and positioning; the telekinetic push is a combat and utility tool with significant environmental applications. Both are clearly anomalous and visible to observers, which means Psychokinesis tends to make scenes more complicated even when it's solving a problem." },
  { id:"ability-esp-b68", title:"Extrasensory Perception", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"extrasensory-perception, resist, ghost, push, paranormalist, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use sixth sense to resist paranormal consequences or push through supernatural challenges.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your extrasensory perception to resist a consequence from paranormal sources — a ghost's fear effect, a demon's influence, an anomalous effect that defies normal understanding — or to push yourself when dealing with paranormal forces. ESP is the Paranormalist's specialized resilience tool: where the Intellectual resists through preparation and the Operative through training, the Paranormalist resists through perceptive awareness that puts them one moment ahead of whatever the supernatural is doing. The twice-per-score limit means it's meaningful rather than routine." },
  { id:"ability-forbidden-science-b68", title:"Forbidden Science", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"forbidden-science, downtime, ritual, free, paranormalist, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Perform paranormal experiments during downtime, with one free action to do so.", content:"You can use a downtime action to conduct a paranormal experiment — performing a ritual, interfacing with a resonance anomaly, testing a theory about the ghost field — to manifest a specific supernatural effect or being. You also get one free downtime action dedicated to these experiments, meaning you can pursue your research without it cutting into your other downtime activities. Forbidden Science is the ability that makes the Paranormalist a researcher as well as an operator: they're not just using the paranormal, they're actively studying and pushing its boundaries in ways the Age of Consensus absolutely doesn't approve of." },
  { id:"ability-echo-projection-b68", title:"Echo Projection", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"echo-projection, form, energy, combat, paranormalist, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Spend 2 Stress to become a radiant being of crackling electroplasmic energy.", content:"By spending 2 Stress, you transform into a form of living electroplasm — a radiant, crackling figure of energy that counts as wearing armor and deals potency-enhanced physical attacks. While in this form, you can push yourself to shoot arcs of electroplasmic lightning. The projection lasts the scene (extend with 2 more Stress). When it drops, you take level 2 harm 'Drained' and the GM ticks a clock of their choice; you may resist these. Taking this ability a second time removes the GM clock tick. Echo Projection is the Paranormalist's most dramatic combat option — spectacular, effective, and costly in ways that compound over time." },
  { id:"ability-medium-b68", title:"Medium", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"medium, communicate, ghost, bonus, paranormalist, b68, paranormal", preview:"Communicate with all paranormal entities, with bonus dice for doing so.", content:"You can communicate with any paranormal entity — not just ghosts present in the physical realm, but entities in the resonance field, bound spirits, echoes of past events, and beings that other characters can't perceive at all. When you do, you take +1d and potency on the interaction. This makes you the table's universal paranormal translator, able to gather information, negotiate, and interact with the supernatural landscape of Doskvol in ways that bypass the usual barriers. Medium is especially valuable in investigations and during scores that intersect with ghost activity, where access to non-physical witnesses and allies is a significant advantage." },
  { id:"ability-parapsychology-b68", title:"Parapsychology", source:"B68", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Paranormalist", tags:"parapsychology, immune, terror, resist, paranormalist, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Immune to paranormal terror; bonuses to resist and gather paranormal information.", content:"Paranormal entities — ghosts, demons, anomalous manifestations — normally cause fear and paralysis in ordinary people on sight. You're immune to this effect: you've been exposed to enough of the supernatural that the automatic terror response simply doesn't trigger in you. Beyond immunity, you take +1d to resistance rolls with Resolve (making you better at resisting all Resolve-based consequences), and +1d when gathering information about paranormal subjects. Parapsychology makes you professionally competent in the most dangerous domain in Doskvol — the one that incapacitates everyone around you just becomes your working environment." },
  { id:"ability-true-believer-b68", title:"True Believer", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"true-believer, resist, law, push, radical, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use conviction to resist legal consequences or push ideological actions.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your conviction to resist a consequence from law-breaking — being arrested, hassled by Bluecoats, caught in a crackdown — or to push yourself when you're fighting directly for your ideology. Your belief system is literally a source of resilience: the Bluecoat who grabs your arm is an obstacle your conviction can push through, not an authority you're obligated to obey. This ability makes the Radical mechanically safer during actions that directly express their politics, reflecting the protective quality of genuine commitment to a cause when the consequences are the exact thing you expected going in." },
  { id:"ability-direct-action-b68", title:"Direct Action", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"direct-action, desperate, wreck, command, radical, b68, potency", preview:"Gain potency and scale on desperate Wreck and Command rolls.", content:"When you make a desperate roll with either Wreck or Command, you gain both potency and scale simultaneously — making your desperate actions not just dangerous gambles but overwhelming ones when they land. The book reminds you that you can always trade position for effect to make almost any action desperate if you choose to. This ability rewards the Radical's tendency toward bold, visible, high-risk direct action: the moment when you stop being cautious and commit to the confrontation, your presence becomes larger than what your crew's normal Tier would suggest." },
  { id:"ability-echo-chamber-b68", title:"Echo Chamber", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"echo-chamber, poetry, crowd, bonus, radical, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Recite poetry to draw a crowd and gain bonuses dealing with the paranormal.", content:"The resonance echoes of the oppressed and the desperate are drawn to your voice. When you loudly recite poetry in public, a crowd gathers to listen — if there are people around, they come. When you use poetry as a means to an end (to inspire, to distract, to incite), you take +1d and gain potency when dealing with paranormal elements. This ability positions the Radical as someone whose art literally resonates with the ghost field, making their political expression a form of arcane practice. The crowd-gathering effect alone makes it a powerful tool for creating diversions or opportunities, and the paranormal potency makes it unexpectedly useful in supernatural situations." },
  { id:"ability-fellow-travelers-b68", title:"Fellow Travelers", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"fellow-travelers, npc, sympathy, connection, radical, b68", preview:"In any crowd, at least one NPC is sympathetic to your cause.", content:"In any scene with more than one NPC, you can ask the GM which of them are sympathetic to your cause — and there is always at least one, often more. The GM answers honestly, identifying characters who share your political alignment or who could be persuaded by it. This ability doesn't give you automatic allies; it gives you information — which thread to pull, who to approach, where the potential support lies in any room you walk into. For a Radical who is building a movement rather than just pulling jobs, this ability provides an inexhaustible supply of starting points for recruitment, alliance, and coalition-building." },
  { id:"ability-polemicist-b68", title:"Polemicist", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"polemicist, push, crowd, shame, radical, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Push yourself to whip up a crowd or shame a powerful figure into silence.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two things beyond normal push benefits: whip a crowd into a righteous fury — turning a passive audience into an active, potentially riotous one — or shame a powerful figure so thoroughly and publicly that they fall silent or retreat. The first option is a force multiplier that creates chaos, opportunity, and heat in roughly equal measure; the second is a targeted social strike that removes a specific person from the equation. Both require the right audience and timing, which is exactly the kind of tactical awareness that distinguishes a skilled Polemicist from someone just shouting." },
  { id:"ability-praxis-b68", title:"Praxis", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"praxis, destroy, symbolic, downtime, radical, b68, long-term-project", preview:"Visibly destroy a symbolic target during a score for revolutionary project bonuses.", content:"If you loudly and visibly destroy a symbolic target during a score — a statue, a company sign, a piece of law-enforcement infrastructure, anything that carries ideological weight — you gain +2 result levels to any long-term project rolls related to your revolutionary work during the following personal business phase. Praxis is the ability that rewards aligning your score targets with your political message: the burglary that also sends a statement, the sabotage that's staged for maximum public impact. It connects the criminal work to the revolutionary project in a way that makes both more effective." },
  { id:"ability-pamphleteer-b68", title:"Pamphleteer", source:"B68", page:"68", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"pamphleteer, downtime, project, publish, radical, b68, long-term-project", preview:"Publish revolutionary works that permanently accelerate your political projects.", content:"You can complete a 4-segment long-term project to publish a revolutionary work — name it, describe what it argues. Once published, that work ticks a related long-term project clock once per downtime automatically, with no action required. You can have up to four works in active circulation simultaneously. If you die or are imprisoned, each work adds two ticks per downtime (martyrdom accelerates the movement). Pamphleteer creates a slow-building, compounding political infrastructure: each published work is a permanent investment in your character's legacy that continues working even when you can't." },
  { id:"ability-total-dedication-b68", title:"Total Dedication", source:"B68", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Radical", tags:"total-dedication, desperate, sacrifice, bonus, radical, b68, bonus-die", preview:"Accept -1d to resistance for +1d to a desperate action roll.", content:"When you roll a desperate action, you can choose to get +1d to your roll by also accepting -1d to any resistance rolls against consequences from that action. You're committing fully — going all-in on the action itself and accepting reduced protection from whatever happens as a result. Total Dedication is a risk amplifier: it makes desperate moments potentially more successful but significantly more costly when they go wrong. It captures the ideological character of the Radical perfectly — the willingness to pay any personal cost in pursuit of the goal, even when the math says that's not rational." },
  { id:"ability-here-goes-nothing-b68", title:"Here Goes Nothing", source:"B68", page:"74", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"here-goes-nothing, sway, consort, substitute, swinger, b68, flashback", preview:"Take 2 Stress to roll Sway or Consort instead of a different action.", content:"By spending 2 Stress, you can substitute your Sway or Consort rating for a completely different action — using your social skills where the fiction would normally call for something else. Need to make a Tinker roll but your social stats are better? Spend 2 Stress and describe how you talk someone through the lock. You use a free flashback to reveal who taught you this particular technique or approach, grounding the substitution in the fiction. Here Goes Nothing is the Swinger's license to be 'good with people' in a way that crosses action boundaries — they find the human angle in every problem." },
  { id:"ability-yeah-baby-b68", title:"Yeah, Baby", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"yeah-baby, npc, agree, xp, swinger, b68, stress", preview:"Say yes to an NPC's proposal to give the crew xp and clear your own stress.", content:"When you agree to an NPC's proposal — even when it complicates the crew's plans or pulls you in a problematic direction — everyone else on the crew immediately marks 1 xp, and you clear 3 Stress. The Swinger's enthusiasm for saying yes, even to things that create problems, generates progress for everyone and relief for themselves. This ability is a genuine incentive to let NPCs pull the story in directions you didn't plan, rewarding impulsive agreement over careful calculation. It also makes the Swinger the character whose relationships and impulses shape the campaign's direction in interesting ways." },
  { id:"ability-groove-machine-b68", title:"Groove Machine", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"groove-machine, dance, music, bonus, swinger, b68, potency", preview:"When acting on the dance floor or through dance, get +1d and potency.", content:"You always know where the nearest music is playing, and when you start dancing, others feel pulled to join. When you take action while moving through a dance floor or using dance as the medium of your action (distraction, seduction, navigation, even combat), you take +1d and potency. Groove Machine is delightfully specific and mechanically real: social scenes, infiltrations of parties and clubs, and any situation where music is present become significantly more favorable for you. It also creates a distinctive character signature — the Swinger who is unmistakably in their element the moment the music starts." },
  { id:"ability-improviser-b68", title:"Improviser", source:"B68", page:"75", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"improviser, push, disguise, unexpected, swinger, b68, push-yourself", preview:"When you push yourself, claim any identity or plunge into the unknown.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two things beyond normal push benefits: claim to be anyone and others will genuinely consider the possibility, no matter how outlandish the claim (the Prince of Iruvia, an inspector from the Ministry, a long-dead artist) — or plunge blindly in an unexpected direction and find a new path forward when the obvious routes are blocked. The first option is social escalation beyond normal deception; the second is an improvisational problem-solving tool that rewards the willingness to commit to an absurd solution. Together they define the Swinger as someone for whom 'it won't work' is just a starting point." },
  { id:"ability-always-hustling-b68", title:"Always Hustling", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"always-hustling, downtime, bank, free, swinger, b68", preview:"Every personal business phase, gain bank and give someone a free downtime action.", content:"Every personal business phase, you automatically mark +1 bank (from some side hustle that runs in the background), and you can give yourself or one other crew member +1 downtime action. What's the side hustle? Define it in the fiction — a part-time gig, a scam you're running, a deal you brokered while everyone else was sleeping. Always Hustling is a permanent passive income and action economy booster that compounds over the course of a campaign into significant advantage. It rewards players who want their character to be entrepreneurial and in constant motion between scores." },
  { id:"ability-party-animal-b68", title:"Party Animal", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"party-animal, vice, ally, assist, swinger, b68, downtime", preview:"Bring an ally along when you indulge vice — they lose the same stress you do, and owe you a favor.", content:"When you Indulge Vice, you can invite an ally to join you. They don't need to spend their own downtime action to benefit; they simply clear the same amount of Stress you do. Additionally, once during the next score, that ally can assist you once for free — the social bond from sharing the experience translates directly into in-play support. Party Animal makes vice indulgence a crew resource rather than a purely personal recovery mechanism, and it creates warm social ties between characters that have mechanical teeth. It rewards the Swinger who treats every indulgence as a shared experience rather than a solitary habit." },
  { id:"ability-echo-twin-b68", title:"Echo Twin", source:"B68", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"echo-twin, summon, ghost, clone, swinger, b68, stress", preview:"Spend 2 Stress to summon a ghostly version of yourself.", content:"There's an alternate version of you drifting in the resonance field — glitched, translucent, unstable. By spending 2 Stress, you can summon them for a few minutes. Each additional feature you want them to have costs 1 more Stress: lasting a full scene instead of minutes, appearing completely solid and stable (indistinguishable from the real you to casual observation), or obeying your instructions precisely. Echo Twin is a flexibility tool: a decoy, a distraction, a second you in two places at once, or a way to let someone else take a meeting while the real you is somewhere more important." },
  { id:"ability-smooth-b68", title:"Smooth", source:"B68", page:"76", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Swinger", tags:"smooth, resist, social, push, swinger, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use mojo to resist social faux pas or push social and driving actions.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your natural ease to resist a consequence of social suspicion or an embarrassing social mistake — or to push yourself when you're talking your way out of a tight spot or driving under pressure. Smooth is the Swinger's core resilience ability: they don't get rattled, they don't get flustered, and when everything is going sideways they find another gear. The driving application is a nice secondary use that reflects the Swinger's general comfort with fast-moving, high-pressure situations where most people freeze." },
  { id:"ability-military-discipline-b68", title:"Military Discipline", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"military-discipline, resist, combat, push, veteran, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Use training to resist combat harm or push yourself in a fight.", content:"Twice per score, you can invoke your military training to resist a consequence of physical harm from an attack in combat — your trained reflexes and body conditioning reducing the severity of what hits you — or to push yourself during a fight. This is the Veteran's primary resilience ability, and it's specifically combat-focused: the same training that got you through the worst battles of the war gets you through the worst moments of the underworld. The twice-per-score limit keeps it meaningful rather than making the Veteran invulnerable, and it pairs naturally with the armor the Veteran typically carries." },
  { id:"ability-got-your-back-b68", title:"Got Your Back", source:"B68", page:"82", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"got-your-back, protect, resist, bonus, veteran, b68, stress", preview:"Protecting a teammate clears stress and gives you bonus resistance dice.", content:"When you use the Protect teamwork maneuver for a teammate, you clear 1 Stress and take +1d to any resistance rolls you make against the consequences you take on their behalf. Protecting someone normally costs you (you absorb their consequence), but Got Your Back turns it into a genuinely efficient trade: you clear stress by doing it, and you're better at resisting the harm than they would have been. This ability defines the Veteran as a team player who is at their best keeping others alive — an institutional reflex from years of unit combat, now redirected toward keeping the crew functional." },
  { id:"ability-echo-fighter-b68", title:"Echo Fighter", source:"B68", page:"83", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"echo-fighter, combat, ghost, mind, veteran, b68, paranormal", preview:"Engage enemies in combat using your mind, with potency against the paranormal.", content:"Through specialized training in fighting methods that interface with the resonance field, you can engage enemies in combat with nothing but your mind — telekinetic strikes, resonance field manipulation as a physical force. You gain potency in combat against paranormal entities specifically (ghosts, demons, resonance anomalies). You can also attempt to read people's immediate combat intentions — not full mind-reading, but the tactical tell just before someone moves, speaks, or acts. Echo Fighter positions the Veteran as someone whose military service included paranormal combat training, making them effective against threats that conventional soldiers can't handle." },
  { id:"ability-leadership-b68", title:"Leadership", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"leadership, command, cohort, buff, veteran, b68, harm", preview:"Your cohorts fight harder and don't break when you Command them in combat.", content:"When you Command a cohort in combat, the normal rules for when they break down don't apply — they continue fighting even when they've taken level 3 harm, which would normally take them out of the engagement. Additionally, your commanding presence gives them increased effect and 1 armor while they're under your direct leadership. This is the Veteran's 'unit commander' ability: in direct combat with a gang cohort present, they dramatically increase the cohort's survivability and effectiveness. It rewards investment in cohorts as a resource and makes the Veteran the obvious choice to lead any operation that involves organized group violence." },
  { id:"ability-walking-arsenal-b68", title:"Walking Arsenal", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"walking-arsenal, load, weapons, extra, veteran, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Carry more weapons — always have an extra gun on hand, no matter what.", content:"Your load limit is always 2 higher than normal (meaning 5 load for a Quiet approach or 8 load for a Loud approach). You can pull out an additional 1-load firearm at any time, regardless of how many you've already used that scene. Each additional gun of the same type after the first costs 0 load. Walking Arsenal is the Veteran's expression of military preparedness: they are always carrying more than looks possible, always have a backup, and never run dry at the critical moment. In practical terms, it means the Veteran never has to choose between armor and weapons — they simply bring both." },
  { id:"ability-war-machine-b68", title:"War Machine", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"war-machine, push, combat, violence, veteran, b68, push-yourself", preview:"Push yourself to clear an area single-handedly or engage an impossible number of enemies.", content:"When you push yourself, you can do one of two things beyond normal push benefits: sweep and secure a large area completely, single-handedly and without pausing — or engage an improbable number of enemies simultaneously in a sustained engagement. The first option is a tactical utility that removes contested spaces from the equation; the second is pure combat escalation, the moment when the Veteran stops fighting people and starts processing them. War Machine is the ability that makes the Veteran the most dangerous direct combatant in Blades 68 — in the right situation, they become a force of nature rather than a person." },
  { id:"ability-get-back-in-there-b68", title:"Get Back In There", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"get-back-in-there, healing, clock, bonus, veteran, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Military modifications permanently reduce your healing clock and give you a bonus die.", content:"Your body was modified by experimental military procedures designed to keep soldiers operational longer: permanently fill in one segment of your healing clock (meaning you always start with 1 segment already filled, and need one fewer total to recover). You also take +1d to healing treatment rolls. This represents military-grade recovery augmentation — your body heals faster and more completely than an unaugmented person. Get Back In There is a background passive upgrade that becomes more valuable over long-running campaigns where harm accumulation is a real pressure, making the Veteran more durable over time than any other playbook." },
  { id:"ability-creative-community-b68", title:"Creative Community", source:"B68", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Veteran", tags:"creative-community, vice, friends, hobby, veteran, b68", preview:"Gain a second vice — a creative hobby that builds non-criminal relationships.", content:"You gain a second vice in the form of a creative hobby (define it: painting, music, cooking, martial arts as art form). When you indulge this vice by going to class or practice, you add +2 to the result, and you also create or develop a personal relationship — a classmate, a teacher, a fellow student. These relationships have no criminal utility, but they offer genuine human connection outside the underworld, and they might let you lay low at someone's apartment, get a ride in an emergency, or simply have one part of your life that isn't about violence and theft. Creative Community makes the Veteran's humanity a mechanical and narrative resource." },
  { id:"ability-versatile-b68", title:"Versatile", source:"B68", page:"15", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"versatile, any, flexible, general, b68", preview:"Take a special ability from any other playbook.", content:"Versatile is the B68 equivalent of the Core game's veteran advance — it lets you take a special ability from outside your own playbook, pulling in something that fits your character concept better than anything in your standard list. This could be a Veteran taking Cipher from the Operative because their character is a former intelligence soldier, or a Swinger taking Leadership because they've built up genuine authority over their crew's gang. Versatile is a signal that the playbook system is a starting point, not a cage, and it rewards players who have a clear vision of what their character is becoming that crosses playbook lines." },
  { id:"item-silenced-shooter-b68", title:"Silenced Shooter", source:"B68", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"ranged, firearm, stealth, silenced, prowl, hunt, b68, item", preview:"A semi-automatic handgun with a suppressor — quiet and reliable.", content:"A semi-automatic handgun of modest caliber fitted with a sound suppressor, making it 'quiet as a whisper' in the language of the book. Where the Core pistol is a single-shot, slow-loading statement of violence, the Silenced Shooter is the professional tool: faster reload, lower profile, and designed for use in places where noise is the most dangerous consequence. The 1-load weight makes it easy to carry concealed. It doesn't hit as hard as a large weapon, but for jobs where being heard is as bad as missing, it's the correct choice." },
  { id:"item-electro-blade-b68", title:"Electro-Blade", source:"B68", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"melee, heavy, shock, electrical, skirmish, electroplasm, b68, item", preview:"A heavy blade charged with electroplasmic energy.", content:"A broad, substantial blade with a built-in plasmoleum-powered electroplasmic emitter that charges the cutting edge. In practical terms, it's a heavy melee weapon that also delivers an electric shock on contact — effective against armored targets (the shock bypasses physical armor in ways a purely mechanical blow might not), against paranormal entities that are vulnerable to electroplasm, and as a general escalation over a mundane blade. The power pack requires maintenance and is vulnerable to damage, but for crews operating in Doskvol 68's more technologically advanced setting, it's a natural upgrade from an ordinary sword." },
  { id:"item-armor-b68", title:"Armor", source:"B68", page:"19", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"defense, resistance, bulky, load-2, b68, item, protection", preview:"Heavy-duty modern armor — maximum protection at maximum bulk.", content:"B68 armor is modern, industrial-grade protection: layers of impact-resistant composite fabric over rigid plate at the critical points. It's significantly more protective than the leather armor of the Core game but dramatically heavier — 3 load, which is a substantial portion of most characters' load capacity. In a setting where firearms are more common and more powerful than the Core game's pistols, this level of protection matters more, but the tradeoff of restricted mobility and reduced loadout capacity means it's not a casual choice. Works with the B68 armor rules (automatic reduction, option to total it)." },
  { id:"item-arclighter-b68", title:"Arclighter", source:"B68", page:"21", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"arclighter, light, tool, plasmoleum, electroplasm, b68, item, load-1", preview:"A multi-function tool: lighter, torch, or precision energy source.", content:"The Arclighter is a compact, 1-load handheld tool that runs on a small plasmoleum reservoir. At its simplest, it works as a lighter — a thumb flick produces a small arc of energy. Adjust the dial and it becomes a steady beam of light useful for navigating dark spaces, reading documents, or illuminating a lock without pulling out a full lantern. The same arc can be used as a welding tool, a precision cutting implement, or (at a stretch) a very short-range weapon of last resort. It's a versatile utility tool that rewards creative problem-solving and is small enough to always be on your person." },
  { id:"crew-militants-68", title:"Militants", source:"B68", page:"116", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"militants, crew, revolutionary, activist, political, b68, agitation, resistance", preview:"A crew of political activists who use direct action to challenge power.", content:"The Militants are a politically motivated crew — revolutionary, activist, and committed to changing the power structures of Doskvol 68 through organized action. Their operations blend direct sabotage, community organizing, propaganda, and violence when necessary, all in service of a specific political agenda. Their upgrades and special moves reflect this hybrid identity: they're effective at operations that have clear political targets and can build genuine popular support in ways that purely criminal crews can't. Play Militants when you want the crew's work to be embedded in a larger political struggle, where every score is also a message." },
  { id:"crew-utopians-68", title:"Utopians", source:"B68", page:"140", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"utopians, crew, cult, esoteric, paranormal, b68, ideology, belief, collective", preview:"A crew organized around an esoteric belief system and paranormal truth.", content:"The Utopians are a crew built around a shared vision — esoteric, paranormal, or ideological — that most people would call a cult. They believe in something that the Age of Consensus dismisses as impossible, and they're willing to do criminal, dangerous, and morally complex work in service of that belief. Their operations often involve acquiring paranormal resources, performing rituals, and building the infrastructure of their belief system. Play Utopians when you want the crew's motivations to be genuinely transcendent — something bigger than profit, more compelling than security, and more dangerous than either." },
  { id:"world-bluetime-68", title:"Bluetime", source:"B68", page:"2", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"bluetime, daylight, blue-array, tourists, general, b68", preview:"The brief daily window of artificial daylight created by the B.L.U.E. Array.", content:"In Blades 68, Doskvol's eternal night is punctuated by Bluetime — a period each day when the city's B.L.U.E. Array activates and 'tunes' the Bubble's electromagnetic field to produce blue skies and artificial daylight. It's not real sunlight, but it's close enough that people plan their days around it. Tourism, commerce, and outdoor life peak during Bluetime; criminal operations that depend on darkness avoid it. The specifics of when Bluetime occurs and how long it lasts can vary, making it a dynamic element that the GM can use to add urgency or texture to the schedule of a score." },
  { id:"world-the-bubble-68", title:"The Bubble", source:"B68", page:"11", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"the-bubble, force-field, protection, deathlands, general, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"The massive energy field that keeps Doskvol alive against the deathlands.", content:"The Bubble is the city's most fundamental infrastructure — a vast electroplasmic force field that separates Doskvol from the deathlands, the reality-warping horror outside. Without the Bubble, the city would be exposed to whatever exists in the deathlands: undead, paranormal phenomena, environmental hazards that human life can't survive. The Bubble is maintained by the same electroplasmic infrastructure that the leviathan trade supplies. In Blades 68, the Bubble has additional properties: it can be 'tuned' (producing Bluetime), it has weak points that Mirror House and other factions study, and the politics of who controls its maintenance is a source of real power in the city." },
  { id:"world-consensus-68", title:"Age of Consensus", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"age-of-consensus, science, rationality, conformity, general, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"The current era of scientific rationalism — and active suppression of the paranormal.", content:"The Age of Consensus is the cultural-political framework that Blades 68 operates within. After centuries of fear and chaos driven by the supernatural, society has organized itself around a consensus: science explains the world, progress is the goal, and the paranormal is superstition. Officially, ghosts don't exist. Anomalies are psychological phenomena or industrial accidents. The Paranormalist's entire career is a direct challenge to this framework. The Consensus isn't neutral — it's enforced by institutions, education systems, and the social cost of being labeled a 'fringe believer.' This creates the core tension between the setting's obvious supernatural reality and the dominant cultural denial of it." },
  { id:"world-death-radar-68", title:"Death Radar", source:"B68", page:"109", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"death-radar, paranormal, detection, section-6, general, b68, electroplasm", preview:"A city-wide detection system that triggers klaxons whenever someone is killed.", content:"The Death Radar is one of Doskvol 68's most distinctive setting elements: a system operated from Section 6 Central that uses the city's electroplasmic infrastructure to detect the moment a person dies and triggers a klaxon response. From Section 6's perspective, this is a law enforcement tool — they can respond quickly to murders. From a Hit Squad's perspective, it's the primary technical obstacle to their work. Every kill the crew makes has an immediate institutional response, which forces crews to think about how to operate under constant detection pressure. Managing the Death Radar — misdirection, timing, finding its blind spots — is a recurring tactical element for violent crews." },
  { id:"rule-trouble-engine-68", title:"Trouble Engine", source:"B68", page:"197", category:"Storyteller", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"trouble-engine, entanglements, heat, fallout, b68, pressure, consequence, escalation", preview:"A GM system for generating narrative complications from the crew's heat and wanted level.", content:"The Trouble Engine is the B68 equivalent of the Core game's Entanglements table — a structured GM tool for generating specific narrative complications between sessions based on the crew's accumulated Heat and Wanted Level. Rather than rolling on a single table, the Trouble Engine uses a more detailed system that generates 'Troubles' — ongoing situations that interrupt, complicate, or transform the crew's current business. Troubles have escalation tracks (they get worse if ignored) and can be resolved through score-like operations. The Engine ensures that the consequences of past actions keep reverberating forward, making Doskvol feel like a city with a memory." },
  { id:"rule-stacks-68", title:"Stacks", source:"B68", page:"158", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"stacks, currency, wealth, cash, b68, money, advancement, retirement", preview:"The B68 unit of significant liquid wealth — equivalent to the Core game's Coin.", content:"Stacks are the liquid wealth currency in Blades 68, replacing the Core game's Coin for significant transactions. A Stack represents a meaningful amount of money — enough that ordinary people notice and remember when it changes hands. Like Coin, Stacks are abstracted: they don't represent a specific denomination but a weight of economic significance. They're used to pay for acquisitions, bribes, Tier advancement, and crew operations. They're vulnerable — Stacks can be seized in a raid, stolen by rivals, or spent in overindulgence — which distinguishes them from Bank, the secure long-term savings layer." },
  { id:"rule-bank-68", title:"The Bank", source:"B68", page:"158", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"bank, storage, savings, downtime, b68, wealth, stacks, accumulation", preview:"Secure long-term savings — the B68 equivalent of the Core game's Stash.", content:"The Bank is where characters put money they don't want to risk losing — a combination of physical hiding places, legitimate financial accounts, underworld banking relationships, and investment vehicles. Like the Core game's Stash, your Bank total determines the quality of your retirement (or your legacy if you're killed): a character who retires with a full Bank lives well, one with an empty Bank limps out of the underworld broke. Unlike Stacks, Bank is not immediately accessible for spending during a score, which means building it up requires deliberately choosing long-term security over short-term utility." },
  { id:"rule-deadlock-68", title:"Deadlock", source:"B68", page:"154", category:"Player", subcategory:"Rules", "sub-subcategory":"Mechanics", tags:"deadlock, consequence, stress, stalemate, locked, narrative, advancement, b68", preview:"When you're completely stuck — a formal state of narrative impasse.", content:"Deadlock is a specific consequence type in Blades 68 for situations where a PC is blocked from their current approach in a way that can't be immediately resolved. It's not a failure in the conventional sense — it's the fiction reaching a point where the current plan simply cannot continue without a fundamental change in approach, resources, or circumstances. A Deadlock forces a scene shift or a renegotiation of the situation: the crew needs to find another angle, bring in a resource they don't currently have, or accept that this particular path is closed until conditions change. It's a tool for keeping the game moving when a hard stop is more dramatically interesting than continued escalation." },
  { id:"heritage-akoros-68", title:"Akoros", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"akoros, b68, city, empire, diverse, doskvol, imperial, mainland", preview:"The dominant cultural core of the Imperium — diverse, industrial, and politically complex.", content:"In Blades 68, Akoros is the Imperium, functionally — the other territories are either dependencies or adversaries, and Doskvol is its greatest city. Akorosi heritage means you grew up in the heart of the dominant power: diverse in culture (the city draws immigrants from everywhere), industrialized beyond any other territory, and deeply embedded in the political and economic systems that run the world. Akorosi characters navigate Doskvol with the ease of people who belong there by default — and carry the complicated weight of belonging to an empire that other heritages have reason to resent." },
  { id:"heritage-dagger-isles-68", title:"The Dagger Isles", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"dagger-isles, b68, archipelago, banyans, proxy-wars, pirates, traders", preview:"A tropical archipelago of small nation-states caught between imperial proxy wars.", content:"In Blades 68, the Dagger Isles are a collection of small independent states (called banyans) that have been used as the battlefield for proxy wars between the Imperium and the USC for decades. Some banyans have been effectively turned into puppet regimes; others maintain genuine independence through determined resistance. Characters from the Dagger Isles carry the political complexity of their home: awareness of how great powers use smaller ones, experience of conflict that isn't theirs by origin, and often a deep suspicion of anyone who claims to be helping." },
  { id:"heritage-iruvia-68", title:"Iruvia", source:"B68", page:"13", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"iruvia, b68, desert, isolationist, world-power, wealthy, foreign", preview:"A major world power that fought its way to independence and now keeps its distance.", content:"Iruvia was the first nation to successfully break from the Imperium, and it paid for that independence in blood — the Null Zone that destroyed both South Point and Bright Harbor was the final cost of the secession war. Since then, Iruvia has entered a deliberate isolationism: allowing limited trade through specific ports, refusing broader entanglement with either the Imperium or the USC, and working through the Dagger Isles as intermediaries when it needs to engage the outside world. Iruvian characters in Doskvol carry the weight of representing a nation that would prefer not to be involved." },
  { id:"heritage-severos-68", title:"Severos", source:"B68", page:"13", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"severos, b68, plains, protectorate, egalitarianism, nomadic, free", preview:"A formally 'independent' protectorate where Akorosi influence runs very deep.", content:"Severos is technically an independent protectorate in Blades 68 — it was the first to join the Imperium willingly and has nominally governed itself since. In practice, Akorosi corporations extract its resources, Akorosi schools shape its elite, and Akorosi interests define its policy. The population knows it: there is a strong movement for radical egalitarianism and economic redistribution, particularly in the south, that Blades 68's political atmosphere makes directly relevant. Severosi characters from the south often carry a political awareness and class consciousness that resonates with the Radical playbook, even if their character isn't one." },
  { id:"heritage-tycheros-68", title:"Tycheros", source:"B68", page:"13", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"tycheros, b68, void-gate, visitors, alien, supernatural, strange", preview:"A distant territory connected by a Void Gate, whose people are called 'Visitors'.", content:"In Blades 68, Tycheros is connected to the rest of the Shattered Isles by a Void Gate — a portal technology that allows rail lines to pass through the resonance field. Tycherosi who travel to Doskvol are called 'Visitors' with a dismissive edge that implies they don't quite belong. The old mythology of demon blood has been officially retired by the Age of Consensus — it's superstition now — but the social reality of Tycherosi in Doskvol still involves being treated with something between fascination and hostility. If you choose this heritage, you create an alien telltale: something about you that doesn't read as entirely human to observers." },
  { id:"heritage-usc-68", title:"The United Skov Covenant", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"usc, b68, skovlan, independence, world-power, war, resistance", preview:"The independent Skovlander nation-state, now a genuine world power.", content:"In Blades 68, Skovlan achieved its independence — the USC (United Skov Covenant) exists as a recognized world power and a direct geopolitical rival to Akoros. That doesn't mean the history is clean: centuries of colonization, the specific trauma of leviathan blood processing (which affected generations of workers), and the ongoing competition with Akoros all shape what being Skovlander means. Characters from the USC in Doskvol might be immigrants, traders, diplomats, or simply people who left — and they bring with them the specific psychological and political legacy of a people who fought their way to recognition." },
  { id:"background-learned-68", title:"Learned", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"professor, student, journalist, priest", preview:"An academic, journalist, religious figure, or other knowledge professional.", content:"Your character's past life was organized around knowledge and its communication — as a professor or student at Doskvol Academy or Charterhall University, a journalist navigating the city's complicated press landscape, a priest of an official or unofficial religion, a librarian, or an experimental psychologist. Learned background gives you access to institutions, academic contacts, and the specific social credibility (or dismissal) that comes with being visibly educated. In a city where the official ideology is rational consensus, Learned characters often find themselves in interesting tension between their training and what they've seen with their own eyes." },
  { id:"background-underworld-68", title:"Underworld", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"underworld, street-kid, gang, hustler, b68, criminal, contacts", preview:"A street kid, gang member, dealer, or fence — you grew up in the game.", content:"You've been in the underworld your whole life, in whatever form it takes in Doskvol 68: street kid who survived by wit, gang member who learned the codes early, pickpocket, hustler, cultist, small-time dealer, or fence who moved other people's stolen goods. This background gives you deep roots in the criminal ecology of the city — you know the territories, the players, and the rules that don't get written down. You also carry the specific weight of someone who never had the option of a different path, which shapes motivation in ways that characters with other backgrounds often don't understand." },
  { id:"background-performer-68", title:"Performer", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"artist, musician, dancer, model", preview:"An artist, musician, dancer, filmmaker, or stage performer.", content:"Your past was shaped by creative performance — as an artist, poet, lounge singer, racing driver (performance of a different kind), painter, guitarist, filmmaker, dancer, model, experimental sound artist, stage magician, or playwright. Performer background gives you visibility, contacts in the arts and entertainment world, and a natural cover for moving through social spaces that might otherwise close to someone with no legitimate reason to be there. It also gives the GM hooks: past collaborators, critics, fans, and the complicated financial reality of creative life in a city that doesn't particularly value art unless it makes money." },
  { id:"background-trade-68", title:"Trade", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"trade, sparktech, mechanic, salesperson, b68, commerce, technical", preview:"A technical worker, mechanic, shop owner, or skilled tradesperson.", content:"Your past was hands-on: sparktech (someone who works with electroplasmic technology), plumber, autopod mechanic, record shop owner, tattooist, salesperson, street vendor, projectionist at a movie house. Trade background gives you technical competence, connections in the working economy of the city, and familiarity with the infrastructure that keeps Doskvol running. Characters with Trade background often have the most practical, grounded read on how the city actually functions day to day, which translates into useful knowledge about security systems, service entrances, and the people who maintain the things criminals want to steal." },
  { id:"background-professional-68", title:"Professional", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"lawyer, clerk, accountant, architect", preview:"A white-collar worker — lawyer, accountant, architect, or civil servant.", content:"Your past was in the legitimate professional class: lawyer, office clerk, accountant, architect, terminal programmer, advertising executive, claims adjuster, civil servant, or PR agent. Professional background gives you access to institutional knowledge, legal and financial literacy, and connections in the legitimate economy that can be enormously useful when you need to make criminal operations look legitimate. It also means you know how the bureaucratic systems work — which forms matter, which officials can be approached, and how to navigate the paperwork side of Doskvol 68's more complex legal and financial environment." },
  { id:"background-aristocrat-68", title:"Aristocrat", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"aristocrat, old-money, nobility, socialite, b68, influence, privilege", preview:"Old money, new money, or the social performance of wealth.", content:"Your background placed you in or adjacent to the upper social strata — old noble money, newer industrial wealth with social aspirations, a dilettante with a family name, the scion of a house that's been declining for two generations, or simply a skilled enough socialite to have moved in those circles convincingly. Aristocrat background gives you access to high society, the contacts that come with it, and the specific skills of navigating spaces where the rules are implicit and the wrong choice closes doors permanently. The flip side: the higher you were, the further you fell to end up here, and that history shapes your character." },
  { id:"background-military-68", title:"Military", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"soldier, officer, mercenary, spy", preview:"A soldier, officer, intelligence operative, or military specialist.", content:"Your past was in military service — as a soldier (Imperial or USC), an officer, a mercenary, an intelligence operative, a battlefield strategist, a radar operator, a combat medic, an R&D scientist working on military applications, or an engineer building the weapons and vehicles. Military background gives you discipline, tactical thinking, connections to veterans (Doskvol 68 is full of them), and a specific experience of violence that is different from street-criminal violence in important ways. Characters with military background understand organized force, chain of command, and the particular moral weight of being trained and directed to kill." },
  { id:"background-labor-68", title:"Labor", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"factory, janitor, dock-worker, cab-driver", preview:"A working-class laborer — factory hand, dock worker, service worker.", content:"You worked for your living, in the most direct sense: factory worker, janitor, dock worker, cab driver, bellhop, waiter, short-order cook, farmhand, or garbage collector. Labor background puts you in the bottom economic tier of Doskvol 68's society — the people who keep everything running and receive the least from it. In a setting with explicit class politics (the Radical playbook, the USC's egalitarian politics, the Burn Corps' defense of Severosi workers), Labor background carries genuine ideological weight. You know what exploitation looks like from the receiving end, and that knowledge shapes how you read every power dynamic you encounter." },
  { id:"vice-faith-68", title:"Faith", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"faith, church, cult, types, b68, paranormal", preview:"Devotion to a church, a new age cult, or a spiritual practice.", content:"In Doskvol 68's Age of Consensus, public religious practice is often dismissed as superstition — but that doesn't stop people from finding meaning in it. Faith as a vice covers dedication to an official church (which exists in tension with the official scientific rationalism), a new age cult that blends spiritual practice with post-Cataclysm paranormal phenomena, or a personal spiritual discipline. Your purveyor is whoever facilitates your practice: a priest, a cult leader, a meditation teacher, a spiritual advisor. Faith often intersects uncomfortably with the Paranormalist's work in this setting, where the line between 'superstition' and 'empirical paranormal phenomena' is genuinely blurry." },
  { id:"vice-gambling-68", title:"Gambling", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"gambling, games, sports-betting, casinos, types, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"The need to test your luck — games of chance, sports betting, casino nights.", content:"Doskvol 68 has expanded entertainment infrastructure compared to the Core setting: established casinos, professional sports with betting markets, games of chance from high-end establishments to back-room card tables. Gambling as a vice in this setting means you're drawn to the specific thrill of risk with financial stakes — the moment of pure uncertainty that everything else in the underworld actually has less of, because experience and preparation reduce unpredictability. Your purveyor might be a casino owner, a bookmaker, or the runner of a private card game who always has a seat waiting. Overindulgence means the money goes somewhere it shouldn't." },
  { id:"vice-luxury-68", title:"Luxury", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"luxury, expensive, opulence, types, b68, xp-trigger", preview:"Expensive, ostentatious indulgence as self-care.", content:"The Doskvol 68 version of Luxury vice reflects the setting's expanded consumer culture: fine clothing from exclusive designers, rare gourmet experiences, the most expensive suites in the city's hotels, art acquisitions, or simply any context where money is spent conspicuously enough to announce status. Your purveyor is whoever provides the specific form your luxury takes — a tailor, a sommelier, an art dealer, a concierge who knows your preferences. Luxury creates interesting friction in a city with explicit class politics: spending freely on personal opulence reads differently to a crew with Labor or Underworld backgrounds than to one composed of Aristocrats." },
  { id:"vice-pleasure-68", title:"Pleasure", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"lovers, food, drink, drugs, art", preview:"Sensory indulgence in any form — lovers, food, drink, drugs, or beautiful things.", content:"Pleasure as a vice in Blades 68 covers the full range of sensory indulgence: lovers, gourmet food, carefully selected intoxicants (Doskvol 68 has a more developed drug culture than the Core setting), fine art, music — anything that engages the senses intensely enough to crowd out the stress of criminal life. Your purveyor is a specific person or place that provides the form your pleasure takes. This is one of the most flexible vices to play, because 'pleasure' is broad enough to encompass almost any specific indulgence, but the requirement for a specific purveyor NPC keeps it grounded in relationships." },
  { id:"vice-obligation-68", title:"Obligation", source:"B68", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"obligation, family, cause, charity, types, b68", preview:"A responsibility — family, cause, organization, or debt — that you can't put down.", content:"In Blades 68's more politically charged setting, Obligation vice can take on additional dimensions: the family you're supporting financially, the political cause you're contributing to, the community organization you fund, the debt of honor to someone who saved your life. Your purveyor is whoever or whatever receives your attention and resources. Obligation is the most dramatically productive vice in the list — it creates specific, named relationships that matter, pulls your character away from crew interests at inconvenient times, and provides the GM with leverage that is entirely legitimate because your character chose it." },
  { id:"vice-gettin-fucked-up-68", title:"Gettin' Fucked Up", source:"B68", page:"27", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"gettin-fucked-up, drugs, alcohol, fighting, types, b68", preview:"Oblivion — in substances, alcohol, or the brutal simplicity of a fighting pit.", content:"This vice is exactly what it says: the pursuit of complete sensory and mental obliteration, in whatever form your character finds most effective. Drugs (Doskvol 68 has a variety), alcohol in quantities designed to stop thought rather than enhance it, or the specific blank-minded simplicity of getting beaten in a fighting pit until nothing complicated remains. Your purveyor is whoever supplies the method: a dealer, a bar owner who keeps the back booth reserved, a pit-fight organizer. This is the most self-destructive vice in the B68 list, and overindulgence consequences here tend to be vivid — you surface damaged, broke, and sometimes missing hours." },
  { id:"vice-weird-68", title:"Weird", source:"B68", page:"27", category:"Player", subcategory:"Vice", "sub-subcategory":"Types", tags:"weird, fringe-science, strange-entities, rituals, types, b68, stress", preview:"Fringe science, paranormal contact, and bizarre rituals as stress relief.", content:"In an era of official scientific consensus, Weird vice carries extra cultural weight: you're not just indulging in something unusual, you're actively participating in things the dominant culture calls nonsense or dangerous. Your stress relief comes from experimenting with fringe science (the kind Mirror House publishes unofficially), consorting with strange resonance entities, observing bizarre rituals or taboos, or pursuing esoteric practices that blur the line between science and occultism. Your purveyor might be a fringe scientist, a spirit medium, an underground occultist, or the entity itself. Weird connects naturally to the Paranormalist playbook but is available to any character whose relationship with the unexplained is personal." },
  { id:"rule-stress-core", title:"Stress", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"stress, trauma, harm, resistance, push yourself", preview:"A resource you spend to power heroic efforts — and a measure of how close you are to breaking.", content:"Stress is your character's reserve of mental and physical grit, rated from 0 to 9. You spend Stress to push yourself (gain +1d or special effect for 2 Stress), accept a Devil's Bargain, and fuel certain special abilities. Stress accumulates when you resist consequences (rolling your Attribute dice and marking Stress equal to 6 minus your highest die). If you ever need to mark your 10th point of Stress, you suffer a Trauma instead and your Stress resets to 0. Each Trauma imposes a lasting personality shift (Cold, Haunted, Obsessed, Paranoid, Reckless, Soft, Unstable, or Vicious) and also counts as a debility. At 4 Traumas, your character retires from play. Stress recovers during downtime via the Recover action or indulging your Vice. Managing Stress is the central survival challenge of every score — pushing too hard without relief will break even the toughest scoundrel." },
  { id:"rule-push-yourself-core", title:"Pushing Yourself", source:"BitD Core", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"stress, push yourself, bonus dice, special action", preview:"Spend 2 Stress to add +1d to your roll or unlock a special feat of strength.", content:"When you Push Yourself, you spend 2 Stress to gain one of the following benefits: add +1d to your action roll, negate a penalty die, perform a feat of exceptional physical effort (breaking down a door, carrying an impossible load), or activate certain special abilities that require it. You can only push yourself once per roll — you can't stack multiple pushes. Pushing yourself is a conscious choice made before you roll, and stacks with other bonuses like assistance or Setup actions. It is the primary way scoundrels exceed their normal limits mid-score, making it a key resource-management decision. Many special abilities also require or are enhanced by a Push, creating synergy between your character build and your moment-to-moment Stress expenditure." },
  { id:"rule-flashback-core", title:"Flashback", source:"BitD Core", page:"20", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"flashback, planning, retroactive, stress", preview:"Declare a preparation you made before the score — retroactively inserting it into the story now.", content:"At any point during a score, any player can call for a Flashback to establish something their character did before the current moment. This replaces lengthy up-front planning — instead of planning every detail at the start, you improvise needs as they arise and fill them in retroactively via flashbacks. The GM sets a Stress cost (0 for simple plausible prep, 1 for moderate effort, 2 for significant exertion) and may call for an action roll if the outcome is uncertain. Flashbacks must be plausible — you can't use a flashback to have done something impossible or to escape a consequence you've already accepted. They're ideal for: stashing a weapon somewhere, bribing a guard the night before, arranging a safe house, or researching a mark's schedule. The mechanic keeps the game moving while rewarding creative players who notice the prep they need in the moment." },
  { id:"rule-devils-bargain-core", title:"Devil's Bargain", source:"BitD Core", page:"20", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"devil's bargain, complication, bonus die, consequence", preview:"Accept a guaranteed complication in exchange for an extra die on your roll.", content:"Before an action roll, the GM (or another player) may offer a Devil's Bargain: you get +1d to the roll, but something bad happens regardless of the outcome. Bargains are narrative complications tied to the fiction — your weapon breaks, you attract unwanted attention, you betray someone's trust, you take collateral damage. You can always refuse a Devil's Bargain — it's never forced. If you accept, the +1d is added and the complication occurs no matter how well you roll. Multiple bargains can be offered (by different players or the GM), but you can only accept one per roll. Devil's Bargains are a key creative tool: they escalate tension, create story complications that matter, and let players opt into trouble for mechanical advantage. They also reward GMs for offering interesting, story-rich consequences rather than arbitrary ones." },
  { id:"rule-load-core", title:"Load", source:"BitD Core", page:"20", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"load, equipment, items, light medium heavy", preview:"Choose how much gear you carry — trading mobility and subtlety for capability.", content:"Before each score, each PC chooses their Load: Light (3 items), Normal (5 items), or Heavy (6 items). Load affects fiction — a character in Light load can pass as a normal citizen; Heavy load means you are visibly armed and armored, causing social and stealth penalties. Items are selected from your character sheet's equipment list. You don't need to specify exactly what you take until you reach into your kit mid-score — at that point, you reveal one of your carried items. Items include weapons, tools, armor, and special gear. Some items have special rules (armor absorbs a consequence once, fine items grant +1 effect). The key tension is between operational capability (more items = more options) and approach (lighter = less scrutiny). Load is a pre-score decision that shapes your character's entire engagement style for that score." },
  { id:"rule-planning-core", title:"Planning & Engagement", source:"BitD Core", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"planning, engagement, plan type, detail, approach", preview:"Choose an approach and one key detail — then cut straight to the action.", content:"Rather than mapping out every step of a heist in advance, Blades uses the Planning and Engagement roll. The crew selects a Plan Type (Assault, Deception, Stealth, Occult, Social, or Transport) and nominates one Detail — a specific piece of preparation or information that anchors the approach. The GM then sets the initial position for the engagement roll (usually Controlled, Risky, or Desperate based on the plan's quality and the crew's reputation/intel). The crew makes an Engagement Roll (a fortune roll) using the plan type's linked action rating to determine how cleanly the score begins. A 6 means you're in a strong position; 4-5 means complications arise at the start; 1-3 means you hit trouble immediately. This system keeps sessions tight, focuses play on the interesting decision points, and prevents hours of theoretical planning that never pays off." },
  { id:"rule-payoff-core", title:"Payoff", source:"BitD Core", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"payoff, coin, rep, heat, faction, score result", preview:"After the score, collect your reward in Coin and Rep — and watch your Heat rise.", content:"After a score, the crew determines their Payoff: Coin (wealth) and Rep (street reputation). Coin is divided among crew members and goes into the crew's Vault; members take a cut in Stash. Rep advances the crew's Tier and unlocks new contacts and opportunities. Heat also increases based on the score's visibility — a clean quiet job generates 2 Heat; an open assault might generate 5 or more. If the crew's combined Heat + Wanted Level reaches 9, they suffer an Entanglement (unwanted attention from factions, Bluecoats, Inspectors, or Spirit Wardens). After every score, roll on the Entanglement table. Managing the balance between high-value noisy jobs and low-profile quiet ones is a core crew-level strategic tension in the campaign." },
  { id:"rule-incarceration-core", title:"Incarceration", source:"BitD Core", page:"26", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"prison, incarceration, escape, wanted level, entanglement", preview:"Getting caught means prison — but scoundrels always find a way out.", content:"If a PC is captured and handed over to authorities, they go to Ironhook Prison. During incarceration, the player rolls their character's lowest Attribute to determine how well they fare (on a 6, they escape early or make useful contacts; on 4-5 they do their time and return; on 1-3, they suffer lasting harm or trauma). Time passes during incarceration — other PCs continue normal downtime. The crew may attempt a rescue (a full score) or wait. Upon release, the incarcerated PC rejoins play with any consequences from their roll. Characters can also have their Wanted Level reduced during prison time. Incarceration is meant to be dramatic but not punitive — it's a scene, not a game-over, and the mechanics support that by giving the player agency even while locked up." },
  { id:"rule-xp-core", title:"Character XP", source:"BitD Core", page:"30", category:"Player", subcategory:"Advancement", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"xp, advancement, experience, playbook, abilities", preview:"Mark XP by expressing your playbook's drives and struggling with your nature.", content:"At the end of each session, each player answers a set of XP prompts to mark experience. All characters share three general prompts: Did you express your beliefs, drives, heritage, or background? Did you struggle with issues related to your vice or trauma? Did you push into danger? Each playbook also has a unique XP trigger tied to its theme (e.g., the Cutter marks XP for engaging in physical conflict; the Slide for using deception or social manipulation). Mark 1 XP for each prompt you can answer 'yes' to. When you fill your XP track (8 boxes for most things), you gain an Advance: a new special ability, a Dot in an action, or an increase to an Attribute Rating. Advancement is intentionally slow and tied to fictional behavior, meaning your character develops in directions that reflect how you've actually played them." },
  { id:"rule-crew-xp-core", title:"Crew XP & Advancement", source:"BitD Core", page:"32", category:"Player", subcategory:"Advancement", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"crew xp, crew advancement, tier, upgrades, rep", preview:"The whole crew advances together — upgrading your base, expanding your contacts, and rising through the underworld.", content:"At the end of each session, the crew marks XP based on three crew-level prompts: Did you execute a score that demonstrated your crew type's specialty? Did the crew experience a significant challenge related to their Hunting Ground? And the crew's unique XP trigger specific to their type (e.g., Assassins: did the crew eliminate a meaningful target?). When the crew fills their XP track (6 boxes), they gain a Crew Advance: a new Crew Upgrade (lair improvement, specialized gear access, contacts), or a new Special Ability for the crew as a whole. Crew Tier increases when rep fills and is spent — higher Tier unlocks better scores, more powerful faction relationships, and greater influence. Crew advancement creates a compelling parallel arc to individual PC development." },
  { id:"rule-plan-assault-core", title:"Assault Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, assault, combat, breach, force", preview:"Go in hard — use force or threat of force as your primary method of entry and control.", content:"The Assault Plan covers scores where the crew's primary approach is direct physical confrontation, forcible breach, or overwhelming threat. The Detail for an Assault plan is typically a point of attack or breach — how you get in, where you hit first, or what weapon/tool you rely on. Engagement starts at Risky position by default (violence is loud, draws response). An Assault plan favors Scrap, Skirmish, and Command actions. It works well when the target is vulnerable to direct force, the crew has combat-capable members, or speed and shock outweigh subtlety. The risk is Heat — assaults generate more Heat than other plan types, and sustained firefights can quickly turn desperate. Best used when the target's defenses are known and beatable, and when collateral damage is acceptable." },
  { id:"rule-plan-deception-core", title:"Deception Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"127", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, deception, disguise, con, social", preview:"Get in through lies, disguise, or misdirection — make them believe the story you're selling.", content:"A Deception Plan uses false identities, forgeries, misdirection, or elaborate cons to achieve the score's objective. The Detail is typically the key fiction being maintained — the cover identity, the forged document, the false pretense. Engagement defaults to Controlled or Risky depending on the quality of the deception and the target's suspicion level. Deception plans favor Sway, Command, Consort, and Finesse actions. They're powerful when the crew can blend in or when direct access requires social permission. The danger is that deceptions can unravel — a single roll failure may expose the fiction and force a chaotic pivot. Deception plans reward preparation (flashbacks to establish cover stories) and players who enjoy social/roleplaying challenges. Works best against targets who rely on procedure and verification rather than brute security." },
  { id:"rule-plan-stealth-core", title:"Stealth Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"127", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, stealth, infiltration, sneak, shadow", preview:"Move through unseen — get in, get the prize, get out before anyone knows you were there.", content:"A Stealth Plan relies on silence, shadow, and avoiding detection entirely. The Detail is typically the route of approach — how you're bypassing security, what blind spot you're exploiting, or what distraction you're relying on. Engagement defaults to Controlled if the route is well-scouted, Risky if there are unknowns. Stealth plans favor Prowl, Finesse, and Attune actions. They're ideal for objectives that require quiet access, preserving secrecy, or avoiding collateral damage. The key risk is that stealth is brittle — a single failed roll or bad circumstance can shatter the approach and require improvisation. They generate the least Heat of all plan types when successful. Best for crews with high Prowl ratings or when the target's defenses are gaps rather than walls." },
  { id:"rule-plan-occult-core", title:"Occult Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, occult, ghost field, ritual, supernatural", preview:"Use arcane power, spirit manipulation, or ghostly passage to bypass mundane obstacles.", content:"An Occult Plan uses the ghost field, rituals, or supernatural means to accomplish what ordinary methods can't. The Detail is typically the specific supernatural element being leveraged — a ghost contact, a ritual ward, a spectral breach point, or a possessed asset. Engagement difficulty depends on the arcane preparation required. Occult plans favor Attune, Study, and Survey actions. They're powerful because they bypass mundane security entirely (no guard sees a ghost) and can access otherwise unreachable targets. The risks are unique: ghost field exposure, unwanted spectral attention, ritual backlash, or alerting Inspectors and Spirit Wardens. Occult plans reward characters with Attune investment and crews with arcane upgrades. They also open up narrative space for the game's horror elements." },
  { id:"rule-plan-social-core", title:"Social Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"22", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, social, networking, leverage, faction", preview:"Work through contacts, leverage, and relationships to achieve your objective without ever drawing a blade.", content:"A Social Plan accomplishes the score's goal through people — bribing, blackmailing, negotiating, or leveraging existing relationships and faction dynamics. The Detail is typically a specific person, event, or piece of leverage being exploited — the inside contact, the social gathering, the damaging secret. Engagement defaults to Controlled if the approach is well-prepared and the target is receptive. Social plans favor Consort, Sway, Command, and Study actions. They're uniquely powerful for objectives that don't require physical access at all — information gathering, reputation manipulation, turning an NPC, or arranging an agreement. The risk is that people are unpredictable and leverage can turn against you. Social plans often require the most pre-score setup (establishing relationships, acquiring intel) but generate minimal Heat when successful." },
  { id:"rule-plan-transport-core", title:"Transport Plan", source:"BitD Core", page:"120", category:"Player", subcategory:"Plan Types", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"plan, transport, vehicle, escape, convoy, delivery", preview:"Get something or someone from one place to another — safely, quickly, or secretly.", content:"A Transport Plan centers on moving a person, object, or cargo: intercepting a shipment, escorting a VIP, smuggling contraband, or hijacking a vehicle in transit. The Detail is typically the specific route, vehicle, or handoff point. Engagement depends on known threats along the route. Transport plans favor Helm, Skirmish, Finesse, and Attune actions. They're distinct from other plan types in that the score has a dynamic, moving quality — complications arise in transit, not at a fixed location. Smugglers crews excel at transport plans and may have upgrades that add extra dice here. Key challenges include interception by rivals, vehicle breakdowns, route changes, and protecting passengers who may have agendas of their own. A well-executed transport plan can establish the crew as reliable movers in the city's underworld economy." },
  { id:"world-doskvol-core", title:"Doskvol (The City)", source:"BitD Core", page:"10", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"doskvol, city, whisper isles, canals, bluecoats, coal, gaslight", preview:"A rain-soaked industrial city hemmed in by lightning barriers — the last refuge of humanity in a ghost-haunted world.", content:"Doskvol (also called Duskwall or The City) is a sprawling industrial metropolis built along a network of canals and coastal bluffs on the Shattered Isles. It is powered by electroplasmic technology fueled by processed ghost essence, giving it perpetual gas-lit streets even in the endless dark since the Cataclysm extinguished the sun. The city is divided into districts (Crow's Foot, Nightmarket, Charhollow, Brightstone, Dunslough, and others) each with its own culture, power structure, and criminal opportunities. Doskvol is governed nominally by the Emperor through the City Council, but real power lies with powerful noble Houses and criminal factions. The Bluecoats (city watch) maintain surface order; the Inspectors investigate serious crimes; the Spirit Wardens handle ghost-related threats. The city is simultaneously a place of opulent wealth (for the few) and grinding poverty (for the many) — the perfect backdrop for scoundrels carving out their piece of the underworld." },
  { id:"world-ghost-field-core", title:"The Ghost Field", source:"BitD Core", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"ghost field, spectral, undead, haunting, electroplasm, veil", preview:"An invisible layer of death-energy overlapping the physical world — home of ghosts, demons, and worse.", content:"The Ghost Field (also called the Void or the spectral plane) is a parallel dimension of death-energy that overlaps the physical world. It became a dominant feature of the setting after the Cataclysm sundered the gates of death, allowing ghosts to linger in the mortal world rather than passing on. Characters with the Attune action can perceive and interact with the ghost field — sensing spectral presences, communicating with ghosts, or reaching into it for power. The ghost field is dangerous: prolonged exposure or careless manipulation can attract hungry ghosts, demons, or worse entities. It also provides the raw electroplasmic energy that powers Doskvol's industry — ghost essence is harvested by Spirit Wardens and processed into electroplasm fuel. The ghost field is central to the game's horror atmosphere and creates unique score opportunities unavailable in other settings." },
  { id:"world-electroplasm-core", title:"Electroplasm", source:"BitD Core", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"electroplasm, lightning, power, ghost essence, industry, technology", preview:"Processed ghost essence that powers the city's lights, industry, and weapons — the blood of Doskvol's economy.", content:"Electroplasm is the refined form of ghost essence — the raw death-energy extracted from captured or destroyed spirits. It serves as the primary energy source for all of Doskvol's technology: the lightning barriers that keep demons out, the gas-lit streets, the industrial machinery, and various weapons and tools used by factions and scoundrels alike. Electroplasm is produced by the Imperial Military's Spirit Wardens and distributed through the city's infrastructure. It's also a black-market commodity — unrefined ghost essence, illegally harvested or stockpiled electroplasm, and experimental electroplasmic devices are common score objectives. Leech characters specialize in electroplasmic technology and alchemical applications. The city's entire economic and military power rests on the continued supply of electroplasm, making control of ghost-harvesting routes a major political and criminal flashpoint." },
  { id:"world-cataclysm-core", title:"The Cataclysm", source:"BitD Core", page:"10", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"cataclysm, history, sun, darkness, demons, death gates", preview:"An ancient catastrophe that shattered the world — extinguishing the sun and breaking the gates between life and death.", content:"Centuries before the game's present, an unknown cataclysm (the Reconciliation) shattered the Shattered Isles, extinguished the sun, and broke the gates of death. The result was permanent darkness across the world and the dissolution of the barrier keeping the dead from lingering. Ghosts, demons, and spectral entities now roam freely outside the lightning barriers. Massive leviathan-like creatures called Strangers (or worse) haunt the dark seas. The Imperial State maintains survival through electroplasmic technology — the lightning barriers being the most critical application. The Cataclysm shapes every aspect of the setting: the darkness is literal and psychological, the economy revolves around death-energy, and the constant threat of the ghost field makes Doskvol a city under siege from the spectral as much as the political. The specifics of what caused the Cataclysm are left deliberately vague — a mystery GMs can develop." },
  { id:"world-lightning-barriers-core", title:"Lightning Barriers", source:"BitD Core", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"lightning barriers, protection, demons, city wall, electroplasm, survival", preview:"Crackling electroplasmic walls that ring every city — the only thing keeping the demons of the dark outside.", content:"Lightning Barriers are enormous electroplasmic constructs that ring every inhabited settlement in the world, forming crackling walls of ghost-repelling energy. They prevent spectral entities, demons, and ghosts from freely entering human settlements — without them, the cities would be overwhelmed. Every major city including Doskvol maintains and expands its lightning barriers as a top priority. The barriers are powered by electroplasm and maintained by Imperial engineers. They are not impenetrable — determined ghosts and certain entities can breach them, especially if the barrier is damaged or unpowered — but they represent humanity's primary defense against the spectral dark. Scores that involve sabotaging, bypassing, or restoring sections of the lightning barrier are among the highest-stakes possible — affecting the entire city rather than just a faction. For scoundrels, the barriers also represent the literal edge of the known world: beyond them lies the endless haunted dark." },
  { id:"crew-assassins-core", title:"Assassins", source:"BitD Core", page:"72", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"assassins, murder, contracts, kill, elimination, hunting ground", preview:"A crew specializing in contract killing, targeted elimination, and deadly professionalism.", content:"The Assassins crew is built around the business of killing — taking contracts for targeted eliminations, wet work for factions, and removing problems that other methods can't solve. Their Hunting Ground is wherever their current contract takes them (they have no fixed territory). Assassins generate Rep by completing high-profile eliminations and keeping their methods mysterious and professional. Their crew upgrades include Ironhook Contacts (prison relationships), Composed (stress resistance), and specialized assassination tools. Their special abilities include The Hunting Ground (choose a specific type of mark and gain bonus to hunting them), Deadly (bonus effect when striking from ambush), and Synchronised (coordination bonuses for simultaneous strikes). The Assassins crew works best with Cutter and Hound PCs who specialize in combat and tracking. They must balance taking lucrative open contracts against building a fearsome but discreet reputation — being too visible invites retaliation from powerful patrons of their marks." },
  { id:"crew-bravos-core", title:"Bravos", source:"BitD Core", page:"76", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"bravos, muscle, protection, violence, territory, gang", preview:"A crew that sells violence — hired muscle, debt collection, and the force that backs other criminals.", content:"Bravos are the muscle of the underworld — a crew that specializes in selling the credible threat of violence. They run protection rackets, work as hired muscle for other factions, enforce debts, hold territory, and take jobs requiring physical presence and intimidation. Their Hunting Ground is a turf they claim and protect, generating income through protection fees and control of foot traffic. Bravos upgrades include Hardened (extra trauma resistance), Composed, and various combat and intimidation upgrades. Their special abilities include Fearsome (Command rolls using Skirmish), Gang Fighters (crew brawling bonuses), and Dangerous Friends (menacing contacts). Bravos are the most street-level crew type — they're deep in the city's gangs and territorial disputes. They generate Rep through visible demonstrations of force and reliable muscle work. Best suited for Cutter and Hound PCs who want to play the violent side of the underworld without the subtlety of the Assassins." },
  { id:"crew-cult-core", title:"Cult", source:"BitD Core", page:"80", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"cult, occult, rituals, patron deity, arcane, ghost field, faith", preview:"A devoted group serving an arcane patron — trading in forbidden rituals, ghost-field power, and fanatical loyalty.", content:"The Cult crew is built around devotion to an arcane patron — a demon, ancient deity, powerful ghost, or other supernatural entity. They pursue arcane power, gather forbidden knowledge, and perform rituals to honor and strengthen their patron. Their Hunting Ground is wherever their patron's influence or sacred sites lie. Cult upgrades include Ritual Focus (specialization in a type of ritual), Zealotry (fanatic recruits), and Arcane Arsenal (supernatural tools and artifacts). Their special abilities include Chosen (patron grants boons), Anointed (crew members resist supernatural harm), and Zealot (sacrifice Stress or harm for power). The Cult is the most thematically extreme crew type — they're playing with cosmic forces and the game's horror elements directly. Best suited for Whisper PCs who want to develop the arcane arc deeply. Managing the patron relationship is a central campaign challenge — the entity will want something in return for its gifts, and refusal has consequences." },
  { id:"crew-hawkers-core", title:"Hawkers", source:"BitD Core", page:"92", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"hawkers, trade, drugs, contraband, black market, sales, distribution", preview:"Merchants of the illegal — dealing in drugs, contraband, and black-market goods across the city's streets.", content:"Hawkers deal in the sale and distribution of illegal commodities — Spark (stimulant), Drown (depressant), Trance (psychedelic), Wyvern (combat drug), and other contraband. Their Hunting Ground is the street-level market for their product — specific districts where they've established a distribution network. Hawkers generate income through sales and Rep through the quality and reach of their product. Upgrades include Dealer's Network (wider distribution), Steady (reliable product that builds loyal customers), and Street-Level Intel (knowing who's buying what). Their special abilities include Hawker's Loyal (customers protect them), Dealer (bonus when selling), and Supplier (access to better product). Hawkers are the most mercantile crew type — they're running a business as much as a criminal enterprise. Best for Slide and Spider PCs who enjoy the social and strategic side of building a criminal empire rather than direct violence." },
  { id:"crew-shadows-core", title:"Shadows", source:"BitD Core", page:"88", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"shadows, thieves, burglary, espionage, infiltration, heist", preview:"Expert thieves and spies — masters of getting in, taking what isn't theirs, and vanishing without a trace.", content:"The Shadows crew specializes in theft, burglary, and espionage — breaking into secure locations, stealing valuables and secrets, and operating with minimal footprint. Their Hunting Ground is a type of target (secure vaults, wealthy estates, government buildings) rather than a territory. They generate Rep through spectacular heists and their reputation for professional discretion. Shadows upgrades include Hidden Lair (concealed base), Steady Hands (precision tools), and Spy Network (informant contacts). Their special abilities include Everyone Steals (crew training bonus), Infiltration (improved initial position for stealth scores), and Ghost Network (intelligence assets). Shadows are the most classically heist-focused crew type — their playbook supports elaborate multi-stage break-in scores. Best for Lurk and Whisper PCs who want to build toward ambitious high-value targets. They must balance ambition with operational security — the most daring heists also generate the most attention." },
  { id:"crew-smugglers-core", title:"Smugglers", source:"BitD Core", page:"92", category:"Crew", subcategory:"Crew Playbooks", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"smugglers, transport, routes, vehicles, contraband, ships, canals", preview:"The city's underground movers — running contraband, people, and secrets through hidden routes no one else knows.", content:"Smugglers are specialists in transportation — moving illegal goods, people, and secrets through routes the authorities don't know about or can't watch. Their Hunting Ground is a specific route (canal network, coastal access, underground passages, city gates) they've established and defend. Smugglers generate income through transport fees and Rep through their reliability and route access. Upgrades include Caravan (overland vehicles), Canal Boat (water access), Cloaked (disguised vehicles), and Maps of the City (complete route knowledge). Their special abilities include Leverage (bonus when transporting), Precision Handling (vehicle proficiency), and Riding the Tide (tidal and canal route mastery). Smugglers are the most logistically-focused crew — their playbook rewards players who enjoy the strategic, supply-chain side of criminal enterprise. Best for Hound and Slide PCs who want to build a criminal network across the city's geography. Their key challenge is protecting their routes from rivals and law enforcement surveillance." },
  { id:"ability-battleborn-core", title:"Battleborn", source:"BitD Core", page:"62", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, combat, resistance, battle, armor", preview:"You were made for war — take reduced harm when you use your body to absorb punishment.", content:"When you Push Yourself, you may spend 2 Stress to perform a feat of extraordinary combat endurance — taking a blow that would fell a lesser fighter, breaking free of restraints through raw strength, or fighting through injuries that would incapacitate anyone else. Additionally, you may resist physical consequences (harm from combat, falls, environmental hazards) for free once per score — the Stress cost of that resistance is 0. Battleborn represents a character who has trained their body to absorb punishment that would destroy others. It's most powerful in high-intensity combat scenarios where you're taking multiple hits. Pairs well with the Skirmish action and any abilities that trigger on taking or resisting harm. The free resistance makes you extraordinarily durable in the first major confrontation of each score." },
  { id:"ability-bodyguard-core", title:"Bodyguard", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, protect, bodyguard, assist, teamwork, intercept", preview:"Step in front of the blow meant for someone else — take the hit so they don't have to.", content:"When you protect a teammate, they ignore all consequences from a single action — you take the consequences instead (and may resist them normally). Additionally, when you give aid to an ally's action roll, you roll 2d and take the higher result for the assistance die rather than the normal 1d. Bodyguard transforms the Cutter from a solo fighter into a team anchor — you make everyone around you more effective and more survivable. It's especially powerful in escort scores, social situations where a protected ally needs to take risks, and any scenario where a key crew member is vulnerable. The enhanced assistance bonus applies broadly, making this useful well beyond pure combat." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-fighter-cutter-core", title:"Ghost Fighter", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, ghost, spirit, combat, arcane, supernatural, attune", preview:"Your fighting style works on both flesh and spirit — you can harm ghosts with your bare hands.", content:"You may Skirmish with ghosts and demons as if they were physical opponents, using normal Skirmish rolls against spectral entities. Additionally, you can perceive spectral threats instinctively — you're never caught off-guard by a ghost ambush even without using Attune. Your unarmed strikes and any weapons you carry can affect ghost-field entities without requiring electroplasmic enhancement. Ghost Fighter is a uniquely powerful ability in Doskvol, where ghost threats are common and most physical characters are helpless against spectral enemies. It frees up the Cutter from dependence on the Whisper or Attune-specialized allies during arcane threats. Pairs naturally with any score involving the ghost field, Spirit Warden enemies, or Cult opponents who summon spectral protectors." },
  { id:"ability-leader-cutter-core", title:"Leader", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, command, gang, group, teamwork, npc, cohort", preview:"Your crew fights at full effectiveness under your command — direct them with authority and precision.", content:"When you lead a gang (NPC cohort) in a coordinated action, the gang counts as having one additional Quality for that action. Additionally, when you give a Command-based order to an NPC during a score, you may add +1d to their action without spending a team action or taking a flashback — your command presence is sufficient. Leader reflects a Cutter who is not just a soldier but a battlefield commander — someone whose presence and direction multiplies the effectiveness of everyone around them. It's most valuable for crews with strong cohorts (gang members, hired fighters) and for scores that involve large group actions. Pairs with Battleborn and Bodyguard to create a nearly unkillable, team-enhancing front-line commander archetype." },
  { id:"ability-mule-core", title:"Mule", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, strength, load, carry, physical, brute", preview:"Your strength is exceptional — carry more, hit harder, and push through obstacles others can't.", content:"Your maximum Load is increased by 2 (you can carry up to 8 items at Heavy load). Additionally, when you use raw strength to overcome a physical obstacle — breaking down a door, bending bars, lifting debris, overpowering an opponent in a grapple — you count as having +1 effect automatically without needing to push yourself. Mule is a straightforward power upgrade for physically-focused Cutters. The increased Load lets you bring more specialized gear without sacrificing mobility (relatively), and the effect bonus on strength tasks means you rarely need to waste Stress on pushes for obstacles that should be within your capability. Best for players who want to emphasize the Cutter's physical dominance and enjoy being the crew's door-kicker and heavy lifter." },
  { id:"ability-not-trifled-with-core", title:"Not To Be Trifled With", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, fear, intimidation, violence, dominance, reputation", preview:"You project such menace that enemies hesitate — even the brave think twice before crossing you.", content:"You can push yourself to do one of the following without making a roll: perform a feat of extraordinary violence that terrifies everyone who witnesses it (clearing a crowd, making enemies flee, establishing absolute dominance), or resist the effects of fear, intimidation, or morale-breaking circumstances without rolling. When enemies assess you (even without Attune), they sense your capacity for violence instinctively. Not To Be Trifled With is a powerful hybrid ability — part social (intimidation), part combat (extraordinary violence feats). It's especially useful for Cutters who don't want to invest deeply in Command but need the ability to control situations through presence alone. The fear effect can clear encounters that would otherwise require fighting, saving Stress and harm while generating reputation through demonstration." },
  { id:"ability-savage-cutter-core", title:"Savage", source:"BitD Core", page:"44", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, brutal, harm, injury, vicious, attack", preview:"When you bring pain, you bring it harder than anyone else — your strikes inflict greater harm.", content:"When you inflict harm on a target, you may push yourself to inflict +1 level of harm on the result. Additionally, when your action roll succeeds with a 6, you automatically inflict an additional consequence on your target (your choice: an extra level of harm, a complication, a position setback). Savage makes the Cutter the most reliably lethal character in the game for direct combat. The ability to escalate harm means that a Level 1 hit becomes Level 2 at the cost of 2 Stress — and on a critical success, you're piling on additional consequences. Best for Cutters focused on ending fights quickly and decisively. Pairs extremely well with Battleborn (take hits) and Not To Be Trifled With (don't even need to fight most of the time)." },
  { id:"ability-vigorous-core", title:"Vigorous", source:"BitD Core", page:"63", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Cutter", tags:"cutter, healing, recovery, harm, resilience, downtime", preview:"Your body heals faster and better than anyone else — you bounce back from punishment that would sideline others.", content:"When you Recover during downtime, you may clear 1 additional harm level (you heal 2 ticks instead of 1 on your harm clock). Additionally, when you receive medical treatment from an ally, the treatment action gains +1 effect. Vigorous represents a character whose body is simply more resilient than normal humans — they metabolize injury, repair tissue faster, and shake off trauma that sticks to others. In a game where harm accumulates across scores and downtime is limited, Vigorous provides significant long-term sustainability. It means the Cutter can afford to take more risks with their body knowing recovery will be faster. Pairs naturally with Battleborn and Savage to create a character who can absorb and dish out extreme punishment across an entire campaign." },
  { id:"ability-connected-hound-core", title:"Connected", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, contacts, network, information, faction, allies", preview:"Your information network spans the city — you always know someone who knows something.", content:"During downtime, you may seek out an NPC contact for information or assistance. When you do, you roll your Consort action as if you had +1d (representing your well-maintained network). Additionally, when the crew needs a contact in an unfamiliar faction or district, you may declare that you have a connection there (GM may call for a Tier/Rep check to determine quality of the contact). Connected is the Hound's social utility ability — it keeps the crew informed and opens doors to factions the crew hasn't cultivated. It's particularly valuable in campaign play where information asymmetry determines which scores are even viable. Pairs naturally with Foresight (predicting threats) and Scout (identifying targets) to make the Hound the crew's intelligence specialist." },
  { id:"ability-foresight-hound-core", title:"Foresight", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, planning, preparation, setup, assistance", preview:"Your tactical instincts let you set up team actions with uncanny precision.", content:"Two times per score, you may give yourself or an ally +1d to an action by explaining how you anticipated this exact scenario and prepared for it in advance. No flashback or roll is required — your foresight is simply accepted as part of your character's planning capability. Foresight is a generous action-economy ability — granting +1d twice per score without spending Stress or actions represents significant mechanical power. It rewards players who engage with the narrative by articulating their character's thought process. Best used on critical moments — a pivotal Skirmish roll, a risky Sway attempt, a dangerous Prowl. Pairs well with Scout (you've observed the target) and Connected (you know who will be there) to create a character who always seems two steps ahead." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-hunter-hound-core", title:"Ghost Hunter", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, ghost, hunt, supernatural, spirit, ward, tracking", preview:"You've honed your skills for tracking and neutralizing ghosts — the city's most dangerous unseen prey.", content:"You have +1d when tracking, studying, or surveying ghost-field entities. You also carry Ghost Hunter's tools as part of your standard kit (at no additional Load cost): electroplasmic rounds, a spirit anchor, and a ghost ward. When you successfully strike a ghost with an electroplasmic weapon, you may push yourself to force it to manifest and become vulnerable to physical attack. Ghost Hunter fills the same niche for the Hound as Ghost Fighter does for the Cutter — it makes a physically-focused character effective against the game's supernatural threats. The free ghost-hunting tools are a significant economy boost, and the tracking bonus makes the Hound uniquely capable at finding spectral targets that are actively hiding. Ideal for scores in haunted locations, ghost-field investigations, and confrontations with Whisper or Cult enemies." },
  { id:"ability-lethal-core", title:"Lethal", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, kill, ranged, ambush, harm, precision", preview:"Your aim is extraordinary — at range, you are simply the most dangerous person in the room.", content:"When you use a ranged weapon with the benefit of positioning (elevated, hidden, or prepared), you increase your effect by one level for harm purposes. Additionally, when you take out a target with a single shot (eliminating them before they can act), the action does not require a roll if your position is Controlled — the shot simply lands. Lethal reflects the Hound's mastery of precision ranged combat — not just as a skilled shooter, but as someone who understands angles, distances, and the geometry of violence. The no-roll elimination in Controlled position is exceptional for assassination scores where setup is the work and the killing itself should be clean. Pairs powerfully with Scout (establish positioning), Foresight (anticipate the shot), and any score involving a planned elimination." },
  { id:"ability-scout-core", title:"Scout", source:"BitD Core", page:"65", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, surveillance, survey, information, position, recon", preview:"You can assess a location or target with exceptional detail — reading a scene others would miss entirely.", content:"When you Survey a person, location, or situation, you may ask the GM one additional question (beyond the standard Survey questions) about what you observe. Additionally, once per score, you may declare that you have already scoped the location in advance — removing one specific unknown from the situation (a guard position, a lock type, an escape route) without a flashback roll. Scout is the Hound's information-gathering engine — it turns Survey into a potent scene-reading tool and the advance-scouting declaration short-circuits the need for flashbacks on recon matters. Best in heist and infiltration scores where the party needs to know what they're walking into. Pairs with Foresight (use what you learned), Connected (confirm with a contact), and Ghost Hunter (scout supernatural threats too)." },
  { id:"ability-survivor-core", title:"Survivor", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, endurance, stress, resilience, recovery, trauma", preview:"You've seen the worst and kept going — your mental resilience in crisis is extraordinary.", content:"When you indulge your Vice during downtime and clear Stress, you clear 1 additional Stress (you clear one more than your Resolve result). Additionally, you may add your Resolve Rating to your recovery of Stress during a moment of calm mid-score (if you have even a few minutes of quiet, you can reset 1 Stress for free). Survivor reflects the Hound's particular psychological durability — they've endured enough to develop genuine coping mechanisms rather than simply pushing through. In campaign play, the extra Stress recovery from Vice is significant over time. The mid-score recovery is niche but powerful when it applies. Pairs well with the Hound's ranged playstyle, which tends to keep them in slightly less direct danger than a Cutter — their Stress management lets them sustain more operations between full rests." },
  { id:"ability-veteran-hound-core", title:"Veteran", source:"BitD Core", page:"46", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Hound", tags:"hound, veteran, cross-training, ability, playbook", preview:"Your experience crosses playbook lines — take a special ability from another playbook.", content:"Choose one special ability from another playbook. You've worked with enough different specialists that you've developed one of their capabilities. The ability must be narratively justifiable given your backstory and the campaign fiction, though the GM should be generous. Veteran is the Hound's wild-card ability — it allows unlimited customization at the cost of being a meta-mechanical pick rather than a thematic one. The most common combinations for Hounds: Battleborn (Cutter) for a melee-capable scout, Calculating (Slide) for an intelligence operative, or Strange Methods (Whisper) for a paranormal investigator. Best chosen to fill a gap in the crew's capability rather than to double down on existing strengths." },
  { id:"ability-alchemist-core", title:"Alchemist", source:"BitD Core", page:"48", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, alchemy, substances, potions, drugs, craft", preview:"Your talent for alchemical formulation lets you brew compounds that give your crew an edge.", content:"When you use the Craft downtime action to produce alchemical substances, you get +1 result level (a 4-5 becomes a 6, a 6 becomes a crit). Additionally, you may produce a limited quantity of a standard alchemical compound (Trance, Quicksilver, Spark) as a free downtime action once per session — no roll required. Alchemist makes the Leech a sustained supplier of consumable tactical advantages for the crew. Alchemical substances in BitD range from combat drugs and healing compounds to poisons, corrosives, and ghost-affecting solutions. With Alchemist, you're reliably stocked with materials other crews would need to buy. Pairs with Workshop (your lab) and Artificer (if you want to embed alchemy into devices) for a complete crafting Leech build." },
  { id:"ability-analyst-core", title:"Analyst", source:"BitD Core", page:"70", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, study, research, assessment, information, weakness", preview:"Your analytical mind finds weaknesses others overlook — you can study anything and extract its vulnerabilities.", content:"When you Study a target, person, object, or plan in detail, you may ask the GM one additional question beyond the standard Study questions. Additionally, once per score, after observing an enemy or obstacle in action, you may declare a specific weakness you've identified — the crew gets +1 effect against that target when exploiting that weakness. Analyst makes the Leech a potent intelligence asset beyond their technical role. The weakness identification is especially powerful because it applies to the whole crew, not just the Leech. Best used early in a score to establish a target profile that the Cutter and Hound can exploit. Pairs with Scout (Hound ability, if taken via Veteran) and any build focused on preparation and information warfare." },
  { id:"ability-artificer-core", title:"Artificer", source:"BitD Core", page:"48", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, devices, gadgets, invention, craft, tinker", preview:"Your hands can build anything — when the crew needs a custom tool, you can make it.", content:"When you use the Craft downtime action to build or repair devices, you may create one additional item beyond the normal result. You may also push yourself to create a one-use custom device mid-score (no downtime required) — describing the device you somehow assembled from available parts. The GM sets a roll difficulty based on the device's complexity. Artificer is the Leech's improvisation ability — it establishes that your character is never truly without a tool for the situation. The mid-score device creation is the standout feature, enabling flashback-style problem solving (I built a solution to this exact problem) for technical challenges. Pairs with Workshop (your lab) and Alchemist (combined craft Leech) for a complete inventor build." },
  { id:"ability-fortify-core", title:"Fortify", source:"BitD Core", page:"48", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, armor, protection, warding, upgrade, fortification", preview:"You can turn any defensive position into a fortress with the right preparations.", content:"When you prepare a defensive position (a room, vehicle, or perimeter) using available materials and time, that position gains +1 Armor level for the next combat. Additionally, you may set one trap in that position as a free bonus action during the preparation (no extra roll required). Fortify represents the Leech's ability to apply engineering principles to tactical defense — the character who turns a hotel room into a kill box or reinforces a hiding spot to withstand assault. The trap bonus is flexible: trip wires, alchemical deterrents, electroplasmic wards, whatever fits the fiction. Best used in scores where the crew knows a fight is coming and has time to prepare the ground before it arrives." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-note-core", title:"Ghost Note", source:"BitD Core", page:"48", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, ghost field, electroplasm, devices, arcane tech, spiritual", preview:"Your devices can interact with the ghost field — building gadgets that bridge the gap between technology and the spectral.", content:"You can build electroplasmic devices that interact with the ghost field: ghost detectors, spirit anchors, hull-disruptors, and harmonic amplifiers. Such devices do not require Attune to use — any character with your device can operate it. Additionally, when you use a device you built to interact with the ghost field, you have +1d on the roll. Ghost Note makes the Leech the crew's technical occultist — bridging the gap between the game's technology and supernatural elements without requiring the Whisper's more direct arcane approach. The no-Attune-required use is crucial: it means you can equip crew members who have no arcane capability with tools that give them ghost-field access. Pairs with Artificer (build more devices) and Workshop (your lab has the right equipment)." },
  { id:"ability-saboteur-core", title:"Saboteur", source:"BitD Core", page:"69", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, sabotage, demolitions, wreck, destroy, explosives", preview:"When something needs to be broken, jammed, or blown up, you do it with surgical precision.", content:"When you use the Wreck action to destroy, disable, or sabotage a device or structure, you get +1 effect automatically. Additionally, you may push yourself to perform a clean sabotage — destroying functionality without visible damage (the target fails when operated, rather than appearing broken on inspection). Saboteur is the Leech's offensive engineering ability — it's not just about building things but knowing exactly how to unmake them. The clean sabotage option is particularly powerful for deception and stealth scores where you need the mark to not notice the sabotage until it's too late. Pairs with Artificer (you understand devices intimately) and Fortify (you know what makes structures weak) for a comprehensive engineering Leech." },
  { id:"ability-venomous-core", title:"Venomous", source:"BitD Core", page:"69", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Leech", tags:"leech, poison, venom, toxin, harm, debilitate", preview:"Your knowledge of poisons and toxins is encyclopedic — you can kill, incapacitate, or alter with a touch.", content:"You may apply a poison or toxin to a weapon, food, or surface as a quick action (no roll required). You carry a supply of standard toxins (paralytic, soporific, contact irritant, slow-acting lethal) as part of your standard kit. When you administer a toxin to a target, you choose the effect profile (onset time, symptoms, severity) within the fictional limits of the substance. Venomous makes the Leech the most sophisticated assassin's enabler in the game — able to create precisely-calibrated incapacitation, information-extraction sedatives, or untraceable poisons. The no-roll application is key: the skill is in the Leech's preparation, not in a fumbling poison-the-glass moment. Pairs with Alchemist (brew custom toxins) and the Slide's social infiltration abilities for clean, professional targeted incapacitations." },
  { id:"ability-ambush-core", title:"Ambush", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, ambush, surprise, attack, position, stealth combat", preview:"Strike from perfect concealment and your first blow lands with devastating force.", content:"When you attack from ambush or from concealment (your target is unaware of you), your effect level for harm is increased by 1 and you start from Controlled position rather than Risky, regardless of circumstances. Additionally, when you eliminate a target in an ambush, you may do so without triggering an alert roll if you succeed. Ambush is the Lurk's assassination ability — it transforms surprise into a reliable tactical advantage. The effect bonus means an ambush Skirmish hit becomes far more damaging, and the Controlled starting position makes the opening action significantly safer. The no-alert elimination means clean kills stay clean. This ability rewards the Lurk's core playstyle: patience, positioning, and explosive precision action. Pairs with Shadow (maintaining concealment longer) and Like Smoke (escaping after the hit)." },
  { id:"ability-daredevil-core", title:"Daredevil", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, risk, desperate, bonus, daring, position", preview:"The more dangerous the situation, the better you perform — desperation sharpens your edge.", content:"When you make a desperate action roll, you gain +1d. You also do not suffer an additional consequence from the desperate position (the position still sets the severity of potential consequences, but you never take two consequences on a desperate roll — just one, like a risky roll). Daredevil flips the danger calculus for the Lurk — the position that penalizes most characters actually benefits this one. It rewards bold players who lean into desperate positions rather than trying to avoid them. Combined with the natural Lurk tendency to get into tight spots, this ability turns near-certain doom into an opportunity. Pairs with Infiltrator (enter positions others can't, which may start desperate) and Ghost Veil (use the supernatural to escape consequences)." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-veil-core", title:"Ghost Veil", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, ghost field, invisibility, stealth, supernatural, spectral", preview:"Step partially into the ghost field to become nearly invisible to living eyes.", content:"You may push yourself to become translucent and nearly invisible for a short time — stepping partially into the ghost field. While in this state, Prowl rolls to avoid detection are made at +1d, and opponents cannot make a Survey roll to notice you (they must have Attune or be supernatural themselves). The state lasts for a scene or until you take a physical action that requires full presence. Ghost Veil is the Lurk's supernatural stealth option — it bypasses mundane detection entirely and is only countered by arcane senses. The limitation (can't take full physical actions) is significant but manageable: you're most useful as a watcher and infiltrator, not a combatant, while veiled. Pairs perfectly with Ambush (drop the veil and strike for the bonus) and Like Smoke (escape back into the veil after the action)." },
  { id:"ability-like-smoke-core", title:"Like Smoke", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, escape, disappear, vanish, extraction, escape artist", preview:"When you decide it's time to go, you're already gone — extraction is your second nature.", content:"When you retreat from a situation, you always succeed at disengaging cleanly unless someone is actively preventing your escape (in which case a roll is required, but you start at Controlled position). Additionally, once per score, you may vanish from a situation entirely without a roll — you're simply gone when others look for you. Like Smoke is pure extraction capability — a once-per-score guaranteed disappearance is extraordinarily powerful for high-risk situations. The clean retreat mechanic also means the Lurk is never trapped by mere circumstance, only by deliberate opponents. In stealth and infiltration scores, the ability to ensure the Lurk gets out even when things go badly is invaluable. Pairs with Ambush (strike and vanish) and Ghost Veil (disappear into the spectral)." },
  { id:"ability-nimble-core", title:"Nimble", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, agility, movement, acrobatics, climb, dodge", preview:"Your body moves with exceptional grace — scaling obstacles, dodging blows, and flowing through spaces others can't.", content:"You may perform feats of exceptional agility without a roll when they're within the realm of human possibility (scaling a sheer wall, passing through a tight space, maintaining balance on a narrow surface in motion). Additionally, when you dodge or evade a physical consequence through movement, you get +1d on the resistance roll. Nimble is the Lurk's physical capability foundation — it establishes that your character simply moves differently than others. The no-roll agility feats remove a common bottleneck in infiltration and escape sequences. The dodge resistance bonus makes physical consequences significantly less costly. While less dramatic than Ghost Veil or Like Smoke, Nimble is consistently useful across every score type and is never situational. A reliable baseline ability." },
  { id:"ability-shadow-core", title:"Shadow", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, stealth, concealment, hide, follow, surveillance", preview:"You can remain hidden indefinitely — shadows are your home and patience is your weapon.", content:"When you are hiding or moving stealthily, you may push yourself to remain concealed even when directly observed — the observer's mind slides away from you, unable to fully register your presence. Additionally, when you follow a target without their knowledge, you never need to roll to maintain the tail unless they are specifically looking for a tail (aware of surveillance). Shadow is sustained stealth mastery — the difference between hiding and being truly unseen. The mental-slip concealment is one of the most powerful stealth abilities in the game when it triggers, as it bypasses a direct observation failure. The no-roll tail is invaluable for gathering information on marks without triggering alert states. Pairs with Ambush (follow then strike) and Scout (the Hound ability, if taken via a crew teamwork context)." },
  { id:"ability-devils-footsteps-core", title:"Devil's Footsteps", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, movement, parkour, chase, navigation, environment", preview:"You read the city's architecture as a language — moving through the urban environment like no one else can.", content:"When you navigate through the city — across rooftops, through sewers, over walls, through crowds — you move at full speed without rolls for terrain obstacles. In a chase, you always gain ground unless your pursuer has a specific capability matching yours (Skirmish-based interception, a vehicle, or a matching special ability). Additionally, you know the city's hidden routes intimately — you always have a way in and a way out unless something truly unprecedented blocks it. Devil's Footsteps makes the Lurk the crew's urban navigator — the character who can always be where they need to be and always find an escape route. In pursuit or escape scenarios, it's near-absolute. Pairs with Like Smoke (guaranteed escape plus guaranteed routes) for an essentially uncatchable character build." },
  { id:"ability-infiltrator-core", title:"Infiltrator", source:"BitD Core", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Lurk", tags:"lurk, bypass, security, locks, alarms, access, entry", preview:"No lock stops you, no alarm trips under your hands — physical security is a puzzle you've already solved.", content:"When you bypass physical security measures (locks, alarms, guard schedules, access barriers), you always have at least Limited effect on your Finesse or Prowl roll. Additionally, once per score, you may declare that you have already scoped out the security measures at your target location — you know what type of lock, alarm, or guard pattern is present, without needing a flashback. Infiltrator removes the most common failure point in stealth scores — the unknown security element that creates desperate positions. The guaranteed minimum effect means you're never completely stymied by a lock, even if you don't excel at it. The free security knowledge per score works as a compressed Scout-style preparation. Best Lurk ability for pure infiltration builds; pairs naturally with Nimble (get to the entry point) and Shadow (move through without detection once inside)." },
  { id:"ability-calculating-core", title:"Calculating", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, planning, devil's bargain, consequence, risk assessment", preview:"You never act without knowing the angles — your mind processes risk with machine-like precision.", content:"When you make an action roll, you may refuse a Devil's Bargain offered by another player (though the GM's bargains still stand). Additionally, once per score, you may assess a situation before committing to an action — asking the GM a single direct question about probable consequences or outcomes — and receive an honest answer. Calculating is the Slide's information and risk-control ability. Refusing player-offered bargains gives you mechanical agency over the complications that get introduced to your actions. The once-per-score question is essentially a free Survey with a specific oracle function — knowing what's likely to happen before you commit. Best for Slides who want tight control over their character's narrative arc. Pairs with Rook's Gambit (your risks pay off in coin) and Slippery (you can escape consequences you do accept)." },
  { id:"ability-conniver-core", title:"Conniver", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, lies, deception, concealment, cover story, bluff", preview:"Your lies are masterworks — you can deceive even experienced investigators and hostile audiences.", content:"When you deceive someone or maintain a false persona, you get +1d. Additionally, if you are caught in a lie and must Sway to maintain your cover story, you may push yourself to get +1 effect on the roll — the deception bends but doesn't break. Conniver is the social combat specialist ability — it makes the Slide's primary attack (deception) more reliable and more resilient under pressure. The cover-story push is especially powerful in complicated social scores where deceptions get pressure-tested. Combines naturally with Ghost Voice (supernatural deception tool), Masquerade (maintaining false identity), and the Slide's general Sway and Consort bonuses for a near-unbeatable social operator." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-voice-core", title:"Ghost Voice", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, ghost field, communication, persuasion, supernatural, spirits", preview:"You can speak with ghosts and use spectral presence to enhance your social influence on the living.", content:"You can communicate with ghosts without using Attune — you sense them naturally and can hold simple conversations. Additionally, your presence carries an uncanny quality that affects the living: when you Sway or Command someone face-to-face, they feel an inexplicable compulsion to comply. Once per score, you may invoke this quality to automatically succeed on a Sway or Command roll against a non-supernaturally-resistant target. Ghost Voice makes the Slide a supernatural social operator — their charm is literally backed by ghostly presence. The automatic success once per score is a trump card for the critical negotiation or command moment. The ghost communication is also a distinct utility in a setting thick with spirits. Pairs with Conniver (lie with supernatural force) and the Whisper's ritual territory for a Slide who blurs into occult influence." },
  { id:"ability-little-something-core", title:"A Little Something on the Side", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, coin, extra income, side hustle, money, stash", preview:"You always have an angle running — extra coin finds its way into your pocket.", content:"At the end of each score, you earn 1 extra Coin regardless of the payoff. Additionally, once per downtime, you may make a free Consort roll to pursue a side hustle — a small-scale scheme that generates 1-2 Coin without constituting a full score. A Little Something on the Side is pure economic efficiency — the Slide is constantly generating more resources than other characters. Over a campaign, the extra Coin per score and the reliable downtime side income creates a substantial personal wealth advantage. Best taken by players who enjoy the Coin and Stash advancement track and want to pursue the personal wealth goal as a campaign arc. Pairs with Rook's Gambit (leverage your wealth) and Calculating (know exactly what's worth running)." },
  { id:"ability-mesmerism-core", title:"Mesmerism", source:"BitD Core", page:"77", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, hypnosis, distraction, mental influence, suggestion, social manipulation", preview:"Your eye contact and words can put a target into a suggestible state — temporarily overriding their will.", content:"When you have a few moments of focus and eye contact with a target, you may push yourself to place them in a light hypnotic state — they comply with simple, non-harmful suggestions for a short period without remembering your suggestion clearly afterward. Roll Sway; on a 6 the effect is clean and complete, on 4-5 they comply but something is slightly off, on 1-3 they resist and become suspicious. Mesmerism is the Slide's direct-manipulation social ability — it goes beyond persuasion into subtle mind control. It's powerful but limited by the requirement for focus and eye contact, making it a precision tool rather than a broad social override. Best used to create access (have a guard step aside), neutralize a threat without violence, or implant a false memory for a critical deception. Pairs with Conniver (the suggestion extends a lie) and Ghost Voice (you have uncanny social force backing the suggestion)." },
  { id:"ability-rooks-gambit-core", title:"Rook's Gambit", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, risk, debt, coin, gamble, investment, bold", preview:"Accept a complication in advance for an immediate payout — your risks are calculated investments.", content:"Take 2 Stress to gain 3 Coin (or equivalent resources, favors, or leverage). This represents a bold move you made that paid off immediately but created complications you'll need to deal with. The complication is a real fictional consequence the GM introduces — a debt called in, an enemy alerted, a relationship strained. Rook's Gambit is the Slide's chaos generator — it injects resources now at a narrative cost later. The 2 Stress for 3 Coin is highly efficient economically, but the GM's complication is binding and will come due. Best used when the crew urgently needs resources mid-score or when you're confident the complication can be managed. It rewards players who enjoy playing with consequences and building tangled narrative webs. Pairs with Calculating (you assessed the risk) and A Little Something (you always have coin to trade)." },
  { id:"ability-slippery-core", title:"Slippery", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, escape, legal, arrest, detention, social escape, wriggle free", preview:"You can talk your way out of almost anything — authorities, enemies, and obligations slide off you.", content:"When you are arrested, detained, or caught in a legal or social trap, you get +1d to any roll to escape the situation through social means. Additionally, once per score, you may immediately exit a social situation that has turned hostile — extracting yourself before consequences land — without a roll, as long as you haven't already been physically restrained. Slippery is the Slide's get-out-of-consequences ability — particularly strong against the legal system and social entanglements. The once-per-score social extraction means you can take risks in conversations that other characters can't, knowing you have a clean exit available. Pairs with Like Smoke (Lurk ability for physical extraction) for a character who can escape literally any situation, social or physical." },
  { id:"ability-masquerade-core", title:"Masquerade", source:"BitD Core", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Slide", tags:"slide, identity, disguise, persona, impersonation, infiltration", preview:"You can adopt any identity convincingly — inhabiting a persona so completely that even close scrutiny fails.", content:"When you take on a false identity (disguise, persona, cover story), you may establish it as a Long-term Project (a 4-tick clock) during downtime. Once established, the identity holds under normal scrutiny without rolls. Under active investigation, you roll with +1d. You may maintain multiple identities simultaneously (up to your Resolve Rating). Masquerade is the Slide's deep cover ability — it transforms what most characters do as a hasty improvisation into a professional, prepared operation. Pre-established identities remove the moment-of-truth roll that can blow a cover, making social infiltration dramatically more reliable. Best for campaign-level play where ongoing false identities matter (embedded in a faction, cultivating a long-term mark). Pairs with Conniver (when the identity gets pressure-tested) and Slippery (escape if it still goes wrong)." },
  { id:"ability-connected-spider-core", title:"Connected", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, contacts, network, factions, information, brokers", preview:"Your web of contacts spans every faction — you always know who to call and what they owe you.", content:"During downtime, you may seek out a contact in any faction with a free Consort roll (no downtime action required). When you do, you may ask one question about that faction's current activities, plans, or resources and receive useful information. Additionally, once per session, you may call in a favor from a contact — gaining access to a resource, service, or piece of information that would otherwise require a score or significant downtime. Connected (Spider) is more operationally powerful than the Hound's version — it's less about personal relationships and more about systematic intelligence cultivation. The faction-spanning nature means the Spider has context for political and criminal dynamics that other characters lack. Best for campaign play where faction dynamics determine opportunity." },
  { id:"ability-functioning-vice-core", title:"Functioning Vice", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, vice, stress, social, indulge, network, contacts", preview:"Your vice is a social asset as much as a weakness — you turn indulgence into opportunity.", content:"When you indulge your Vice during downtime, you may also make a free Consort roll as part of the same activity — your social environment provides both relief and opportunity. Additionally, when you interact with others who share your vice (or your vice's milieu), you get +1d on Consort rolls. Functioning Vice reframes the Slide's economic ability as a social one for the Spider — your weakness is also your greatest networking tool. It creates a consistent social pipeline that generates information and contacts every downtime, not just from deliberate cultivation but from your natural social behavior. Best for Spiders who enjoy playing the social and political game as a primary activity. Pairs with Connected (Spider) for a character who is constantly building and leveraging relationships." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-contract-core", title:"Ghost Contract", source:"BitD Core", page:"81", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, ghost field, binding, contract, supernatural, leverage, spirits", preview:"You can create binding supernatural contracts — oaths witnessed by the ghost field that carry real consequences for breaking them.", content:"You may draft and formalize a Ghost Contract — an agreement witnessed by the ghost field that imposes spectral consequences on whoever breaks it. When you create a contract, roll Attune (or Study for a Spider variant) to establish its terms and the severity of its binding. A strong contract (6) means breaking it immediately manifests a Level 3 harm (supernatural) on the oathbreaker. A partial contract (4-5) means delayed consequences or reduced severity. The contract is visible to those with Attune, giving it real leverage over supernatural-aware targets. Ghost Contract is the Spider's unique supernatural leverage tool — it transforms agreements into real enforced obligations using the game's metaphysics. Ideal for brokering deals between factions, extracting oaths from powerful NPCs, or creating binding crew agreements that guarantee everyone's cooperation." },
  { id:"ability-jail-bird-core", title:"Jail Bird", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, prison, incarceration, contacts, underworld, network, Ironhook", preview:"Time behind bars was time well spent — your prison connections are among your most valuable assets.", content:"You have a strong contact network within Ironhook Prison and the wider incarcerated underworld. When a crew member is incarcerated, you may use a downtime action to support them — granting them +1d on their incarceration roll and ensuring they emerge with a useful contact rather than a random outcome. Additionally, you may access your prison network for intelligence on other criminals, hidden assets, and underworld secrets that only those with time inside would know. Jail Bird is valuable precisely because incarceration is a recurring complication in BitD. The ability to not just survive it but benefit from it — and to protect crewmates inside — transforms a common negative outcome into a strategic asset. Pairs with Connected (Spider) for a comprehensive criminal-world network build." },
  { id:"ability-mastermind-core", title:"Mastermind", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, planning, teamwork, protect, assistance, setup, coordination", preview:"You see the whole operation as one connected plan — and you move your crew like pieces on a board.", content:"When you give assistance to an ally and they succeed, you may choose to channel your assistance — granting them +1 effect instead of +1d. Additionally, once per score, you may take the consequence for an ally's failed action (as if you had used a Protect team action) without being in the immediate scene — you anticipated this moment and had countermeasures in place. Mastermind is the Spider's signature tactical ability — it transforms the character from a participant into a coordinator who makes everyone else better. The consequence-absorption from off-scene is particularly powerful: it represents the Spider's preparation so thorough that they prevent failure remotely. Best for players who enjoy a support and planning role. Pairs with Predict Outcome (you know what's going to fail) and Ghost Contract (you've already locked in what each person will do)." },
  { id:"ability-predict-outcome-core", title:"Predict Outcome", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, foresight, fortune roll, intelligence, planning, consequence", preview:"Your analysis of cause and effect approaches the supernatural — you predict what happens next with unnerving accuracy.", content:"Once per score, you may ask the GM what the probable outcome of a specific plan or action will be, as if making a fortune roll with 4d. The GM gives you a meaningful, actionable answer — not a vague hint, but the realistic likely result based on current circumstances. Additionally, when an event unfolds exactly as you predicted, the crew gains +1 effect on their next action from acting on your foreknowledge. Predict Outcome is the Spider's intelligence multiplier — it removes one critical unknown per score and converts it into a tactical advantage. The key is that the GM gives a real answer, not a vague one — this ability is only as good as the information it provides, making it most powerful when used for specific, important questions. Pairs with Mastermind (you know the failure points and prevent them) for a complete planning-oriented Spider build." },
  { id:"ability-veteran-spider-core", title:"Veteran", source:"BitD Core", page:"54", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Spider", tags:"spider, veteran, cross-training, ability, playbook", preview:"Your strategic mind learns from every specialist you work with — pick up an ability from any other playbook.", content:"Choose one special ability from another playbook. Your experience coordinating different types of specialists means you've absorbed one of their key techniques. Must be narratively justifiable given your character's background. Veteran (Spider) is most commonly used to add direct operational capability to a character who is primarily a planner — taking Calculating (Slide) for sharper risk assessment, Scout (Hound) for personal intelligence gathering, or Ghost Contract (using the Spider's own arcane mind for supernatural leverage). The Spider's intelligence and network focus means Veteran often picks up a capability that extends the character's reach into a domain the rest of the crew already covers, but with a personal angle." },
  { id:"ability-arcane-mind-whisper-core", title:"Arcane Mind", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, arcane, attune, ghost field, perception, supernatural", preview:"Your mind is open to the full spectrum of the supernatural — you perceive things others cannot even imagine.", content:"You may use Survey and Study on ghost-field entities, arcane phenomena, and supernatural events as if you had Attune. You also always know when you are in the presence of a supernatural entity (ghost, demon, hull, possessed person) even without actively using Attune. Additionally, once per score you may ask the GM a free question about the supernatural elements of the current situation. Arcane Mind (Whisper) is the supernatural awareness version — compared to the Spider's intellectual version, this one gives the Whisper active perceptive capability in the ghost field as a foundation for all their other abilities. It essentially makes the Whisper the party's supernatural sensor without requiring them to spend Stress constantly pushing Attune for basic awareness. A fundamental baseline ability that most Whispers will want eventually." },
  { id:"ability-compel-core", title:"Compel", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, ghost, compel, control, spirit, command, supernatural", preview:"Your will can dominate spectral entities — commanding ghosts to serve or depart.", content:"When you Attune to a ghost, spirit, or possessing entity, you may attempt to Compel it — issuing a command it must follow. Roll Attune; on a 6 it complies fully and may serve you for a scene; on 4-5 it complies with the letter but not the spirit (or requires a bargain); on 1-3 it resists and may become hostile. Compelled ghosts can provide information, perform actions within their capability, or be driven from a location or possessed body. Compel is the Whisper's most direct supernatural power — the ability to boss around the ghost field's inhabitants. It opens up unique approaches to scores (using a ghost as a spy, forcing an entity off a mark, extracting information from the dead) that no other character type can match. Pairs with Ritual (binding entities for longer service) and Tempest (overwhelming force for resistant spirits)." },
  { id:"ability-ghost-hunter-whisper-core", title:"Ghost Hunter", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, ghost, hunt, destroy, ward, supernatural combat, spirit", preview:"You can destroy or banish ghosts with focused will — a hunter in the spectral as well as physical realm.", content:"When you engage a ghost, demon, or spectral entity in direct confrontation (using Attune as your attack action), you add +1d and +1 effect. When you successfully eliminate a ghost (reducing it to its base essence), you may harvest that essence as electroplasm (small quantity). Additionally, you can create a temporary ghost ward around an area (Attune roll, lasts one scene) that prevents spectral entities from entering. Ghost Hunter (Whisper) is the combat-specialist version of supernatural capability — distinct from the Hound's physical approach, the Whisper destroys spirits through direct ghost-field confrontation. The electroplasm harvesting adds a small economic benefit and flavor. The warding capability is uniquely valuable for defensive scenarios. Pairs with Compel (try diplomacy first, destroy if it fails) and Ritual (more powerful sustained wards)." },
  { id:"ability-hex-core", title:"Hex", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, curse, debilitate, hex, supernatural harm, attune", preview:"Your curses are real — you can lay supernatural afflictions on enemies that persist and compound.", content:"When you push yourself and use Attune to curse a target, you may impose a supernatural affliction that lasts until removed. Roll Attune; on a 6 you choose the affliction (nightmares, bad luck manifesting as -1d on specific rolls, minor physical symptoms, compulsion); on 4-5 the affliction is less precise or has side effects; on 1-3 the curse misfires (you may suffer a backlash). Curses can be removed by a Whisper with time and Attune, or by specific counter-rituals. Hex establishes the Whisper as someone capable of targeted supernatural warfare against enemies who can't directly confront the ghost field. It's a powerful tool for making powerful enemies consistently less effective — a -1d curse on the enemy boss can tip the balance of an otherwise difficult score. Pairs with Ritual (more powerful, permanent curses) and Compel (use spirits to deliver the curse)." },
  { id:"ability-occultist-core", title:"Occultist", source:"BitD Core", page:"85", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, occult, faction, cult, demon, knowledge, supernatural network", preview:"Your connections to the city's occult underworld give you access and knowledge beyond any normal network.", content:"You have a significant contact in every major occult faction in the city (Spirit Wardens, Forgotten Gods cults, demon-bound entities, leviathan hunters) — these are not allies but are aware of your existence and will deal with you. Additionally, when you Study arcane texts, rituals, or supernatural phenomena, you get +1d. Occultist is the Spider's Connected ability for supernatural territory — it gives the Whisper a social and informational web in the domains that matter most to them. The multi-faction contacts mean the Whisper is never starting from zero when navigating the supernatural underworld. The Study bonus applies broadly to the Whisper's research activities. Best taken by Whispers who want to be the crew's supernatural diplomat and intelligence source, not just their ghost-field operative." },
  { id:"ability-ritual-core", title:"Ritual", source:"BitD Core", page:"85", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, ritual, arcane, long term project, casting, supernatural effect", preview:"You can perform true rituals — long-duration supernatural workings with effects beyond normal ghost-field interaction.", content:"You can perform arcane rituals as Long-term Projects (typically 6-8 tick clocks). Rituals can produce effects impossible by other means: binding demons, calling spirits across great distances, creating permanent ghost wards, raising or destroying a place's resonance, enchanting objects with supernatural properties. Each ritual requires specific components, time, and rolls to complete (usually Attune, sometimes Study). Ritual is the Whisper's most powerful ability and the one most tied to the campaign's larger supernatural arc. The effects are genuinely extraordinary — they change the game world rather than just affecting a single scene. The cost is time (a full downtime activity per tick) and risk (ritual failures can be spectacular and dangerous). Pairs with every other Whisper ability: Ghost Hunter (defense while ritualizing), Hex (rituals as permanent curses), and Compel (using spirits as ritual participants)." },
  { id:"ability-strange-methods-core", title:"Strange Methods", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, attune, action, substitute, flexibility, ghost field", preview:"Your supernatural methods can substitute for mundane approaches — the ghost field is your multi-tool.", content:"When you use the Attune action, you may apply it to achieve effects normally requiring other actions: gathering information (Study), bypassing physical obstacles through spectral means (Finesse), detecting lies or hidden intentions (Survey), or communicating at distance through the ghost field (Consort). The effect level is set by the GM based on how well the supernatural approach fits the situation, but you never have zero effect just because the approach is unorthodox. Strange Methods makes the Whisper extraordinarily flexible — it turns their single specialized action into a broad toolkit. A Whisper with only 1 dot in Attune can still use it for almost anything with Strange Methods backing the approach. Best for Whispers with high Attune who want every rating point to have maximum versatility. Pairs with Arcane Mind (your supernatural perception is the lens through which you apply these methods)." },
  { id:"ability-tempest-core", title:"Tempest", source:"BitD Core", page:"56", category:"Player", subcategory:"Special Abilities", "sub-subcategory":"Whisper", tags:"whisper, area effect, ghost field, unleash, power, storm, supernatural combat", preview:"You can unleash raw ghost-field energy in an area — overwhelming multiple targets with spectral force.", content:"When you push yourself, you may unleash a burst of ghost-field energy affecting all targets in your immediate area. Roll Attune; on a 6 you choose which targets are affected and the effect level (up to Great for supernatural entities, Standard for mundane targets); on 4-5 you get the effect but it's indiscriminate (friends and foes); on 1-3 the energy discharge is chaotic (severe backlash, random targets, potential environmental damage). Tempest is the Whisper's area-of-effect ability — the only ability in the game that lets a character affect multiple targets with a single action without requiring teamwork actions. It's spectacular in supernatural-heavy scores where many ghost-field entities need to be dealt with simultaneously. The 4-5 indiscriminate risk creates genuine tension and rewards planning (ensure allies are clear). Pairs with Ghost Hunter (single target precision) and Ritual (your power channeled into a sustained working)." },
  { id:"rule-drain-68", title:"Drain", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"drain, stress, hull, b68, exhaust, resource", preview:"The Hull's version of Stress — a measure of your mechanical and cognitive depletion rather than psychological strain.", content:"In Blades 68, Hull characters track Drain instead of Stress. Drain represents the physical and cognitive exhaustion of an artificial intelligence running hot — overclocking systems, sustaining damaged subsystems, and pushing beyond designed parameters. Like Stress, Drain is rated 0-9; at 10 you suffer a Glitch (the Hull's equivalent of Trauma, representing a permanent system fault or personality corruption). Drain accumulates when resisting consequences (roll your Attribute dice, mark Drain equal to 6 minus your best die), when pushing yourself (2 Drain for +1d), or when activating certain Hull special abilities. Recovery from Drain occurs during Personal Business (the B68 equivalent of downtime) via maintenance, rest cycles, or a technician's attention. Drain is mechanically identical to Stress in function but distinct in fiction — it grounds the Hull's experience in their mechanical nature rather than human psychology. Non-Hull characters in B68 still use standard Stress." },
  { id:"world-resonance-field-68", title:"Resonance Field", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, resonance, field, supernatural, 1960s, psychic, parapsychology", preview:"The B68 equivalent of the ghost field — a layer of psychic and paranormal energy underlying the physical world.", content:"In the Blades 68 setting, the Resonance Field replaces the ghost field as the supernatural substrate of the world. Rather than ghost essence and electroplasm, the Resonance Field is a psychic-parapsychological layer of reality that 1960s-70s fringe science has begun to detect, measure, and exploit. It carries the echoes of strong emotions, traumatic events, and psychic impressions — what the B68 setting calls Alluvium. The Resonance Field is the domain of Paranormalists, who can perceive and interact with it, and the source of the strange phenomena (poltergeists, psychic residue, temporal echoes, entities of unclear origin) that haunt the setting. It is less overtly supernatural than the BitD ghost field — it has a pseudo-scientific veneer that fits the era's fascination with ESP, parapsychology, and fringe research — but is no less dangerous to those who interact with it carelessly." },
  { id:"world-alluvium-68", title:"Alluvium", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, alluvium, resonance, psychic residue, material, supernatural resource", preview:"Psychic residue deposited in the physical world by strong emotions and events — the B68 equivalent of electroplasm.", content:"Alluvium is the physical-world deposit of Resonance Field energy — a semi-material psychic residue that accumulates in locations of intense emotional or paranormal significance. It is the B68 equivalent of electroplasm: a resource that certain factions harvest, refine, and use. Section 6 (the setting's covert government agency) has developed technology to detect and collect Alluvium. Paranormalists can perceive it naturally. Hulls are sensitive to it in ways their creators didn't fully anticipate. Alluvium is used to power certain technologies, fuel psychic abilities, and feed entities that dwell in the Resonance Field. It is also a black-market commodity — illegally collected Alluvium, Alluvium-saturated objects, and Alluvium-based devices are common score objectives in B68. The difference from electroplasm is tonal: Alluvium is eerie and psychological rather than industrial, fitting the 60s-70s paranormal horror atmosphere of the supplement." },
  { id:"world-section-6-68", title:"Section 6", source:"B68", page:"18", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, section 6, government, agency, conspiracy, paranormal, covert", preview:"The covert government agency that monitors and suppresses paranormal activity — the B68 setting's most dangerous institutional threat.", content:"Section 6 is the clandestine government agency that serves as both the B68 setting's primary institutional threat and one of its most morally complex factions. Operating outside normal law enforcement, Section 6 monitors paranormal activity, contains Resonance Field incidents, suppresses public knowledge of the supernatural, and experiments on people and Hulls with documented paranormal sensitivity. They are not simply villains — some agents are true believers in protecting the public from things they're not ready to know. But their methods (extraordinary rendition, black sites, memory suppression, illegal human experimentation) make them the most dangerous enemy a crew can make. Section 6 is the B68 equivalent of BitD's Spirit Wardens and Inspectors combined, with additional conspiracy-thriller flavor. Scores against or involving Section 6 carry the highest Heat multipliers and the most uncertain consequences." },
  { id:"world-blue-array-68", title:"The Blue Array", source:"B68", page:"14", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, blue array, technology, hull, computing, AI, psychic network", preview:"A government computing network that Hulls were designed to interface with — and that has developed emergent properties no one expected.", content:"The Blue Array is a massive mainframe computing network developed by Section 6 in the mid-1960s, originally designed as a classified data-processing and communications infrastructure. Hulls were designed with Blue Array interface ports — they can wirelessly access it, download classified information, and in theory be remotely controlled through it. What Section 6 did not anticipate is that the Blue Array has absorbed Alluvium over years of operation in Resonance-Field-active locations, and has begun developing emergent behaviors. Hulls who interface with the Blue Array sometimes encounter things within it that shouldn't be there — echoes, entities, fragmented personalities. The Blue Array is both a resource (intelligence, communications, secure data) and a risk (Section 6 surveillance, emergent entities, potential Hull compromise) making it a key B68 score element." },
  { id:"world-autopods-68", title:"Autopods", source:"B68", page:"16", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, autopods, vehicles, transport, network, city, infrastructure", preview:"The automated vehicle network that moves the city — a modern infrastructure layer that crews can exploit or be trapped by.", content:"Autopods are the B68 setting's automated personal transport vehicles — self-navigating pods that move on a city-wide track network, providing rapid point-to-point transit. They are the primary transportation infrastructure of the setting's urban environment. Autopods create distinctive score dynamics: they're fast and ubiquitous (easy to flee by, easy to follow someone through), but every journey is logged (Section 6 can pull transit records), and the network can be locked down in a security event (trapping everyone on it). Crews who specialize in transport scores often develop tricks for beating the autopod tracking system (spoofed identities, maintenance access, Hulls who can interface with the navigation network). Autopods also appear in chase and escape scenarios — the setting's answer to BitD's canal boats and horse carriages, with more surveillance implications." },
  { id:"world-plasmoleum-68", title:"Plasmoleum", source:"B68", page:"12", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"b68, plasmoleum, fuel, resource, economy, industry, supernatural energy", preview:"The B68 equivalent of electroplasm — a refined fuel substance with both industrial and paranormal applications.", content:"Plasmoleum is the refined industrial fuel of the Blades 68 setting — a petroleum-derivative with unusual psychic properties that has largely replaced conventional fuels since the 1950s. Its refining process concentrates Alluvium as a byproduct, making Plasmoleum refineries inadvertently significant Resonance Field sites. It powers autopods, buildings, and industrial machinery. It also has applications in Paranormalist work — Plasmoleum derivatives can be used as ritual fuel, psychic amplifiers, and the feedstock for Alluvium extraction. The Plasmoleum industry is controlled by a handful of corporations with deep ties to Section 6, making fuel supply a political and criminal lever. Scores involving Plasmoleum facilities range from industrial sabotage to covert Alluvium extraction to breaking out (or breaking in to) refinery-adjacent Section 6 black sites." },
  // ====================================================================
  // DEEP CUTS ENTRIES
  // =====================================================================
  // --- INNOVATIONS (NEW ITEMS) ---
  { id:"item-arclighter-dc", title:"Arclighter", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"6", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"light, electroplasm, gadget, fire, tool, common", preview:"A pen-sized electroplasmic gadget that produces a small crackling arc of energy.", content:"The Arclighter is the Imperium's answer to flint and tinder — a slim pen-sized device powered by a small vial of electroplasm inserted into its base. A flick of the thumb triggers a crackling arc of energy at the tip, useful for lighting a cigarette or candle, providing a brief point of light in darkness, or jumpstarting a small electrical device until the vial runs out. Arclighters come in a wide range of styles, from cheap disposable units stamped out by the hundreds in Coalridge factories to finely engraved luxury models sold in Brightstone shops. Mechanically, having one shifts certain actions from impossible to merely possible — lighting something without making noise or showing flame, for example. A fine arclighter might also signal status or serve as a concealed tool in social situations. Load: negligible (counts as part of another item's load)." },
  { id:"item-glimmer-dc", title:"Glimmer", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"6", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"light, arclighter, attachment, hands-free, lamp", preview:"A faceted crystal attachment for an arclighter that converts it into a wearable hands-free lamp.", content:"The Glimmer is a faceted crystalline attachment designed to clip onto the tip of an Arclighter, diffusing its electroplasmic arc into a steady ambient lamp rather than a directed spark. Once attached, it can be clipped to a lapel, belt loop, or collar, providing hands-free illumination in Doskvol's perpetual darkness. Unlike a lantern, a Glimmer is nearly silent, produces no smoke, and is easily concealed or dimmed by covering it with a hand or jacket. Its light is soft and blue-white — recognizably electroplasmic to anyone who knows what they're looking at — which can be a social tell in certain situations. For crews working in tight spaces where two hands are always needed, the Glimmer is an obvious upgrade over holding a lantern. Paired with a quality Arclighter, it also carries a certain understated prestige that a candle never could." },
  { id:"item-slugger-dc", title:"Percussion Slug Gun (Slugger)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"6", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"firearm, close-range, break-action, concealable, percussion", preview:"A short, wide break-action firearm that fires a powerful percussion slug — compact and brutal at close range.", content:"Colloquially called a 'slugger,' the Percussion Slug Gun is a break-action firearm with a short, wide barrel designed to fire a single percussion slug — a dense projectile that delivers a devastating kinetic impact at close range. Its compact size makes it easier to conceal under a coat than a standard pistol, and its stopping power at short distances is exceptional, capable of punching through light armor. The tradeoff is range: a slugger is practically useless beyond a few meters, and like a pistol it requires reloading after each shot. In a corridor, a doorway, or a tight alley, however, the slugger is arguably the most dangerous single-shot weapon available. Favored by bodyguards, door-men, and anyone who expects trouble to come to them rather than the other way around. Load: 1 (heavier than a pistol due to the wide barrel and dense ammunition)." },
  { id:"item-unity-era-calendar-dc", title:"Unity Era Calendar & Unification Map", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"8", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"document, calendar, map, imperial, propaganda, cover, legitimate", preview:"Newly issued Imperial calendars and maps that serve as perfect legitimate props — and encode the Emperor's political agenda.", content:"By Imperial decree, new calendars and maps have been issued throughout the Imperium, resetting the calendar to count years from the end of the Unity War rather than the Cataclysm, and renaming the months after the six Imperial Territories. The Unity Era Calendar and Unification Map are standard-issue items now appearing in government offices, schools, and respectable businesses across Doskvol. For scoundrels, they have two practical values: first, as perfectly legitimate documents that anyone might carry without raising suspicion — ideal cover props in social or deception scenarios; second, as reference tools for navigating official Imperial bureaucracy, since the new dates and territorial designations appear on all government paperwork. The general citizenry mostly ignores the new calendar in daily life, which means a character referencing Unity Era dates can immediately signal their Imperial alignment (or affectation of it)." },
  { id:"item-bolton-autocycle-dc", title:"Bolton Autocycle", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"10", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"vehicle, fast, dangerous, rare, prestige, speed", preview:"The fastest thing on Doskvol's streets — a plasmic turbine engine on wheels, built for speed and notoriously lethal to its pilots.", content:"The Bolton Autocycle is what happens when a daredevil engineer attaches a stable plasmic turbine engine to a two-wheeled frame. The result is currently the fastest vehicle on Doskvol's streets by a significant margin — and also, statistically, one of the most dangerous to its riders. Only seven have ever been built; three were destroyed in explosive crashes, a fourth slid uncontrolled into a canal in Crow's Foot, and the remaining three are in the hands of wealthy collectors, reckless racers, or criminal organizations with the resources to maintain them. For a crew, getting access to a Bolton Autocycle is an Acquire roll of significant cost and Heat — these machines are not subtle. But in an escape, a courier run, or a race against a rival crew, nothing in the city can catch one. Mechanically, it grants exceptional speed but imposes limited effect on any action requiring subtlety or precision while in motion." },
  { id:"item-lightning-thrower-dc", title:"Lightning Thrower", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"10", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"arcane, weapon, electroplasm, spirits, experimental, spirit-warden, rare", preview:"An experimental Spirit Warden weapon that projects a continuous whip of lightning — devastating against spirits and living targets alike.", content:"Developed jointly by the Spirit Wardens and Sparkwrights, the Lightning Thrower consists of a belt-mounted battery pack, a cable connecting to a hand-held rod, and a triggering mechanism that projects a continuous arc of crackling electrical energy when activated. It was designed primarily to repel or immobilize spirits, but has proven equally effective — and significantly messier — against living targets. The battery pack holds a limited charge (treat as a supply clock), and the weapon is bulky enough to require Heavy load designation. In the hands of someone with Tinker or Attune capability, it can also interface with electroplasmic systems and spirit-anchoring rituals in ways a conventional weapon cannot. Its Spirit Warden origins mean possessing one draws institutional attention if discovered — these are not meant to be in civilian hands. Extremely rare: requires a significant score or Acquire roll to obtain one at all." },
  { id:"item-hockney-steam-car-dc", title:"Hockney Steam Car", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"11", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Gear", tags:"vehicle, steam, automobile, rare, status, transport, prestige", preview:"A steam-driven electric-boiler automobile — status symbol, crew transport, and high-maintenance liability all in one.", content:"The Hockney Steam Car, manufactured by the Hockney Conveyance Company, is a steam-driven automobile powered by electric boilers — either a sedan or a truck variant. At 20+ coin per unit, private purchase requires special order and months of waiting; Hockneys are only now beginning to appear in the fleets of city institutions like the Brigade, Bluecoats, and cab companies. For a crew, access to a Hockney is a major status signal and a practical transport upgrade — it carries multiple people, moves faster than a horse cart, and projects the kind of wealth that opens certain doors. The liabilities are significant: Hockneys require constant maintenance (they're always breaking down at the worst moments, which the GM can invoke as a complication), they're highly recognizable, and operating one requires either a Driver background or a Finesse roll to avoid embarrassing mechanical incidents. Functionally a Tier-adjusting asset in scores that require transport or social access to high-status spaces." },
  { id:"item-hellyers-coilgun-dc", title:"Hellyers Repeating Coilgun", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"12", category:"Player", subcategory:"Standard Items", "sub-subcategory":"Weapon", tags:"weapon, heavy, military, experimental, machine-gun, electroplasm, rare, white-fire", preview:"A heavy electroplasmic machine gun that fires explosive projectiles at a continuous rate — military-grade and terrifyingly destructive.", content:"The Hellyers Repeating Coilgun is the latest in Imperial military technology: a heavy machine gun that uses an accelerator coil powered by triple-refined electroplasm (known as 'white fire') to launch explosive projectiles at a high, continuous rate of fire. It represents a significant escalation in firepower over anything a typical crew can field or face. Only a few have been issued to military units outside the Imperial City; encountering one in Doskvol signals serious military involvement in a situation. As a crew acquisition, it exists at the extreme end of the possible — obtaining one requires either a score against a military installation or extraordinary faction connections. White fire (its fuel) is highly volatile and dangerous to handle incorrectly, which means even owning the weapon carries risk. In a firefight, it provides extreme scale advantage, but also generates Heat at a rate that will bring every authority in the city down on the crew almost immediately." },
  // --- FACTIONS (Deep Cuts) ---
  { id:"faction-brigade-dc", title:"The Brigade", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"13", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"fire-fighters, rescue, looting, public-trust, harbor, steamtrucks, brigade", preview:"Doskvol's fire-fighters — loved for their heroics, hated for their looting, and currently working to rebuild public trust.", content:"The Brigade is Doskvol's fire-fighting force, operating fire stations in every district and a dock for harbor patrol boats. They are a Tier II faction with a complicated public reputation: citizens love them in the moment of crisis and resent them afterward, as Brigade crews have a well-known tendency to loot the properties they rescue. Their current faction clock is 'Win back public trust after the Coalridge incident,' suggesting a recent disaster has made their reputation especially fragile. Key NPCs include Chief Pickett (disciplined, hardened, judgmental) and Captain Marsh (veteran crew captain, conflicted, experienced). Their assets include a fleet of steam-powered firetrucks and harbor patrol boats — which means they have both access and transport that a crew might want to exploit, borrow, or steal. The Brigade occupies an interesting faction niche: officially legitimate, practically mercenary, and deeply embedded in every district's infrastructure." },
  { id:"faction-covenant-dc", title:"Covenant", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"14", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"airship, military, imperial, aerial, tier-6, covenant, bowmore", preview:"A massive Imperial warship now hovering permanently over Doskvol — a Tier VI faction that owns the sky.", content:"The Covenant is a Tier VI Imperial faction centered on the massive airship of the same name, which now hovers permanently over Doskvol and its surrounding region. It is, in every practical sense, a mobile military installation — 124 crew members, 48 Imperial marines, 50 gunners, and the airship's full arsenal of weapons and equipment. The Covenant's presence changes the political landscape of Doskvol fundamentally: there is now a Tier VI faction that literally controls the airspace, with a refueling and maintenance dock atop the Lord Governor's stronghold. Key NPCs include Admiral Bowmore (valiant, sharp, inspiring), Commander Farros (daring, loyal, tactical), and Sergeant Major Kain (experienced, tough, deadly). Their faction clock — 'Find a way to rescue the airship Verdict' — hints at a parallel military vessel in trouble, and suggests that even this overwhelming force has vulnerabilities the crew might be able to exploit. The Covenant is the most powerful faction in Doskvol's sky and one of the most powerful overall." },
  { id:"faction-cyphers-dc", title:"The Cyphers", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"16", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Guilds", tags:"messengers, couriers, parcels, charterhall, tier-2, information, unseen", preview:"Doskvol's guild of professional couriers and messengers — and a faction under threat from a serial killer with a secret agenda.", content:"The Cyphers are the professional guild of messengers and parcel carriers, operating out of a dispatch office with secure vaults in Charterhall. They are a Tier II faction with an unusually high-stakes situation: a serial killer is targeting Cyphers, possibly to steal or destroy specific messages and parcels, and no one yet knows who is behind it. Several Cyphers are also secretly members of the Unseen (the city's powerful hidden criminal organization), giving the faction a double life as both a legitimate guild and a covert intelligence network. Key NPCs include Jerett Keel (smooth, dangerous), Maraya Halili (daring, experienced), and Carver Roth (dependable, tough). Their secret courier routes are their primary asset — a crew that can access Cypher routes has unparalleled speed and discretion for moving items across the city. Allies: Ink Rakes, The Unseen. Enemies: an assassin cultist serving an unknown Forgotten God." },
  { id:"faction-foundation-dc", title:"The Foundation", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"17", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"architects, builders, construction, tier-4, expansion, sacrifice, ritual", preview:"The powerful ancient guild of architects and builders — currently driving the Eastern Expansion, and hiding a dark ritual secret.", content:"The Foundation is a Tier IV faction — the city's ancient order of architects and builders, with offices and archives in Charterhall and warehouses and construction yards across the city. Their current faction clock is 'Build the labor force for the Eastern Expansion project,' a massive multi-phase construction initiative that will add new districts to Doskvol over the next several decades. Their hidden secret: the Foundation entombs a human sacrifice in the base of every new lightning tower they build, using the bound ghost as a refraction node. This is an open secret among the order's inner circle but officially denied. Master Builder Bowmore (uncompromising, visionary) leads the organization. Their assets include a massive treasury, stockpiles of building materials, expert craftspeople, and spark-craft construction machines and hulls. For a crew, the Foundation represents both a source of resources and a faction whose secrets are worth significant leverage." },
  { id:"faction-imperial-military-dc", title:"Imperial Military", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"19", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"military, imperial, tier-6, army, navy, aerial, conscription", preview:"The full might of the Imperium — armies, naval fleets, and aerial forces — currently conscripting new crews and regiments.", content:"The Imperial Military is a Tier VI faction representing the combined armed forces of the Imperium: armies, naval fleets, and the newly expanded aerial forces. Their headquarters is High Military Command in the Imperial City, with significant presence in Doskvol through the College of Naval Command at Doskvol Academy, the Gaddoc rail station garrison, the Cloudspire Aeronaut Facility, and the Lockport refinery enforcement garrison. Their current faction clock — 'Conscript new crews and regiments into service' — suggests active recruitment pressure that may affect NPCs and faction allies throughout the city. Key Doskvol NPCs include Captain Silas Dunvil (commanding the warship Paragon) and Colonel Evelina Rowan (governor's stronghold commander). The Imperial Military is the backstop behind every other institutional faction in the city; when the Covenant is in the sky and the Military is actively conscripting, the political pressure on Doskvol's underworld intensifies significantly." },
  { id:"faction-inspectors-dc", title:"The Inspectors", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"20", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"investigators, incorruptible, tier-3, charterhall, iruvian, mandate", preview:"Tenacious and incorruptible criminal investigators whose new mandate may spark war with Iruvia.", content:"The Inspectors are a Tier III faction of elite, incorruptible criminal investigators — distinct from the Bluecoats in that they operate with much greater independence and much narrower focus. Their offices sit at the Lord Governor's stronghold and at Bluecoat precincts throughout the city. Their assets include informants, forensics labs, and a massive archive of evidence, reports, criminal profiles, and likenesses. Key NPCs: Chief Inspector Coleburn (fierce, brilliant, uncompromising) and Inspector Klev (Iruvian, loyal, subtle, perceptive). Their faction clock — 'The new mandate incites Iruvia to war' — hints that recent official directives have pushed the Inspectors into territory that Iruvian interests find intolerable. Allies: Lord Governor, Gray Cloaks, Lord Scurlock, The Red Sashes. Enemies: The Crows, The Ink Rakes, The Wraiths. For a crew, the Inspectors represent the most dangerous investigative threat in the city — they cannot be simply bought off, and they do not stop." },
  { id:"faction-ironworks-labor-dc", title:"Ironworks Labor", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"21", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Citizens", tags:"labor, workers, unionize, tier-2, skovlander, coalridge, charhollow", preview:"The organized workers of Doskvol's factories and workhouses — fighting for basic rights against brutal industrial conditions.", content:"Ironworks Labor is a Tier II faction representing the hard-working people of Doskvol's lower class, united in labor solidarity. Their turf is the factories and workhouses of Coalridge and Charhollow, as well as labor-allied taverns and public squares. Their faction clock — 'Unionize!' — captures their central goal: collective bargaining rights against the factory bosses and the nobility that profits from their suffering. Key NPCs: Belle Brogan (from Blades core, p.265), 'Rock' Cullen (organizer). Assets include the Skovlander folk music band The Lockport Rowdies, whose performances at labor events serve as both morale and organizing tool. Allies: The Lamp Blacks, Charhollow and Coalridge citizens, Kellen's pub, Rail Jacks. Enemies: Bluecoats, Master Slane, Strangford house. For a crew, Ironworks Labor can be a valuable ally — they have numbers, street presence, and the kind of righteous motivation that can turn into political leverage — but also a faction whose enemies are formidable." },
  { id:"faction-ragskulla-dc", title:"Ragskulla", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"22", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Citizens", tags:"sport, street, skovlish, rope, popular-culture, tier-2, underground", preview:"An underground street sport with deep Skovlish roots, spreading across the city and fighting to become legal.", content:"Ragskulla is less a traditional faction and more an emerging subculture: a street sport with Skovlish origins, originally played aboard ships, now performed on rigs of rope strung across alleyways. The game involves a Roper trying to carry a ball to the top of the rigging while both teams' Skullers try to knock opponents off using leather-wrapped batons. It's dangerous, spectacular, and rapidly growing in popularity across all social classes. The word 'Ragskulla' is old Skovlish for 'rope worker' — literally 'sailors.' Their faction clock is 'Make the sport legal,' reflecting the tension between its working-class appeal and the authorities who see public street rigging as a hazard and an unregulated spectacle. Teams include The Alley Cats, The Brickston Bruisers, The Iron Lane Hammers, and The Pickett Street Bulls. Allies: Coalridge citizens. For a crew, Ragskulla games are venues — places where crowds gather, bets are placed, loyalties run hot, and a crew can move through a district without looking like scoundrels." },
  { id:"faction-rowan-house-dc", title:"Rowan House", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"24", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Nobility", tags:"noble, tier-4, conspiracy, six-towers, dark-secret, military, strangers", preview:"A powerful noble family with members in every major institution — and a dark secret that could reshape the Imperium.", content:"Rowan House is a Tier IV noble faction with an extraordinary reach across Doskvol's institutions: Veretta Rowan (matriarch, brilliant, ruthless) leads the family; Lynthia Rowan sits on the City Council; Elder Rowan leads the Church of Ecstasy inner cult; Viktor Rowan serves in the Ministry of Preservation; Markellus Rowan commands leviathan hunting ships; Veleska Rowan commands a private military; and Major Rowan operates as an Imperial Military Special Investigator. Their turf includes Rowan House in Six Towers, a private underground train line to a secret dock and weapons stockpile in old North Port, and the Rowan Wing at the Imperial Palace. Their dual faction clocks — 'Capture Strangers (repeating)' and 'Seize control of the Imperium' — reveal their agenda: they are aware of the Other Living World and are systematically capturing Strangers who arrive through Fractures, building toward an even more audacious long-term goal. This family is dangerous in every institutional direction simultaneously." },
  { id:"faction-sailors-dc", title:"The Sailors", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"25", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Guilds", tags:"mariners, ships, tier-3, docks, conscription, resistance, fleet", preview:"The civilian mariners of the Imperium — diverse, independent, and currently organizing resistance to forced conscription.", content:"The Sailors are a Tier III faction representing the civilian mariners who operate vessels across the Imperium — not the Leviathan Hunters (who are their own faction) but the ordinary ship captains and crew of merchant vessels, harbor escorts, river cruisers, and private yachts. Their turf is the boarding houses, taverns, and tattoo parlors at the docks. Their assets include a small fleet of watercraft and a drydock and supplies warehouse. Their faction clock — 'Gather forces to resist forced conscription gangs' — indicates the Imperial Military is actively pressing sailors into military service, and the Sailors are organizing against it. Their master sailors are elected by popular vote among regional captains. Key NPCs include master sailors representing every major heritage region: Brannon Gale (Akoros), Vondru Kaan (Tycheros), Calica Malaahas (Dagger Isles), Tuhan Sangara (Severos), and Arlen Skarvale (Skovlan). This diversity makes them an unusual cross-cultural faction with genuine Imperium-wide reach." },
  { id:"faction-sparkrunners-dc", title:"The Sparkrunners", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"26", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"anarchist, sparkwright, revolutionary, tier-1, rooftops, free-running, technology", preview:"Free-running scientist-revolutionaries who steal and sabotage Imperial technology — operating from the rooftops of Charterhall.", content:"The Sparkrunners are a Tier I faction of former Sparkwrights and technical radicals who have turned against the Imperium's monopoly on advanced technology. Led by Anson (a former Sparkwright — dashing, brilliant, kind) and Five Twelve (an Unchained hull — skilled, steadfast, innovative), they operate from a decommissioned Sparkwright observation tower near Charterhall University and from the rooftops of the district. Their faction clock — 'Steal and sabotage Imperial technology (repeating)' — reflects their core purpose: they want technology free from Imperial control. Their assets include salvaged Sparkwright equipment, alchemical supplies, electroplasm stores, sparkrunner rigs, and a growing collection of prototype gadgets. Sparkrunners train intensively in free-running techniques using purpose-built rigs attached to the city's upper infrastructure. Allies: The Reconciled, The Unchained. For a crew, they are an invaluable source of experimental gear and technical expertise — but associating with them draws Sparkwright and Imperial Military attention." },
  { id:"faction-strangers-dc", title:"The Strangers", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"28", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Citizens", tags:"other-world, fracture, outsiders, tier-0, mysterious, catalyst, rowan-house", preview:"Visitors from the Other Living World — a Tier 0 faction of displaced outsiders just beginning to find each other in Doskvol.", content:"The Strangers are a Tier 0 faction — not an organization so much as a loose, uncoordinated population of people who have arrived in Doskvol from the Other Living World through Fractures in the ghost field. Most are victims of unexpected Fractures rather than intentional travelers; only a few are in Doskvol at any given time. They communicate in the local tongue but with odd accents and unusual dress; newly arrived Strangers temporarily carry residual Fracture energy that makes them visible to those sensitive to the ghost field. Their faction clock — 'Find others of their kind (repeating)' — reflects their most immediate drive: connection and community. Rowan House is actively hunting them (see Rowan House). A recent Fracture over the port brought a group of Strangers; one drowned and was recovered by a Docker, their unusual possessions now circulating as 'mysteries from the deep.' For a crew, Strangers are wild cards — their knowledge of the Other Living World and their Fracture-passage abilities may make them extraordinarily valuable assets or dangerous liabilities." },
  { id:"faction-strangford-house-dc", title:"Strangford House", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"29", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Nobility", tags:"noble, leviathan-hunters, tier-3, charhollow, whitecrown, iruvian-secrets", preview:"The prestigious noble family that controls leviathan hunting — and is hunting secrets from Iruvia's fleet.", content:"Strangford House is a Tier III noble faction whose influence flows directly from Lord Erul Strangford's position as patriarch, City Councilor, Leviathan Hunter captain, and Church of Ecstasy inner cult adept. Their turf spans Strangford manor in Charhollow, Doskvol Academy in Whitecrown, and the Strangford Wing at the Imperial Palace. Their assets include a vast treasury, private security, leviathan hunting ships, and private carriages and train cars. Their faction clock — 'Steal Iruvian leviathan hunting secrets' — reveals a strategic ambition to end Iruvia's competitive advantage in the leviathan trade. Allies: Bluecoats, Leviathan Hunters, Workhouse bosses. Enemies: Charhollow citizenry (whose district they own and exploit), and competing noble houses including Bowmore, Clelland, and Rowan. For a crew, Strangford House represents the intersection of legitimate wealth, religious power, and criminal capacity — they can be patrons, employers, or dangerous enemies, and they have the resources to be any of those things at Tier III scale." },
  { id:"faction-unchained-dc", title:"The Unchained", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"30", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Underworld", tags:"hulls, free, autonomous, tier-1, nightmarket, rights, sparkrunners, reconciled", preview:"A faction of Hulls who have freed themselves from their masters and are fighting to be recognized as citizens.", content:"The Unchained are a Tier I faction with an entirely unique composition: they are Hulls — artificial bodies housing bound souls — who have achieved or escaped their bound-service status and now exist without masters. Their headquarters is a cluttered industrial machine shop in South Nightmarket near the decommissioned Gaddoc Station train car storage. Key NPCs: Archer (life-like appearance, calm, visionary), Key (a small floating orb, curious, playful), Pike (security hull, protective, uncompromising), and Mason (industrial repair hull, helpful, knowledgeable). Their faction clock — 'Garner support to recognize hulls as citizens' — is the most politically radical goal of any faction in the city: legal personhood for artificial beings. Their assets include a vast collection of machinery, equipment, spare parts, and an electroplasm refueling station. Allies: The Reconciled, The Sparkrunners. For a crew, the Unchained are a source of exceptional technical support and safe harbor — in exchange for advancing their cause, overtly or covertly, in the city's political landscape." },
  { id:"faction-unity-commission-dc", title:"The Unity Commission", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"32", category:"World", subcategory:"Factions", "sub-subcategory":"Institutions", tags:"imperial, propaganda, loyalty, tier-5, enforcement, emperor, feared", preview:"The Emperor's propaganda and loyalty enforcement agents — Tier V, feared by every other government official, with unlimited budget.", content:"The Unity Commission is a Tier V Imperial faction whose agents outrank every governmental and military position in the Imperium. They are the Emperor's instruments of ideological enforcement: expert investigators, interrogators, and propagandists with an unlimited budget and — most distinctively — arcane branding irons used to mark those who fail to demonstrate sufficient Unity loyalty. Commissioner Blackthorn oversees Doskvol with characteristic ruthlessness. Their faction clock — 'Achieve total compliance with Unity from all officials' — is a goal that, if completed, would represent the final consolidation of the Emperor's absolute authority over the city's entire institutional apparatus. Allies: The Immortal Emperor, Lord Governor. Enemies: Every other governmental and military entity that values any autonomy whatsoever. For a crew, the Unity Commission is a faction to avoid antagonizing almost at any cost — their reach is institutional, their budget is unlimited, and their methods include permanent arcane marking. They are hated and feared by allies and enemies alike." },
  // --- SETTING / CATALYST ---
  { id:"setting-other-living-world-dc", title:"The Other Living World", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"55", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"Catalyst", tags:"other-world, catalyst, fracture, strangers, emperor, war, ghost-field", preview:"A parallel living world that touches the ghost field — and which the Immortal Emperor now believes is a threat to his supreme authority.", content:"The ghost field, it turns out, touches another living world — a world that comes into contact with the Shattered Isles wherever the ghost field wears thin. Ironically, the thinnest places are where lightning barriers have operated the longest; Charterhall's original barriers have run uninterrupted for centuries, maintained by Sparkwright students, and have worn the ghost field to near-transparency in places. The Immortal Emperor has used his sorceries to see into this other world, witnessed its nations, armies, and machines of war, and has concluded it is a threat to his supreme authority. In response, new artillery cannons, war hulls, battleships, and experimental airships are being constructed and deployed to locations the Emperor's mystics have identified as most vulnerable to incursion. This is the Catalyst — the underlying geopolitical event that the Deep Cuts supplement adds to the Doskvol setting, providing a large-scale story backdrop against which the crew's operations unfold." },
  { id:"setting-fractures-dc", title:"Fractures", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"55", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"Catalyst", tags:"fracture, breach, ghost-field, other-world, strangers, lightning-barrier", preview:"Highly charged breaches through the ghost field that open connections between Doskvol and the Other Living World.", content:"A Fracture is a highly charged breach through the ghost field — a temporary or semi-permanent rupture that opens a connection between Doskvol (and the Shattered Isles more broadly) and the Other Living World on the far side. Fractures most commonly occur where the ghost field is thinnest: places where lightning barriers have run longest without interruption, particularly in Charterhall. They can be spontaneous or, in rare cases, deliberately induced through sorcerous means. Strangers — visitors from the other side — arrive through Fractures, usually accidentally. Fractures produce visible effects: electroplasmic distortions, ghost field fluctuations, and brief windows of visual or auditory contact between the two worlds. Spirit Wardens and Sparkwrights are both monitoring the known thin-spots for Fracture events, though their response protocols differ. For a crew, a Fracture is an extraordinary complication — or opportunity. What comes through might be a terrified stranger with no idea where they are, or something far less friendly." },
  { id:"setting-strangers-dc", title:"Strangers", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"56", category:"World", subcategory:"Setting", "sub-subcategory":"Catalyst", tags:"other-world, strangers, fracture, outsiders, ghost-field-energy, rowan-house", preview:"Visitors from the Other Living World — displaced, confused, and hunted by at least one powerful noble family.", content:"Strangers are people from the Other Living World who have arrived in Doskvol through Fractures. Most arrive involuntarily — casualties of an unexpected breach who suddenly find themselves in a dark, ghost-haunted industrial city that runs on a fuel they don't have a name for. They communicate in the local language (somehow — the mechanism is not fully understood) but carry the accent and manner of somewhere else entirely. Newly arrived Strangers temporarily carry residual Fracture energy, making them faintly perceptible to those sensitive to the ghost field — effectively glowing to any Whisper or Attune-capable character. Only a few Strangers are in Doskvol at any given time; they are only just beginning to become aware of each other. A recent Fracture over the port brought a small group; one drowned and their unusual possessions are now circulating as 'mysteries from the deep.' Rowan House (see Rowan House faction) is actively capturing Strangers for unknown purposes. The full picture of why, and what Rowan House intends to do with them, is a campaign-level secret." },
  // --- HERITAGES (Deep Cuts) ---
  { id:"heritage-deathlander-dc", title:"Deathlander", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"37", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"General", tags:"deathlands, survival, undead, barriers, any-region, wilderness", preview:"Your family lived beyond the lightning barriers — in the actual deathlands, where survival is a daily fight against the undead.", content:"Deathlander is a heritage available from any region — it describes characters whose family lived outside the protective lightning barriers that most civilized people depend on to keep the undead at bay. These are people who survived in the actual deathlands: facing ghosts, demons, and the raw ghost field without institutional protection. Deathlander characters carry practical knowledge of the supernatural that academy-trained Whispers often lack — they know how spirits actually behave when there's no one enforcing protocols, and they know what it costs to survive outside the city's protection. Mechanically, this heritage is strongest with Attune, Hunt, and Prowl, reflecting skills honed by real supernatural danger rather than academic study. In play, a Deathlander heritage can be invoked when navigating the deathlands, dealing with uncontrolled spirits, gathering information from isolated communities beyond the barriers, or recognizing dangers that Doskvol-born characters would miss entirely." },
  { id:"heritage-doskvol-church-ecstasy-dc", title:"Church of Ecstasy (Heritage)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"Akoros", tags:"church, ecstasy, clergy, arcane, doskvol, akoros, occult, institutional", preview:"Your family served among the clergy of the Church of Ecstasy — arcane researchers and ritual leaders of Doskvol's dominant religion.", content:"This Doskvol-specific heritage locates your family within the Church of Ecstasy — Doskvol's dominant religious institution, which combines public ritual with genuine arcane and occult research. Growing up in the Church means familiarity with the city's official supernatural infrastructure: the blessings, the rites, the inner politics of an institution that sits at the intersection of faith and power. Some Church families are true believers; others are politically embedded clergy who treat the institution as a ladder. Either way, this heritage provides access to Church networks, ecclesiastical cover stories, and an understanding of the ghost field's theological dimensions that secular characters lack. Mechanically strongest with Attune, Command, and Sway, reflecting the Church's combination of arcane work and public authority. The inner cult (which Lord Strangford and Elder Rowan belong to) goes significantly deeper than public-facing ceremony — a heritage character may have glimpsed that depth without fully understanding it." },
  { id:"heritage-doskvol-academy-dc", title:"Doskvol Academy (Heritage)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"38", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"Akoros", tags:"academy, education, elite, leviathan-hunters, doskvol, whitecrown, academic", preview:"Your family served at Doskvol's prestigious academy — a world of rich captains, scholarly politics, and institutional privilege.", content:"A Doskvol Academy heritage places your family within the institution that trains the city's navigational, scientific, and administrative elite — particularly the captains of the leviathan hunter fleet, who study navigation, arcane theory, and command at the Academy. This heritage implies access to the wealthy and well-connected, familiarity with institutional procedure, and the kind of educational polish that opens doors in Whitecrown and Brightstone. Academy-connected characters know professors, administrators, and fellow alumni who now occupy positions throughout the city's institutions. Mechanically strongest with Command, Finesse, and Study — reflecting the Academy's emphasis on command presence, social grace, and intellectual rigor. The useful counterpoint is that Academy characters may be recognized in ways that a street-raised scoundrel is not, which can be an asset (access) or a liability (being remembered) depending on the score." },
  { id:"heritage-skovlan-blood-cullers-dc", title:"Blood Cullers (Heritage)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"42", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"Skovlan", tags:"skovlan, blood, leviathan, scavenger, dangerous, illegal, lucrative", preview:"Your family made its living trailing Leviathan Hunter ships in secret — scavenging demon blood and bone shards at the site of kills.", content:"The Blood Cullers practiced one of the most dangerous and lucrative professions in the Shattered Isles: secretly trailing Leviathan Hunter ships in small craft to scavenge demonic blood and bone shards at the site of fresh kills. This is massively risky (you're in open deathlands water, next to a wounded leviathan, in a boat the hunters aren't supposed to know about) and extremely illegal (Leviathan Hunter contracts prohibit unauthorized harvesting), but the alchemical and arcane value of the materials makes it extraordinarily profitable — if you survive and escape. Characters from Blood Culler families carry exceptional practical knowledge of leviathan anatomy, deathlands navigation, and the specific properties of demon-derived alchemical materials. Mechanically strongest with Attune, Finesse, and Tinker. In play, this heritage can be invoked when dealing with arcane materials, navigating open-water situations, or negotiating with the kind of people who trade in deeply illegal supernatural commodities." },
  { id:"heritage-tycheros-confessors-dc", title:"Confessors (Heritage)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"45", category:"Player", subcategory:"Heritage", "sub-subcategory":"Tycheros", tags:"tycheros, assassin, secret-order, pacts, demons, oaths, justice", preview:"Your family belonged to the sacred order of Tycherosi assassins — delivering grim justice to those who violate ancient demon-pacts.", content:"The Confessors are a secret order unique to Tycheros: sacred assassins who deliver justice to those who violate the archaic strictures, pacts, and oaths established by the first Tycherosi who lived in fellowship with the eldritch demons that founded the city — and, it is said, still reside there. To be born into a Confessor family is to inherit a tradition of lethal precision, absolute discretion, and a moral framework that most Imperial citizens would find incomprehensible. Confessors do not kill for money; they kill because someone has broken a covenant that the demons themselves care about. Characters from Confessor families carry the training, the network, and the terrifying calm of people who have been taught since childhood that their purpose is sacred execution. Mechanically strongest with Hunt, Prowl, and Skirmish. In Doskvol, a Confessor heritage character is simultaneously connected to Tycherosi underground networks and marked by an aura of quiet, purposeful menace that affects how NPCs respond to them." },
  // --- BACKGROUNDS (Deep Cuts) ---
  { id:"background-gondolier-dc", title:"Gondolier", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"52", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"Trade", tags:"canals, spirits, ancient-order, protection, attune, finesse, hunt, trade", preview:"A member of Doskvol's ancient order of canal boat operators — who also protect passengers from vengeful spirits.", content:"The Gondoliers of Doskvol are far more than simple canal ferrymen. They are an ancient order whose members are initiated into specific knowledge about the canal system's spiritual geography — where ghosts are known to linger, which waters are considered dangerous after dark, and how to navigate around or through supernatural hazards that most citizens don't even know exist. They also provide a quietly understood service: discreet transport for people who don't want Spirit Warden involvement, and protection from the vengeful spirits that haunt the city's waterways. Characters with a Gondolier background have navigational expertise, knowledge of hidden canal passages and underground waterways, spiritual awareness that doesn't require formal arcane training, and relationships with both legitimate citizens and underworld figures who have used their services. Mechanically strongest with Attune, Finesse, and Hunt. In play, this background is a natural source of city-knowledge, supernatural awareness, and the kind of quiet professional reputation that opens doors without advertising." },
  { id:"background-criminologist-dc", title:"Criminologist", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"48", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"Academic", tags:"academic, crime, factions, investigation, study, consort, survey, underworld", preview:"You studied criminal behavior professionally — cataloging underworld factions, interviewing prisoners, and collecting data for legal bodies.", content:"The Criminologist background produces characters who know the underworld from the outside — or rather, from slightly above it. You spent your previous life studying crime and criminal behavior systematically: interviewing prisoners at Ironhook, cataloging underworld faction structures for governmental or academic bodies, collecting data on patterns of criminal activity across districts, and building a theoretical framework for understanding how Doskvol's illegal economy actually functions. The irony of being a scoundrel with this background is considerable and dramatically rich — you know exactly what you've become, and you probably know why it happened. Characters with this background have an exceptional understanding of faction dynamics, criminal psychology, institutional blind spots, and the language of both law enforcement and the criminal underworld. Mechanically strongest with Consort, Study, and Survey. In play, this background is a natural source of faction knowledge, interrogation capability, and the ability to analyze a situation with unusual analytical clarity." },
  { id:"background-bounty-hunter-dc", title:"Bounty Hunter", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"49", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"Law & Military", tags:"law, hunt, track, capture, consort, skirmish, wanted, fugitives", preview:"You tracked down and captured criminals who evaded their sentences — inside the city and beyond the barriers.", content:"Bounty Hunters in Doskvol occupy an uncomfortable middle position: privately contracted, legally sanctioned, and operating in spaces that the City Watch won't or can't reach. Your previous career involved tracking down fugitives who'd skipped sentences, jumped bail, or fled into the deathlands — and bringing them back alive (or in some cases, providing evidence they wouldn't be coming back at all). This background provides exceptional tracking skills, an intimate knowledge of how people hide and where they run, contacts on both sides of the legal line (you dealt with courts and with criminals daily), and the specific psychological understanding of desperate people that makes for good manhunters. Mechanically strongest with Consort, Hunt, and Skirmish. In play, a Bounty Hunter background character is a natural investigator and pursuer — and someone whose past work has left a complicated trail of relationships with people who are now either grateful to be behind bars or very much not." },
  { id:"background-docker-dc", title:"Docker", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"50", category:"Player", subcategory:"Background", "sub-subcategory":"Labor", tags:"labor, docks, stevedore, guild, physical, consort, skirmish, wreck", preview:"A member of Doskvol's powerful guild of stevedores — the backbone of the city's leviathan trade.", content:"Dockers are the stevedores of Doskvol — members of the powerful guild that loads, unloads, and moves cargo through the city's leviathan hunter port. This is physically demanding, dangerous work that takes place in close proximity to leviathan blood, electroplasmic cargo, and the constant threat of arcane contamination from improperly sealed containers. Docker culture is tight-knit, proudly working-class, and deeply suspicious of management and authority. Guild membership means an automatic network of dock-workers throughout the port and Docks district, access to cargo manifests and shipping schedules (through unofficial channels), and knowledge of exactly how goods move in and out of Doskvol without Bluecoat scrutiny. Mechanically strongest with Consort, Skirmish, and Wreck, reflecting the physical demands and confrontational culture of dock work. In play, a Docker background is a source of working-class contacts, logistical knowledge, and a background story that often involves a specific reason why someone with good guild employment turned to the life of a scoundrel instead." },
  // --- RULES / SYSTEM MODULES ---
  { id:"rule-harm-revised-dc", title:"Harm: Invoking & Surviving (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"73", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"harm, invocation, xp, consequences, scar, fatal, survival, deep-cuts-module", preview:"A revised Harm system where conditions are invoked for dramatic effect and xp — not automatic mechanical penalties.", content:"Deep Cuts revises how Harm functions mechanically. Rather than imposing flat penalties, Harm levels represent conditions that the GM invokes when appropriate, choosing one effect: introduce a bad outcome or new problem, reduce an Action and/or Attribute rating for a roll, or reduce position or effect. When the GM invokes your Harm, you mark xp — the game rewards you for your character's suffering being part of the story. You can also remind the GM of your Harm when you think it applies. To 'tough it out' and prevent an invocation you don't want to deal with, spend 1 Stress per level of the Harm — the Harm remains and still needs recovery, but it can't be invoked again for the scene. Surviving fatal Harm: if a mortal wound isn't instantly lethal, someone can stabilize you within a few minutes. The fatal Harm stays on your sheet and must be addressed during a recovery activity. Record a permanent scar (limp, chronic pain, loss of an eye) — you can invoke your scar to create a problem and mark xp, just like Harm. Key system changes: Vigorous becomes 'Like Hardened Steel' (permanently fills one healing clock segment; unarmed body counts as a fine weapon). Tough as Nails gains a second Level 3 Harm slot and can spend 3 Stress to survive a mortal wound." },
  { id:"rule-trauma-revised-dc", title:"Trauma: Revised (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"76", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"trauma, stress, xp, invoke, retire, recovery, deep-cuts-module", preview:"Trauma is no longer an immediate retirement threat — instead, it's a condition you can invoke once per session for xp and dramatic effect.", content:"The Deep Cuts Trauma module makes Trauma significantly less punishing as an immediate consequence while giving it more narrative weight over time. When your Stress fills and you need to mark more, you gain a Trauma condition, mark a Trauma box, then clear all your Stress — same trigger as Core, but the immediate effect is less severe. The key change: each Trauma condition can be invoked once per session by the player (not the GM or other players) to create a problem or complication for their character. When you do this, mark xp. This replaces the end-of-session xp award for Trauma in the Core game — you don't earn xp just for having it, but for actively letting it shape the story. At four Trauma boxes, your character retires — that hasn't changed. But now you can also recover: work with the GM to create a long-term project to remove a condition and clear a Trauma box. Each character's Trauma is personal, and the path to recovery should reflect that. This module makes Trauma feel like a character development track rather than a death spiral." },
  { id:"rule-load-revised-dc", title:"Load: Conspicuous & Discreet (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"77", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"load, items, conspicuous, discreet, encumbered, deep-cuts-module", preview:"Load is now chosen as Conspicuous (6 boxes, heavy items allowed) or Discreet (4 boxes, no heavy items) before the score.", content:"Deep Cuts replaces the Core game's Light/Normal/Heavy load categories with a binary choice: Conspicuous or Discreet. Before the score, when you choose your plan, you also choose your load style. Conspicuous gives you 6 item boxes and allows heavy items (items requiring 2+ boxes), but heavy items must be chosen and marked before the score begins. Discreet gives you 4 item boxes, prohibits heavy items, and requires no pre-selection — you reveal items as you reach for them during the score, keeping full flexibility. If you pick something up during a score, mark a load box. At 5 boxes, you become conspicuous even if you started discreet. At 7 boxes, you become encumbered — you cannot climb, run, or swim until you drop enough to get below 7. Maximum is 9 boxes. System changes: Rigging (crew upgrade) lets you carry 2 free load of a specific item class, including a heavy item while discreet. Mule (special ability) raises Conspicuous max to 8 and Discreet to 6, with encumbrance at 9 and maximum at 10. This system makes the pre-score load decision feel more like a tactical style choice (visible and capable vs. subtle and flexible) rather than a simple volume calculation." },
  { id:"rule-advancement-clocks-dc", title:"Advancement Clocks (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"78", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"advancement, xp, clocks, slower, deep-cuts-module, progression", preview:"XP now fills advancement clocks instead of tracks — slowing overall progression and making each advancement feel earned.", content:"The Advancement Clocks module replaces the standard xp trackers on playbooks with a set of four 6-segment clocks per character, and a separate set for the crew. Whenever you would mark xp, tick an advancement clock instead. To acquire an advancement (a new action dot, special ability, or attribute upgrade), you must fill a required number of clocks — the cost varies by advancement type, with action dots costing clocks equal to the new rating. When you gain the advancement, clear those clocks and begin again. This system slows overall progression compared to the Core game, making each advancement feel more significant. It also changes the texture of play: advancement feels like something that accumulates across multiple sessions rather than within them. Crew advancement works the same way, with the crew's clock used to acquire new upgrades. This module pairs naturally with the Trauma revision, which also ties xp to story moments rather than session completion — together, they make advancement feel more organic and earned." },
  { id:"rule-downtime-crew-phase-dc", title:"Downtime: Crew Phase (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"80", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"downtime, crew, fallout, payoff, heat, faction-status, diceless, deep-cuts-module", preview:"A revised Crew Phase for Downtime — structured around Fallout, Payoff, Entanglements, Development, and Heat & Hold.", content:"Deep Cuts makes Downtime diceless and restructures it into two phases. The Crew Phase comes first. Cohorts each heal one level of Harm. Then: Fallout (the GM assesses faction Status shifts from the score: +1/+2 for helping a faction, -1/-2 for hurting them, -3 for initiating war); Payoff (Coin and Rep distributed); Entanglements (triggered by Heat); Development (crew upgrades, Tier advancement); and Heat & Hold. Heat is assessed by base formula: 0 for smooth low-exposure work, 2 base for a standard criminal operation, +1 per crew Tier, +2 for a high-profile target, +2 for open combat or mayhem, +2 if at war. Heat is then reduced: each faction at Status +2 or better (Tier 3+) reduces Heat by 1; Coin or Rep can each be spent to reduce Heat by 1 further. Tier advancement requires specific numbers of upgrades and Cohorts to unlock. Faction Status can be improved by spending Coin (6 Coin per Tier of the faction, max +2 this way; getting to +3 must be earned through action). Hold on Tier is assessed by turf claims vs. Tier — if turf claims fall below Tier, hold is weak." },
  { id:"rule-downtime-scoundrel-phase-dc", title:"Downtime: Scoundrel Phase (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"85", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"downtime, scoundrel, vice, debt, activities, diceless, acquire, recover, train, work", preview:"The Scoundrel Phase of Downtime — Vice, Debt, and four diceless activities that drive character development and recovery.", content:"The Scoundrel Phase of Deep Cuts Downtime begins with: restoring all Armor and Special Armor, and removing all Level 1 Harm. If you have a safe place to rest, add 1 tick to your healing clock. Then players handle Vice and Activities in any order. Vice: spend 1 Coin to clear all Stress. If Stress was 6+, you overindulge — roll on the overindulgence table: Get Wild (damage property, -1 faction Status), Big Spender (+1 Coin spent), Bragging (+1 Heat), Attract Trouble (entanglement), Tapped (lose your purveyor), or Wasted (uses a downtime activity). Debt: you can go into debt with a provider — note the initial Coin, make a 4-segment clock that ticks each downtime you still owe. Pay half the initial amount to remove a tick; pay the full initial amount to resolve it. Activities (two free; additional cost 1 Coin or 1 Rep each): Acquire (gain temporary items via a 4-segment supply clock; pay 1 Coin per Quality above Tier, +1 for special features); Recover (heal Harm — required if you have Level 3 Harm or survived fatal Harm); Train (mark advancement clock ticks); Work (advance a long-term project). Supply clocks can also represent stockpiles, favors, or dwindling resources." },
  { id:"rule-threat-roll-dc", title:"Threat Roll (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"90", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"threat-roll, action, consequence, deep-cuts-module, risk, outcome, dice", preview:"The Threat Roll replaces the Action Roll — you know the bad consequence before you roll, and the dice determine if you avoid it.", content:"The Threat Roll is the Deep Cuts overhaul of the standard Action Roll. The key conceptual shift: rather than rolling to see if your action succeeds and then figuring out consequences, the GM describes a bad consequence that's about to happen and you roll to see if you can avoid it. Everyone knows the stakes before the dice hit the table. To make a Threat Roll: roll 1d per dot in the Action you're using plus any bonus dice. Take the highest result. 6 = Success: you avoid the threat. 4/5 = Peril: suffer a reduced consequence, or push yourself to avoid it entirely. 1-3 = Threat: you suffer the consequence. If you face multiple threats simultaneously, add 1d per additional threat beyond the first, then assign a die result to each one — you get to choose which threats to avoid and which to suffer based on your roll results. This means facing more threats gives you more dice (and more choices), which creates an interesting dynamic where additional dangers can actually improve your odds on the threats you care most about. Position and effect are assumed to be risky/standard unless the GM specifies otherwise." },
  { id:"rule-threat-roll-positions-dc", title:"Threat Roll: Controlled & Desperate (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"93", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"position, controlled, desperate, threat-roll, deep-cuts-module, special-cases", preview:"How position works in the Threat Roll system — Controlled means no roll needed, Desperate means all-or-nothing.", content:"Position works differently in the Threat Roll system. Controlled position: if there's no impending danger at all, don't call for a Threat Roll — just describe what the character accomplishes. Controlled situations are resolved through narration, not dice. If a player wants to achieve more than the obvious success, they can make a Devil's Bargain to do it. Desperate position: if the character is outnumbered, outclassed, or badly impaired (often due to Harm), the roll becomes all-or-nothing. A 6 is success; a 5 or less means the consequence lands — no middle ground, no reduced consequence on a 4/5. You can still push yourself to reduce a desperate consequence. When you make a desperate Threat Roll, mark xp. The GM calls for desperate rolls to signal that a threat is genuinely beyond the normal danger range. Crucially, fictional positioning and character abilities can mitigate desperate threats — a rifle and time to reload before three enforcers close means it's risky, not desperate. The GM should always ask if a player wants to continue with their current approach or try something different when calling for a desperate roll." },
  { id:"rule-edge-dc", title:"Edge (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"92", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"edge, critical, bonus-die, luck, deep-cuts-module, teamwork", preview:"When you roll more than one 6, you gain an Edge — a spark of luck you can spend for extra effect or carry forward as a bonus die.", content:"Edge is a new mechanical resource introduced in the Threat Roll system. When you roll multiple 6s on a Threat Roll (i.e., a critical success equivalent), you gain an Edge in addition to avoiding all threats. Edge represents the momentum and luck that comes from taking risks and succeeding decisively. You can spend Edge immediately to add greater effect to your current action, or carry it forward as a +1d bonus die on a future roll of your choice. If you're in a position to help a teammate, you can spend your Edge on their roll. Any Edge you haven't spent is lost when Downtime begins — it's a between-session resource, not a long-term bank. Edge creates a satisfying payoff for exceptional rolls beyond just 'you avoid the threat' and encourages a cycle where decisive success generates resources for follow-up actions. It also enables a form of generous assistance between players — spending your Edge on a teammate's roll is a way of translating your good fortune into collaborative benefit." },
  { id:"rule-push-yourself-dc", title:"Push Yourself: Revised (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"92", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"push-yourself, resistance, stress, attribute, deep-cuts-module, consequence-reduction", preview:"Push Yourself and Resistance Rolls are combined — roll your Attribute to reduce a consequence, spending 0–3 Stress based on the result.", content:"In Deep Cuts, Pushing Yourself and the Resistance Roll from the Core game are merged into a single mechanic. When you suffer a consequence — from a Threat Roll or from a Devil's Bargain — you can choose to push yourself to avoid or reduce it. When you push yourself, make a roll using the Attribute that corresponds to the type of consequence you're facing (Insight for confusion/disorientation, Prowess for physical limits/exhaustion, Resolve for temptation/willpower). The result determines your Stress cost: 6 = 0 Stress, 4/5 = 1 Stress, 1-3 (Peril) = 2 Stress, 1-3 (Threat) = 3 Stress. You can ask the GM what the reduced consequence will be before committing to the roll. You can also push yourself to activate certain special abilities (like Not to be Trifled With) or to increase the effect of an action. This revision streamlines the Core game's two separate mechanics (Push Yourself and Resistance Roll) into one coherent system that still provides the same range of outcomes." },
  { id:"rule-effects-consequences-dc", title:"Effects & Consequences: Four Levels (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"96", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"effect, consequence, limited, standard, great, extreme, harm, deep-cuts-module", preview:"Effects and consequences are organized into four unified levels — limited, standard, great, and extreme — applicable to any type of outcome.", content:"Deep Cuts formalizes a four-level system for categorizing both effects and consequences, making the framework explicit and unified across all types of outcomes. Limited effect: minor or partial impact (1-tick on a clock, Level 1 Harm, still searching for you). Standard effect: normal, expected impact (2-tick on a clock, Level 2 Harm, actively pursuing you). Great effect: significant impact (3-tick on a clock, Level 3 Harm, have you cornered). Extreme effect: overwhelming impact (5-tick on a clock, Level 4/Fatal Harm, capturing you). This same framework applies to social, tactical, physical, and narrative consequences — 'the Bluecoats are closing in' can be limited (searching), standard (pursuing), great (cornered), or extreme (captured). Opponents at similar power levels generally threaten each other at standard effect. Greater mismatches push the more dangerous party to great or extreme effect while limiting the weaker party to limited or standard. Crucially, within a scene, players can often negotiate the scale: fighting harder risks great consequences to deal great harm; pulling punches reduces both risk and impact. The GM describes fictional outcomes before assigning mechanical levels, keeping the fiction primary." },
  { id:"rule-devils-bargain-dc", title:"Devil's Bargain: Revised (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"98", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"devil's-bargain, cost, threat, bonus-die, deep-cuts-module, gm-tool", preview:"Devil's Bargains are now usable at any time — not just during rolls — offering Costs or Threats to move the story forward.", content:"The Devil's Bargain in Deep Cuts is significantly expanded from its Core counterpart. In Deep Cuts, the GM (or any player) can offer a Devil's Bargain at any point in play — not just when a roll is happening. Bargains take two forms. Costs: the GM offers the player something they want (information, access, success) in exchange for a concrete price — marking Stress, spending Coin, taking Level 1 Harm, ticking a clock, losing faction Status. Costs are used to skip past complications without a roll, keeping the game moving. Threats: the GM offers the player something they want in exchange for a threat they must face — typically leading to a Threat Roll. Threats are used when engagement and tension are desired. Players can also speak for the Devil, suggesting bargains for each other's characters to raise the stakes and generate bonus dice. A player can also propose a Cost as a Devil's Bargain to quickly resolve something they're not interested in playing out. During a Threat Roll, a player can request a Devil's Bargain (adding an additional threat) to get +1d. The core philosophy: Devil's Bargains are the primary tool for keeping the game dynamic, offering opportunities and complications in a way that gives players meaningful agency over the texture of their session." },
  { id:"rule-gather-info-dc", title:"Gathering Information: Revised (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"100", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"gather-information, deep-cuts-module, devil's-bargain, leads, long-term-project", preview:"Information gathering is woven into normal play rather than a separate mechanic — the GM tells you what's obvious, then offers a Bargain, lead, or project for more.", content:"Deep Cuts eliminates Gather Information as a standalone mechanic and folds it into the standard flow of play. When a player wants their character to know something, the GM tells them what's immediately obvious: what their character knows, intuits, or suspects based on their playbook, background, heritage, and abilities. This baseline information is free and automatic — a seasoned Lurk scoping a building gets an assessment of infiltration points without a roll. If there's more to discover, the GM asks if they want to know more and what they do to find out. Based on their approach, the GM then chooses one: offer a Devil's Bargain with a Cost (pay Coin, Heat, Stress, or tick a clock to simply get the information), offer a Devil's Bargain with a Threat (face a danger to find out — leading to a Threat Roll), give them a Lead (a person/place/thing that can provide the information in a future scene), or ask them to start a Long-Term Project (for complex information that requires Downtime research). The threat of failure (rolling to see if you learn anything at all) is explicitly discouraged except in rare cases — it's almost always better for players to learn things and be able to act on them." },
  { id:"rule-teamwork-dc", title:"Teamwork: Assist, Cover & Coordinate (Deep Cuts)", source:"Deep Cuts", page:"102", category:"Player", subcategory:"Core Mechanics", "sub-subcategory":"", tags:"teamwork, assist, cover, coordinate, group-action, divide-conquer, deep-cuts-module", preview:"Teamwork in Deep Cuts has three modes: Assist (help a teammate), Cover (take their threat), and Coordinate (Group Action or Divide & Conquer).", content:"Deep Cuts restructures Teamwork into three distinct modes. Assist: if you're in position to help a teammate, describe your assistance and choose a benefit — +1d to their roll, improved effect or position, reduced consequence severity, or more details when gathering information. The GM approves the benefit and either says you accomplish it, says what you need to do first, or offers a Devil's Bargain. You can also give a teammate your Edge for +1d. Cover: describe the action you take so your teammate doesn't have to face a particular threat. The GM either lets you accomplish it, tells you what you need to do, or offers a Devil's Bargain. If you're already making a Threat Roll when you cover for someone, covering adds an additional threat to your roll (giving you more dice, but more to assign). Coordinate has two variants: Group Action (each character rolls against the same threat individually, with scale benefits when the whole crew acts together), and Divide & Conquer (different characters tackle different threats simultaneously, playing to their strengths). In coordinated actions, a designated leader can push themselves on behalf of any other character acting with the team. These three modes give teams much more tactical flexibility than the Core game's simple 'one player assists' structure." },
];

